e\u00e7il\n |date=January 2019\n |title=TURKEY\u2019S CLIMATE POLICIES HAVE REACHED A DEADLOCK: IT TAKES COURAGE TO RESOLVE IT\n |url=https://www.hyd.org.tr/attachments/article/511/saha2en.pdf\n |magazine=saha\n |volume=Special Issue 2\n |pages=24\u201330\n |issn=2149-7885}}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=[[European Commission]]\n |title=Turkey 2019 Report\n |date=May 2019\n |url=https://ec.europa.eu/neighbourhood-enlargement/sites/near/files/20190529-turkey-report.pdf\n }}\n*{{cite report\n | author      = Climate Action Tracker\n | year        = 2019\n | title       = Scaling Up Climate Action series: Turkey\n | url         = https://climateactiontracker.org/documents/672/CAT_2019-11-29_ScalingUp_TURKEY_FullReport_ENG.pdf\n | publisher   = Climate Action Tracker\n}}\n*{{cite report\n | author      = \u00c7\u0131nar Engineering Consultancy \n | year        = 2019\n | title       = Af\u015fin C power station environmental impact report\n | lang        = tr\n | url         = http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019#\n | publisher   = [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)]]\n}}\n*{{cite report\n | last1       = Glomazic\n | first1      = Rade\n | last2       = Raptsun\n | first2      = Mykola \n | year        = 2017\n | title       = Review and analysis of the status of the climate related strategies, policies, plans, and legislation (Status Report)\n | url         = http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/LCDTR-Activity-1.1.1.-Status-Report.pdf\n | publisher   = Hulla & Co Human Dynamics KG\n}}\n*{{cite report\n | last1       = Glomazic\n | first1      = Rade\n | last2       = Raptsun\n | first2      = Mykola \n | year        = 2018\n | title       = Identification of the sectoral development policies intended to meet the GHG emissions reduction targets (Demand Status Report)\n | url         = http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/LCDTR-Activity-1.1.2.-Demand-Status-Report.pdf\n | publisher   = Hulla & Co Human Dynamics KG\n}}\n*{{cite report\n | year        = 2019\n | title       = The European environment \u2014 state and outlook 2020\n | url         = https://www.eea.europa.eu/publications/soer-2020\n | publisher   = [[European Environment Agency]] (EEA)\n}}\n*{{Cite report\n | year        = 2019\n | url          = https://newclimate.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/GHG-Mitigation-Scenarios-Dec2019.pdf\n | title        = Greenhouse gas mitigation scenarios for major emitting countries\n | publisher    = New Climate Institute\n}}\n*{{cite journal  \n |journal=[[OECD]]\n |title=OECD Environmental Performance Reviews: Turkey 2019\n |date=February 2019\n |doi=10.1787/9789264309753-en\n |series=OECD Environmental Performance Reviews\n |isbn=9789264309746\n |author1=OECD\n |author1-link=OECD\n }}\n*{{cite report\n |date         = January 2020 \n |title        = E\u00dcA\u015e - A briefing for investors, insurers and banks\n |publisher    = [[Beyond Coal|Europe Beyond Coal]]\n |url          = https://beyond-coal.eu/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/EBC_EUAS_briefing-paper.pdf\n}}\n\n<!-- need to add the rest of these reports - and also the turkish ones to Turkish article -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://unfccc.int/documents/194818 Greenhouse Gas Inventory to 2017 in downloadable spreadsheets]\n* [https://unfccc.int/documents/194819 National Greenhouse Gas Inventory to 2017 Report]\n* [http://di.unfccc.int/flex_annex1 Greenhouse Gas Inventory Data - Flexible Queries Annex I Parties]\n* [https://www4.unfccc.int/sites/NDCStaging/pages/Party.aspx?party=TUR NDC Registry (only a flag so far)]\n* [https://www.electricitymap.org/?page=country&solar=false&remote=true&wind=false&countryCode=TR Live carbon emissions from electricity generation]\n* [https://www.climatewatchdata.org/countries/TUR Climate Watch: Turkey]\n* [https://carbon-turkey.org/en Capacity Development for the Implementation of a Monitoring, Reporting and Verification (MRV) System for Greenhouse Gas Emissions]\n* [http://turkishcarbonmarket.com/carbon-markets Carbon Market]\n* [http://www.skdturkiye.org/en/dusuk-karbon-ekonomisine-gecis-ve-verimlilik Business Council for Sustainable Development Turkey:Transition to Low Carbon Economy and Efficiency]\n\n{{Asia topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n{{Europe topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Climate change in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|gases from the Eurasian country which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|the effects of global warming and adaptation to it|Climate change in Turkey}}\n{{short description|Climate-changing gases from the Eurasian country}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey''' are the [[Greenhouse gas inventory|contributions]] within [[Turkey]] to the emission of [[greenhouse gasses]] such as [[carbon dioxide]] or [[ hydrofluorocarbons]]. Turkey's human contributions to emissions can be segmented by sector, such as looking specifically at [[List of power stations in Turkey|Turkey's power stations]] or transport. In addition, the natural and [[Agriculture in Turkey|agricultural landscape of Turkey]] contribute to its national greenhouse gas emissions, with methane and [[N2O|N<sub>2</sub>O]] from agriculture more than offset by carbon dioxide trapped in forests, thus slightly reducing Turkey's overall emissions. [[Energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's policies on energy]], industry, and its explicit policies on climate change affect its level of emissions, and these policies are shaped by the relationship between emissions and economic activity. Finally, media, academic, and individual figures have provided commentary on Turkey's policies and levels of emissions. \n\nCoal, cars and cows vent half the greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey, but a fifth is absorbed by trees. Turks emits about 1% of the world's total greenhouse gases,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/ekonomi/turkiyede-sera-gazi-emisyonu-azaldi/1786460|title=T\u00fcrkiye'de sera gaz\u0131 emisyonu azald\u0131|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> averaging over six tonnes each,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/environment/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-fall-for-second-year-in-a-row|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions fall for second year in a row|date=2020-03-31|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> somewhat worse than the [[List of countries by greenhouse gas emissions per capita|global average per person]] of five tonnes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wri.org/blog/2019/12/co2-emissions-climb-all-time-high-again-2019-6-takeaways-latest-climate-data|title=CO2 Emissions Climb to an All-Time High (Again) in 2019: 6 Takeaways from the Latest Climate Data|date=2019-12-03|website=World Resources Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. Burning fossil fuels for electricity, heat and [[transport in Turkey]], emitted over 70% of greenhouse gasses in 2018 and industry and agriculture emitted over 10% each;<ref name=\":3\" /> whereas forests and reforestation together absorbed about 20%.  Coal, which is used to generate electricity for heating and by industry, accounts for most of Turkey's fossil fuel {{nowrap|{{chem2|CO2}}}} emissions; followed by natural gas, which is also used for heating and electricity generation; and [[petroleum products]] used for transport. \n\n[[File:Ghg pie chart Turkey.svg|Sources of 2017 greenhouse gas emissions|thumb|upright=1.4]]\n\nAlthough [[climate change in Turkey]] is forecast to have severe impacts,<ref name=\"3rd BR\">{{cite book |title=Turkey's Seventh National Communication and Third Biennial Report to United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change |publisher=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Environment and Urbanization |url=http://unfccc.int/files/national_reports/biennial_reports_and_iar/submitted_biennial_reports/application/pdf/1428795_turkey-br3-1-tur.br3.english.pdf |page=4}}</ref> the country's plans to limit emissions have been described as \"critically insufficient by the [[think tank]] Climate Action Tracker.<ref name=\"CAT\">{{cite web|url=https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/|title=Turkey|publisher=Climate Action Tracker|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614203500/https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/|archive-date=14 June 2018|accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref> Turkey has signed but not ratified global agreements on reducing greenhouse gas emissions: the country has not yet ratified the [[Kigali accord]] to regulate hydrofluorocarbons, and is one of the few [[List of parties to the Paris Agreement#Signatories|countries that have not ratified the Paris agreement on climate change]]. One of the main reason for Turkey's high rate of emissions is that [[List of coal fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] are subsidized. Emissions grew quickly during the late 20th and early 21st centuries but in the 2010s and 2020s invested in energy efficiency and [[renewable energy in Turkey|renewable energy]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/04/12/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-hit-over-526-million-tons|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions hit over 526 million tons|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref> and is likely to meet the \u201cunambitious\u201d [[Intended Nationally Determined Contribution]] (INDC) it has submitted to the [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC).<ref name=\"Climate Transparency 2018\">{{cite web |title=BROWN TO GREEN: THE G20 TRANSITION TO A LOW-CARBON ECONOMY |date=2018 |url=https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/BROWN-TO-GREEN_2018_Turkey_FINAL.pdf |publisher=Climate Transparency |accessdate=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302090520/https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/BROWN-TO-GREEN_2018_Turkey_FINAL.pdf |archive-date=2 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==2030 target==\nTurkey submitted its [[Intended Nationally Determined Contributions]] goals to the [[UNFCCC]] in 2015. This 2030 target would result in an overall increase in emissions compared to the 2010s.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=7}}{{sfnp|New Climate Institute|2019|p=109}} On a per-capita basis, this target would also mean an emissions rate of 10 tonnes per person in 2030. However, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, an increase to 8 tonnes per capita by 2030 is considered more likely.{{sfnp|New Climate Institute|2019|p=111}} However, if suitable policies were implemented for electricity supply, land transport and residential buildings a decrease would be possible.<ref name=\"Climate Action Tracker 2019 p. 63\">Climate Action Tracker (2019), p. 63</ref> The [[OECD]] says Turkey needs to integrate climate and energy objectives, and that its National Climate Change Strategy and Action Plan should break down emissions reduction goals by sector, and include regular monitoring and evaluation.<ref name=\"OECD 2019, executive summary\"/>\n\nIn 2019, the [[OECD]] recommended that [[climate change mitigation]] efforts be increased<ref name=\"OECD 2019, page 38\">OECD (2019), page 38</ref> as the national strategy and action plan only partly covers mitigation and only for the short-term.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\" /> Turkey's [[Intended Nationally Determined Contributions]] (INDC), submitted in 2015, are up to 21 percent reduction in GHG emissions from the Business as Usual (BAU) level by 2030.<ref name=\"INDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www4.unfccc.int/submissions/INDC/Published%20Documents/Turkey/1/The_INDC_of_TURKEY_v.15.19.30.pdf|title=REPUBLIC OF TURKEY INTENDED NATIONALLY DETERMINED CONTRIBUTION|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920155826/http://www4.unfccc.int/submissions/INDC/Published%20Documents/Turkey/1/The_INDC_of_TURKEY_v.15.19.30.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> However that would result in a large rise in emissions,<ref>[https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/22070/EGR_2017.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y \"The Emissions Gap Report 2017 page 9\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129125722/https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/22070/EGR_2017.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|date=29 January 2019}} United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)</ref> and has been described as \"critically insufficient.\"<ref name=\"CAT\" /> Turkey's GHG per person is slightly below the EU average but GHG per unit GDP a little above.<ref>EEA (2019), p. 161</ref> In southern Europe solar power can compete without subsidies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evwind.es/2019/09/21/wind-power-and-solar-energy-already-compete-without-subsidies/70999|title=Wind power and solar energy already compete without subsidies {{!}} REVE News of the wind sector in Spain and in the world|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and neighbouring [[Greece]] plans to close all its coal-fired power stations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkangreenenergynews.com/greece-seeks-to-phase-out-coal-by-2028-ptolemaida-v-prospects-unclear/|title=Greece seeks to phase out coal by 2028, Ptolemaida V prospects unclear|date=2019-09-25|website=Balkan Green Energy News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> by 2028, starting in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/environment/un-chief-urges-leaders-to-avoid-new-coal-after-2020/1592627|title=UN chief urges leaders to avoid 'new coal' after 2020|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref> [[Portugal]], which has regions with similar solar potential, aims to be [[carbon neutral]] by 2050.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portuguese Government Launches Climate Plan With Ambitious Carbon-Neutral Target |url=https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/portugal/portuguese-government-launches-climate-plan-with-ambitious-carbon-neutral-target/ |work=South EU Summit |date=24 December 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013405/https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/portugal/portuguese-government-launches-climate-plan-with-ambitious-carbon-neutral-target/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Greenhouse gas sources==\n[[File:Ghg bar chart Turkey.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Greenhouse gas emissions and absorption in Turkey in 2017{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=iv}}]]\n\n526 Mt of {{CO2}} was emitted in 2017,<ref name=\"TurkStat\">{{cite web |title=Greenhouse Gas Emissions Statistics, 1990-2017 |url=http://www.turkstat.gov.tr/PreHaberBultenleri.do?id=30627 |publisher=Turkish Statistical Institute |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> mostly by fossil fuels, but around 100 Mt was reabsorbed by [[land use, land-use change, and forestry]] (LULUCF),<ref name=\"GHGsummary\">{{cite web |title=Summary of GHG Emissions for Turkey |url=http://di.unfccc.int/ghg_profiles/annexOne/TUR/TUR_ghg_profile.pdf |publisher=[[UNFCCC]] |accessdate=8 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108184410/http://di.unfccc.int/ghg_profiles/annexOne/TUR/TUR_ghg_profile.pdf |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|1=vertical bars show uncertainty, which for 2017 without LULUCF was 5.3%, but as LULUCF uncertainty as shown was very large with LULUCF was 13.8%{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=22}} }} mostly by forests. The amount removed by forests is very uncertain (as shown by the vertical bar on the chart above it could be anything from 50 Mt to 150 Mt) but is expected to be clarified in 2020.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=489}}\n\n[[File:CO2 by fossil fuel Turkey.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|CO<sub>2</sub> emitted by fossil fuels burnt in Turkey in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org//statistics/|title=Statistics|website=www.iea.org|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>]]\nIn 2017 [[coal in Turkey]] emitted the most, followed by oil then natural gas.\n\nWith a population of 80 million Turkey's emissions are above the world average, which is 5 tonnes per person per year. The government agency [[Turkish Statistical Institute]] (Turkstat) follows [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) guidelines and uses [[Greenhouse gas emissions accounting#Production-based accounting|production based greenhouse gas emissions accounting]] to compile Turkey's [[emission inventory]]. Being listed as a developed country (Annex 1), Turkey must submit its inventory of 2018 emissions to the UNFCCC by 15 April 2020, and so on for each calendar year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/process-and-meetings/transparency-and-reporting/reporting-and-review-under-the-convention/greenhouse-gas-inventories-annex-i-parties/reporting-requirements|title=Reporting requirements {{!}} UNFCCC|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> The UNFCCC reviews countries' inventories and makes recommendations for improvement: many recommendations to Turkey have been resolved or will be resolved by the next inventory, but many have been outstanding for over 3 years.{{sfnp|Inventory review|2019|p=21}} The UNFCCC has asked for much more detail to be provided, so that emissions projections provided by Turkey for various government policies and [[Shared Socioeconomic Pathways]] can be understood, for example details of the [[Integrated assessment modelling|integrated assessment model]] developed by [[I\u015f\u0131k University]] and [[Bosphorus University]].{{sfnp|Tech review 3rd report|2019|p=15}}{{efn|1=As \"national communications\" are required every 4 years the 5th biennial report and 8th national communication may be combined as the same document, as was the case previously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/process/transparency-and-reporting/reporting-and-review-under-the-convention/support-for-developing-countries/modalities--procedures-and-guidelines#eq-2|title=Preparation of NCs and BRs {{!}} UNFCCC|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>}}  These are used for non-energy emissions.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=33}}\n\n===Burning fossil fuels for heat and power===\n{{See also|Energy policy of Turkey}}\nIn 2018 Turkey's energy sector, which under IPCC guidelines includes fuel for transport, emitted almost three quarters of the country's greenhouse gases, whereas [[Industrial Processes]] and Product Use (IPPU) and agriculture each emitted an eighth.<ref name=\":3\" /> The largest emitters are energy industries\u2014mainly electricity generation\u2014followed by transport.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=43}} [[Carbon capture and storage]] barely exists in Turkey's energy sector; it is not economically viable as Turkey has no [[carbon emission trading]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Esmaeili |first1=Danial |date=June 2018 |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |publisher=[[Sabanc\u0131 University]] |url=http://research.sabanciuniv.edu/36807/1/1806_IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |access-date=14 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514155754/http://research.sabanciuniv.edu/36807/1/1806_IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=14 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Energy emissions are modelled by [[Energy modeling#MARKAL/TIMES|TIMES]].{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=33}}\n\n====Power stations====\n[[List of power stations in Turkey|Power stations in Turkey]] emitted 145 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017,{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1s1 cell B10}} mostly from burning coal. Turkey's emissions from electricity generation could rise to 200 Mt by 2021.<ref>{{cite journal |last=\u015eahin |first=Utkucan |title=Forecasting of Turkey's electricity generation and CO2 emissions in estimating capacity factor |journal=American Institute of Chemical Engineers Environ Prog. |volume=38 |pages=56\u201365 |date=2 November 2018 |doi=10.1002/ep.13076 }}</ref> {{efn|In 2017, the carbon content([[tonne|t]]/[[Terajoule|TJ]]), oxidation factor and CO<sub>2</sub> emission intensity (t/TJ [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|NCV]]) of the main fossil fuels burnt in Turkish power stations were:{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|pp=50 & 51, table 3.5, 3.6, 3.7}}\n\n[[Lignite]]  30,  0.973,  107\n[[Bituminous coal|Hardcoal]]    26,  0.975,  95\n[[Natural gas]]  15,  1,  56\n\nThe CO<sub>2</sub> emission intensity (or emission factor) shown above is the mass of CO<sub>2</sub> emitted for each unit of ''heat'' produced by burning a fuel. In contrast the ''grid'' [[emission intensity]] is the mass of CO<sub>2eq</sub> produced per unit of ''electricity'' supplied to the [[electrical grid]]. Because [[thermal power station]]s generally convert less than half of the heat energy into electrical energy, their numbers for grid emission intensity are much greater than those shown above.\n}}\n\nAlmost all coal burnt in power stations is either local [[lignite]] or imported hardcoal. [[Coal assay|Coal analysis]] of Turkish lignite compared to other lignites shows it to have a lot of ash and moisture, a low [[energy value of coal]] and high emission intensity: in other words Turkish lignite emits more CO<sub>2</sub> than typical lignites per unit energy produced when burnt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powerengineeringint.com/articles/print/volume-25/issue-11/features/cfb-in-turkey-the-right-timing-for-the-right-technology.html|title=CFB in Turkey: The right timing for the right technology|website=www.powerengineeringint.com|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> However although imported hardcoal has a slightly lower emission intensity when burnt, the lifecycle greenhouse gas emissions take account of transportation so are similar.<ref name=\"Atilgan et al 2016, p. 177\">Atilgan et al (2016), p. 177</ref>\n\nDespite considerable potential for expansion of [[renewable energy in Turkey]], which except for geothermal emits little CO<sub>2eq</sub>, Turkey averages a grid emission intensity over 460 gCO<sub>2eq</sub>/kWh (over 125 t/TJ),<ref name=AVTrans2018>{{cite web|title=Towards Decarbonising Transport|url=https://www.agora-verkehrswende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2017/Verkehr_und_Klima_in_den_G20_Laendern/15_G20_WEB.pdf|publisher=Agora Verkehrswende|access-date=6 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107015851/https://www.agora-verkehrswende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2017/Verkehr_und_Klima_in_den_G20_Laendern/15_G20_WEB.pdf|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> similar to that of natural gas. Both grid intensity and carbon emissions per person are worse than the global average.<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy Revolution: A Global Outlook |url=https://www.drax.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Energy-Revolution-Global-Outlook-Report-Final-Dec-2018-COP24.pdf |publisher=Drax |accessdate=7 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209123738/https://www.drax.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Energy-Revolution-Global-Outlook-Report-Final-Dec-2018-COP24.pdf |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=====Coal fired power stations=====\n[[File:Yenik\u00f6y Power Plant Milas Mu\u011fla Turkey.jpg|thumb|[[Yenik\u00f6y power station]] and two others pollute [[Mu\u011fla]]<ref>{{cite web |title=THE REAL COSTS OF COAL: MU\u011eLA |url=http://www.caneurope.org/docman/coal-phase-out/3552-the-real-costs-of-coal-mugla/file |website=CAN Europe}}</ref>]]\n[[List of coal fired power stations in Turkey|Coal fired power stations in Turkey]] emitted 98 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017:{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1.A(a)s1 cell G26 \"solid fuels\"}} and, if operated at the targeted [[capacity factor]], planned new [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan power stations|units at Af\u015fin Elbistan]] would add over 61 Mt each year, according to the [http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019# Af\u015fin-Elbistan C environmental impact report].<ref>\u00c7\u0131nar (2019), p. 280</ref>{{efn|1=Somewhat over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> is emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations. According to page xix of [http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019# the Af\u015fin-Elbistan C environmental impact report] it is aimed to generate just over 12.5 TWh (gross) per year, so why the CO2 emissions are predicted to be so high is unclear. According to the calculation at the end of page 280 of the September 2019 version of the EIA 6.16X10<sup>10</sup> tCO2/year would be emitted, but that is a unit error as according to the inputs it would be 6.16X10<sup>7</sup> tCO2/year which is the figure quoted above.}}\n\n[[Coal in Turkey]] is the largest source of the nation's greenhouse gases. Over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> is emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations.<ref name=\"Atilgan et al 2016, p. 177\"/> Once emissions from coal burnt for industry and heating buildings, and [[methane emissions]] from [[coal mining]] are added to those from the almost 100 TWh coal-fired electricity generated annually,<ref name=\"MinCoal\">{{cite web |title=Coal |url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal |publisher=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917110843/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> about one third of Turkey's emissions come from coal.<ref>\u015eahin (2016), p. 7</ref> In 2017 coal combustion emitted over 150 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/statistics/?country=TUR&isISO=true|title=Statistics for Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> {{As of|2016}}, however, methane emissions from coal mining was the largest uncertainty in Turkey's total gross emissions.<ref name=\"Urbanization 2016 p. 95\">Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), p. 95</ref> Eren Holding, via Eren Enerji's coal-fired [[ZETES power stations]], emits over 2% of Turkey's greenhouse gases; and \u0130\u00c7DA\u015e emits over 1% via its Bekirli coal-fired power stations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global coal power map|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/mapped-worlds-coal-power-plants|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228173255/https://www.carbonbrief.org/mapped-worlds-coal-power-plants|archive-date=28 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Energy Minister]] Fatih D\u00f6nmez favors coal<ref>{{cite news |title=New Turkish energy minister bullish for coal -- but lira weakness limits market |url=https://www.platts.kr/latest-news/coal/london/analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-26988555 |publisher=Platts |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917105121/https://www.platts.kr/latest-news/coal/london/analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-26988555 |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Environment Minister]] Murat Kurum is making plans for adaptation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-must-move-towards-clean-energy-expert/1534088|title=Turkey must move towards clean energy: Expert|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> The 2 proposed coal power plants are mainly financed by governments, the Chinese funded [[Emba Hunutlu power station]] and  [[Turkey Wealth Fund]] backed [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station|Af\u015fin-Elbistan C]], and may or may not actually complete construction,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/20/10484952/see-turkey-braced-for-falling-demand-bankruptcies-amid-emergency-measures-fallout|title=SEE, Turkey braced for falling demand, bankruptcies amid emergency measures fallout|last=Sabadus|first=Aura|website=Icis|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> despite government guarantee to purchase electricity from lignite-fired power stations until 2024 at an inflation-linked price.<ref>{{cite web |title=2017/11070 |url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2017/12/20171202-9.pdf |publisher=Resmi Gazete |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215140139/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2017/12/20171202-9.pdf |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TETA\u015e's Purchase of Electricity from Domestic Coal Fired Power Plants |url=http://www.cakmak.av.tr/articles/Power/113951311_2.pdf |publisher=\u00c7akmak Avukatl\u0131k Ortakl\u0131\u011f\u0131 |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917181641/http://www.cakmak.av.tr/articles/Power/113951311_2.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkey's climate change policy includes an increase in the economic life of coal reserves.<ref>{{cite book |title=REPUBLIC OF TURKEY CLIMATE CHANGE ACTION PLAN 2011 - 2023 |date=2012 |publisher=Ministry of Environment and Urbanization General Directorate of Environmental Management Climate Change Department |page=28 |url=http://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/iklim/editordosya/file/eylem%20planlari/iklim_degisikligi_eylem_plani_EN_2014.pdf |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917105525/http://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/iklim/editordosya/file/eylem%20planlari/iklim_degisikligi_eylem_plani_EN_2014.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}} the government aims to keep the share of coal in the energy portfolio at around the same level in the medium to long term.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}}\n\n=====Gas fired power stations=====\n[[File:Ta\u015fk\u0131s\u0131\u011f\u0131 K\u00f6y\u00fc.JPG|thumb|Ta\u015fk\u0131s\u0131\u011f\u0131 K\u00f6y\u00fc gas-fired power station: natural gas is cleaner than coal but costs money to import and also emits greenhouse gases]]\n\n[[List of power stations in Turkey#Natural Gas|Gas fired power stations in Turkey]] emitted 45 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1.A(a)s1 cell G27}} {{As of|2019}}, however, some power utilities, including at least three gas-fired plants, were struggling to repay their foreign currency debts after the depreciation of the [[Turkish lira|lira]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-05/turkey-working-on-plan-to-clear-some-bad-energy-loans-from-banks|title=Turkey Wants Banks to Write Off $1.9 Billion to Boost Credit|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Subsidies are being reduced in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Outlook 2019: Turkish natural gas market set for potential 'de-liberalization' in 2019 |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/natural-gas/122718-outlook-2019-turkish-natural-gas-market-set-for-potential-de-liberalization-in-2019 |work=Platts |publisher=S & P Global |date=27 December 2018 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219130303/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/natural-gas/122718-outlook-2019-turkish-natural-gas-market-set-for-potential-de-liberalization-in-2019 |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Transport fuel====\n[[File:Traffic jam in Istanbul's road.JPG|thumb|[[Istanbul]] is one of the few major European cities without a low-emission zone]]\n\n[[Transport in Turkey]] is road-dominated<ref name=\"OECD 2019, section 1\">OECD (2019), section 1.</ref> and emitted 85 Mt of CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017, 16% of the nation's total. 79 Mt came from roads followed by 4 Mt from domestic aviation.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=118}} Emissions from air transport were expected to grow rapidly following the opening of the large [[Istanbul Airport]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change is no joke |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/alkin-kerem/2018/10/20/climate-change-is-no-joke |work=Daily Sabah |date=19 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024192148/https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/alkin-kerem/2018/10/20/climate-change-is-no-joke |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Although Turkey has joined the [[Carbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International Aviation]], emissions from domestic aviation are not taxed. International journeys are not included in a country's emissions total but the UNFCCC has asked for fuel sales for international aviation and shipping to be reported, separately.{{sfnp|Tech review 3rd report|2019|p=15}}\n\nMore than three quarters of Turkey's road transport emissions come from diesel.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=133}} Although gasoline and diesel (except possibly agricultural diesel) prices are above the [[G20]] average and electricity is subsidized, the country has a tiny proportion of [[charging station]]s and [[electric car]]s.<ref name=AVTrans2018/> {{As of|2020||df=}}, there were no [[low-emission zone]]s in any Turkish cities, although enabling regulations were introduced in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Low-emission zones for Turkish cities in the works |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/05/03/low-emission-zones-for-turkish-cities-in-the-works |work=Daily Sabah |date=3 May 2019 |access-date=3 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503151329/https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/05/03/low-emission-zones-for-turkish-cities-in-the-works |archive-date=3 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rate of the special consumption tax\u2014a sales tax on luxuries such as private cars\u2014and the annual motor-vehicle tax is lower for electric cars than for fossil fuel cars, but batteries are taxed by weight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meclis'ten Elektrikli Otomobile bir darbe daha geldi! |url=http://tehad.org/2018/12/31/meclisten-elektrikli-otomobile-bir-darbe-daha-geldi/ |work=T\u00fcrkiye Elektrikli ve Hibrid Ara\u00e7lar Platformu (TEHAD) |date=31 December 2018 |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107072153/http://tehad.org/2018/12/31/meclisten-elektrikli-otomobile-bir-darbe-daha-geldi/ |archive-date=7 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Electric buses<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/2019/10/21/local-bus-manufacturers-take-stage-at-busworld-europe-fair|title=Local bus manufacturers take stage at Busworld Europe fair|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> and hybrid cars are manufactured locally, but none of Turkey's car factories yet produce purely electric cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey determined to boost hybrid, electric car sales |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/turkey-determined-to-boost-hybrid-electric-car-sales-3473176 |work=Yeni \u015eafak |date=29 January 2019 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129114408/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/turkey-determined-to-boost-hybrid-electric-car-sales-3473176 |archive-date=29 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, 0.1% of cars sold were hybrid or electric.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/02/02/number-of-electric-hybrid-cars-in-turkey-triples-in-2019|title=Number of electric, hybrid cars in Turkey triples in 2019|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Increasing Turkey's proportion of electric cars in use to 10% by 2030 would have many benefits.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Transport-sector-transformation.Integrating-electric-vehicles-into-Turkey%E2%80%99s-distribution-grids.pdf|title=Transport sector transformation: Integrating electric vehicles into Turkey\u2019s distribution grids|url-status=live}}</ref> Very few foreign-made electric cars are sold;<ref>{{cite web |title=T\u00fcrkiye Elektrikli ve Hibrid Otomobil Pazar\u0131 / Marka ve Modeller |url=http://tehad.org/2019/01/17/turkiye-elektrikli-ve-hibrid-otomobil-pazari-marka-ve-modeller/ |accessdate=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219130331/http://tehad.org/2019/01/17/turkiye-elektrikli-ve-hibrid-otomobil-pazari-marka-ve-modeller/ |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> those from American manufacturers, such as [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], are unavailable due to a 120% tariff.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla reportedly pulls out of Turkish expansion plan due to new Trump trade war tariffs |url=https://electrek.co/2018/10/31/tesla-turkey-expansion-trump-trade-war-tariffs/ |work=Electrek |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220002727/https://electrek.co/2018/10/31/tesla-turkey-expansion-trump-trade-war-tariffs/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, Turkey lacks any measures to reduce the [[Life-cycle assessment#Well-to-wheel|well to wheel]] impact of petrol and diesel vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Fuel Quality Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-1-FQD-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430091730/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-1-FQD-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live |page=15 }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, fuel quality and emissions standards for new cars do not meet [[European Union]] (EU) standards.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\">European Commission (2019), page 94</ref> [[Turkish Airlines]] did not respond to the 2018 [[Carbon Disclosure Project]] questionnaire<ref>{{cite web |title=CDP Turkey Climate Change and Water Report 2018 |url=https://cdpturkey.sabanciuniv.edu/en/content/cdp-turkey-climate-change-and-water-report-2018 |publisher=[[Carbon Disclosure Project]] |access-date=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417090544/https://cdpturkey.sabanciuniv.edu/en/content/cdp-turkey-climate-change-and-water-report-2018 |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in 2019, the airline was named as one of those with the weakest plans to cut emissions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leading airlines failing to plan for long haul on climate, warns influential investor initiative |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/tpi/leading-airlines-failing-to-plan-for-long-haul-on-climate-warns-influential-investor-initiative/ |publisher=London School of Economics\u2019 Grantham Research Institute |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523022530/http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/tpi/leading-airlines-failing-to-plan-for-long-haul-on-climate-warns-influential-investor-initiative/ |archive-date=23 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Burning fuel to heat buildings and cook====\n[[File:Air Pollution in Ankara.jpg|thumb|Pollution over [[Ankara]]: coal is still burnt to heat older buildings in cities]]\n\nResidential fuel such as natural gas, coal and wood contributed 43 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=150}} {{As of|2017}} the end-user price of natural gas is subsidized.<ref name=\":1\" /> Subsidies for poor families to use coal for heating produce [[black carbon]], a contributor to climate change,<ref name=\"OECD 2019, section 1\"/> and other [[air pollution in Turkey|local air pollution]].\n\nBurning fuel, such as coal and natural gas, for commercial and industrial buildings emitted 21 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=148}}\n\n===Industry===\nIn 2018, [[Economy of Turkey#Industrial sector|Turkey's industrial sector]] emitted an eighth of its greenhouse gases.<ref name=\":3\" /> Iron, steel and cement manufacturing account for 40% of [[primary energy]] consumed by industry; those industries are making efforts to become more environmentally friendly.<ref>Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), pages 45,115</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MRV IN TURKEY: FROM THEORY TO PRACTICE CEMENT SECTOR EXPERIENCE |url=http://www.tcma.org.tr/images/file/COP%2023%20sunum.pdf |publisher=Turkish Cement Manufacturers\u2019 Association |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917181649/http://www.tcma.org.tr/images/file/COP%2023%20sunum.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, estimates of the effects of government policy on the sector's emissions are lacking.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=28}} Some business people are concerned that in future the [[European Green Deal]] might include a carbon border tax which Turkey would be outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eureporter.co/frontpage/2020/01/13/europeangreendeal-could-re-energize-eu-relations-with-turkey/|title=#EuropeanGreenDeal could re-energize EU relations with #Turkey|date=2020-01-13|website=EU Reporter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In 2017, [[Economy of Turkey#Steel-Iron industry|Turkey's iron and steel production]] emitted 21 Mt of CO<sub>2eq</sub>.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=229}} The European steel-making industry has complained that imports from Turkey are unfair competition because they are not subject to a carbon tax.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/turkeys-steel-imports-into-europe-a-problem-for-the-industry-says-liberty-house-boss-11814316|title=Turkey's steel imports into Europe a 'problem' for the industry, says Liberty House boss|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\n====Cement====\n[[File:Ata\u015fehir'de y\u00fckselen yeni binalar.2.jpg|thumb|The [[Turkish construction and contracting industry]] was very active until 2018]]\nTurkey is the 4th largest [[cement]] producer in the world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/2019/07/05/turkish-cement-sector-exports-surge-46-percent-in-first-half|title=Turkish cement sector exports surge 46 percent in first half|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and in 2017 cement production emitted 7% of the countries total GHG.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=23}} However, Turkey's construction sector contracted considerably at the end of 2018<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's economy tips into recession as lira crisis bites |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-economy-gdp/turkeys-economy-tips-into-recession-as-lira-crisis-bites-idUSKBN1QS0MT |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=11 March 2019 |access-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321155249/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-economy-gdp/turkeys-economy-tips-into-recession-as-lira-crisis-bites-idUSKBN1QS0MT |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> thus using less cement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://think.ing.com/snaps/turkey-a-small-correction-in-january-ip/|title=Turkish industrial production grows 7.9%|last=Mercan|first=Muhammet|date=|website=ING Think|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05|quote=cement production ....... shows the extent of activity in construction}}</ref> More [[cross-laminated timber]] could be used for building, instead of concrete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegef.org/sites/default/files/web-documents/10090_PIFReviewSheet.pdf|title=Promoting Low Cost Energy Efficient Wooden Buildings in Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Environment Facility|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe biggest reduction in emissions from cement production could be made by reducing its [[Clinker (cement)|clinker]] content<ref name=IEAcement2018>{{cite book |title=Technology Roadmap: Low-Carbon Transition in the Cement Industry |date=2018 |url=https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/TechnologyRoadmapLowCarbonTransitionintheCementIndustry.pdf |access-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321070300/https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/TechnologyRoadmapLowCarbonTransitionintheCementIndustry.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> from the current 87%, for example by making [[Limestone Calcined Clay Cement|LC<sup>3</sup> cement]], which is only half clinker; the second-biggest reduction could be made by switching half of the fuel from [[hard coal]] and [[petcoke]] to a mixture of rubber from waste tires, [[refuse-derived fuel]] and [[biomass]].<ref name=\"Cementis2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cementis.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Turkey-GHG-from-Cement.pdf|title=Abstract on the potential GHG emissions reduction in Turkey through the cement industry|publisher=Cementis GmbH|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321063407/http://www.cementis.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Turkey-GHG-from-Cement.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2019|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref> The country has plenty of these materials and some cement plants already use them.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=99}}\n\nFurther decarbonization of cement production would depend heavily on [[carbon capture and storage]] (CCS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Decarbonization of industrial sectors: the next frontier |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/~/media/McKinsey/Business%20Functions/Sustainability%20and%20Resource%20Productivity/Our%20Insights/How%20industry%20can%20move%20toward%20a%20low%20carbon%20future/Decarbonization-of-industrial-sectors-The-next-frontier.ashx |publisher=[[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728015756/https://www.mckinsey.com/~/media/mckinsey/business%20functions/sustainability%20and%20resource%20productivity/our%20insights/how%20industry%20can%20move%20toward%20a%20low%20carbon%20future/decarbonization-of-industrial-sectors-the-next-frontier.ashx |archive-date=28 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite the earthquake risk from the [[geology of Turkey]], CCS may be technically feasible in a [[salt dome]] near [[Lake Tuz]]<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Carbon Capture and Storage Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-2-CCS-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430111238/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-2-CCS-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> or in [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbak\u0131r]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=FIRTINA ERT\u0130\u015e|first=\u0130rem|date=|title=APPLICATION OF MULTI-CRITERIA DECISION MAKING FOR GEOLOGICAL CARBON DIOXIDE STORAGE AREA IN TURKEY|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/download/article-file/491521|journal=Anadolu University Journal of Science and Technology A- Applied Sciences and Engineering|volume=|pages=|via=|access-date=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430074142/https://dergipark.org.tr/download/article-file/491521|archive-date=30 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However CCS is not currently financially viable because, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, the country has no carbon price.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\"/>\n\n===Agriculture and waste===\n[[File:Jersey cattle in Sisda\u011f\u0131 04.jpg|thumb|Reducing beef and dairy consumption would also reduce imports<ref>{{cite report|title=Turkey Livestock Annual Report 2018|date=2018-08-31|series=GQIN Report|id=TR8027|publisher=[[USDA]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920171601/https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_9-7-2018.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=live|url=https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_9-7-2018.pdf|access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2018, agriculture emitted an eighth of Turkey's greenhouse gases,<ref name=\":3\" /> mainly due to [[enteric fermentation]], agricultural soils, and fertilizer management.<ref>{{cite web |title=Strategies Regarding Mitigation of Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Agriculture Sector in Turkey |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/publication/turkiyede-tarim-sektorunden-kaynaklanan-sera-gazi-emisyonlarinin-azaltilmasina-yonelik-stratejiler/?lang=en |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917143354/http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/publication/turkiyede-tarim-sektorunden-kaynaklanan-sera-gazi-emisyonlarinin-azaltilmasina-yonelik-stratejiler/?lang=en |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The amount of [[nitrous oxide]] emitted by agricultural soils, however, is uncertain.<ref name=\"Urbanization 2016 p. 95\"/> About one million live cattle were imported in 2018, and cattle<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_8-29-2019.pdf|title=Livestock and Products Annual 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=USDA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and fuel for agriculture is subsidized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey increases agricultural subsidies |url=http://www.blackseagrain.net/novosti/turkey-increases-agricultural-subsidies |publisher=UkrAgroConsult |date=10 April 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215559/http://www.blackseagrain.net/novosti/turkey-increases-agricultural-subsidies |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some sugar factories such as those owned by T\u00fcrk\u015feker burn coal<ref>{{cite news |title=45.000 ton k\u00f6m\u00fcr alacak |url=https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/45-000-ton-komur-alacak/2343/ |work=Enerji Ekonomisi |date=3 July 2018 |access-date=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323072408/https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/45-000-ton-komur-alacak/2343/ |archive-date=23 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and some run small, coal-fired power plants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Algedik |first1=\u00d6nder |title=Coal & Climate Change - 2017 |url=http://www.onderalgedik.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Coal-and-Climate-Change-2017.pdf |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918012206/http://www.onderalgedik.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Coal-and-Climate-Change-2017.pdf |archive-date=18 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, Turkey's agriculture minister said that sugar is a strategic product.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish Agriculture Ministry may bid for some privatized sugar plants: Minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-agriculture-ministry-may-bid-for-some-privatized-sugar-plants-minister-128678 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=13 March 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215509/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-agriculture-ministry-may-bid-for-some-privatized-sugar-plants-minister-128678 |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}} estimates of the affects of government policy on the sector's emissions are lacking.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=28}}\n\nIn 2018, waste emitted 3.4% of the country's greenhouse gases.<ref name=\":3\" /> Turkey is working to improve sustainable waste and resource management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/ndc.spotlight%2012.6.19%20Enhancing%20Climate%20Action%20in%20Turkey%20-%20Zero%20Waste%20Programme.pdf|title=Enhancing Climate Action in Turkey: Zero Waste Programme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In particular because organic waste sent to landfill emits methane, Turkey plans to separate more of it for [[compost]]ing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zero-waste town to be built in Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/zero-waste-town-to-be-built-in-turkey-141256 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=15 February 2019 |access-date=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024544/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/zero-waste-town-to-be-built-in-turkey-141256 |archive-date=2 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Climate change mitigation ==\n=== Reducing greenhouse gas emissions ===\nPolicy for a [[Just Transition|just transition]] away from carbon-intensive assets such as coal is lacking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transition Policy for Climate Change Mitigation: Who, What, Why and How |url=https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/08/transition-policy-for-climate-change-mitigation.pdf |publisher=CCEP Working Paper 1807 |accessdate=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124162710/https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/08/transition-policy-for-climate-change-mitigation.pdf |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019 ratification<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kigali-amendment.openclimatedata.net/|title=Kigali Amendment|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210095237/http://kigali-amendment.openclimatedata.net/|archive-date=10 February 2019|access-date=1 March 2019}}</ref> of the [[Montreal Protocol#Hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs)|Kigali amendment to the Montreal Protocol]] reducing emissions of [[hydrofluorocarbons]] <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mondaq.com/turkey/x/666522/Climate+Change/Turkey+Announces+Rules+For+Use+Of+Fluorinated+Greenhouse+Gases+Listed+In+Kyoto+Protocol|title=Turkey Announces Rules For Use Of Fluorinated Greenhouse Gases Listed In Kyoto Protocol|date=23 January 2018|access-date=1 March 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024631/http://www.mondaq.com/turkey/x/666522/Climate+Change/Turkey+Announces+Rules+For+Use+Of+Fluorinated+Greenhouse+Gases+Listed+In+Kyoto+Protocol|archive-date=2 March 2019|publisher=Mondaq}}</ref> was under consideration by parliament<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/cygm/haberler/s-de-event-sunumlar-20191211093159.pdf|title=Setting up a new F-gas legislation in Turkey|last1=Kleinschmidt|first1=Julia|year=2019|publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning]]}}</ref> and awaiting presidential approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.diken.com.tr/turkiye-emisyonlari-azaltmayi-hedefleyen-kigali-degisikligini-onayliyor/|title=T\u00fcrkiye emisyonlar\u0131 azaltmay\u0131 hedefleyen 'Kigali De\u011fi\u015fikli\u011fi'ni onayl\u0131yor|date=2019-05-16|website=Diken|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531155456/http://www.diken.com.tr/turkiye-emisyonlari-azaltmayi-hedefleyen-kigali-degisikligini-onayliyor/|archive-date=31 May 2019|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> {{As of|2020}} it had not been ratified but there are some restrictions<ref>{{Cite book|last=T\u00dcM\u00d6Z G\u00dcND\u00dcZ|first=\u00d6zge|url=http://www.ozonactionmeetings.org/system/files/13_tur_ods_f-gas_regulation_in_turkey_the_link_of_the_kigali_amendment_ozge_son.pdf|title=ODS and F-gas Regulation in Turkey and the Link to the Kigali Amendment|publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning]]|year=2019|pages=}}</ref> and revision of the 2018 regulation is being considered<ref name=\":4\" /> (see also [[Registration,_Evaluation,_Authorisation_and_Restriction_of_Chemicals#In_non-EU_countries|Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals]]). Turkey's Energy Efficiency Action Act, which came into force in 2018, commits nearly 11bn USD to efficiency and could significantly limit emissions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Policy Projections |url=https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/current-policy-projections/ |publisher=Climate Action Tracker |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301074408/https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/current-policy-projections/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, however, policies had yet to be translated into measurable targets and implementation measures.<ref name=\"OECD 2019, executive summary\">OECD (2019), executive summary</ref> The [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] (EBRD) is investing in energy efficiency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/10/02/ebrd-to-introduce-new-energy-efficiency-finance-model|title=EBRD to introduce new energy efficiency finance model|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==== Energy ====\n{{As of|2019}}, high interest rates are an obstacle to the construction of solar power plants,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mert|last=G\u00fcrt\u00fcrk|title=Economic feasibility of solar power plants based on PV module with levelized cost analysis |journal=Energy|volume=171|date=15 March 2019|pages=866\u2013878|doi=10.1016/j.energy.2019.01.090}}</ref> but a solar panel factory is expected to start production in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/08/16/solar-panel-plant-to-boost-turkeys-role-in-renewables|title=Solar panel plant to boost Turkey's role in renewables|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> As Turkey has plenty of water (for the moment), wind and sunshine it would be relatively easy for the country to escape from carbon lock-in<ref>\u015eahin (2018), p. 5</ref> if [[energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's energy policy]] was changed to remove the US$1.6 billion<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey\u2019s energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> annual fossil fuel subsidies. Experimentation with hydrogen distribution is planned for 2021:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/01/15/hydrogen-to-enter-fuel-energy-distribution-network-next-year|title=Hydrogen to enter fuel, energy distribution network next year|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> moving towards a [[hydrogen economy]],<ref>{{cite web |title=National Hydrogen Association (Turkey) |url=http://hidrojenteknolojileri.org/eng/ |publisher=NATIONAL HYDROGEN ASSOCIATION |accessdate=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106153512/http://hidrojenteknolojileri.org/eng/ |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> for example for heating, could reduce dependence on imported natural gas. Alternatively in rural areas without a piped gas supply [[heat pump]]s might be used.\n\nNational and international investments in renewable energy and energy efficiency are being made; for example, the [[EBRD]]. [[Smart meter]]s are being installed at a slow pace.<ref>{{cite news |title=Analysis: Smart energy investments in Turkey |url=https://www.smart-energy.com/features-analysis/analysis-turkey-energy-market/ |work=Smart Energy International |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141748/https://www.smart-energy.com/features-analysis/analysis-turkey-energy-market/ |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Buildings ====\nBuilding standards in Turkey do not take into account the climate differences across the country and the existing 2005 Environment Act, Energy Efficiency Regulation and green building certificates are often not properly implemented. Academics have suggested adopting the EU standard (2018/844/EU amending the [[Directive on the energy performance of buildings]]) to increase the proportion of passive houses.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), pages 8 and 30</ref> At the [[2019 UN Climate Action Summit]] on Turkey promised all new buildings to be [[Zero-energy building|zero carbon buildings]] by 2030 and existing buildings by 2050.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/climate-change-summit-idUKL5N26E5P0|title=FACTBOX-12 global initiatives to beat back climate threats|date=2019-09-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/op-ed/2019/10/18/climate-crisis-in-the-wake-of-a-critical-summit-1571347020|title=Climate crisis: In the wake of a critical summit|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> Building codes need improvement to ensure that if parking spaces are provided they have enough [[charging point]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Transport ====\nFor the [[2019 UN Climate Action Summit]] on [[carbon neutrality]] by 2050, Turkey worked on decarbonization of land transport.<ref name=UN2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/WP-Infrastructures-Cities-and-Local-Action.pdf|title=Track #7: Infrastructure, Cities and Local Action|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Although there are several [[List of electric bus makers and models|manufacturers of electric buses]] and many are exported,<ref>{{cite news |title=Vilnius signs contract to buy its first electric buses |url=https://www.baltictimes.com/vilnius_signs_contract_to_buy_its_first_electric_buses/ |work=Baltic Times |date=27 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327165040/https://www.baltictimes.com/vilnius_signs_contract_to_buy_its_first_electric_buses/ |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, fewer than 100 are in use within the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=First ever self-driving e-bus in Istanbul, e-buses in provinces |url=https://balkangreenenergynews.com/first-ever-self-driving-e-bus-istanbul-e-buses-streets-provinces/ |work=Balkan Green Energy News |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327165040/https://balkangreenenergynews.com/first-ever-self-driving-e-bus-istanbul-e-buses-streets-provinces/ |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cities could be improved to make local journeys by bicycle safer.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), page 32</ref> The world's first all-electric [[Tugboat|tug]] is due to start work in Istanbul harbor in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ship-technology.com/news/corvus-energy-provide-battery-navteks-first-electric-tug/|title=Corvus Energy to provide energy storage system for Navtek's first all-electric tug|date=2018-07-13|website=Ship Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714080541/https://www.ship-technology.com/news/corvus-energy-provide-battery-navteks-first-electric-tug/|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bairdmaritime.com/work-boat-world/tug-and-salvage-world/feature-innovation-drives-rapidly-evolving-tug-and-salvage-industries/|title=FEATURE {{!}} Innovation drives rapidly evolving tug and salvage industries|last=McCready|first=John|date=2019-11-12|website=Baird Maritime|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> [[Automotive industry in Turkey|Turkey's automotive industry]] plans to make [[TOGG Turkish national car|a national electric car]] from 2022<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey plans to create domestic car with electric engine |url=https://www.azernews.az/region/147695.html |work=Azernews |date=23 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327174036/https://www.azernews.az/region/147695.html |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and has estimated that doing so would save the country 7 billion lira over 15 years, in part due to savings on oil imports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indigenous automobile to add 50B euros to Turkish economy in 15 years |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/automotive/2019/03/25/indigenous-automobile-to-add-50b-euros-to-turkish-economy-in-15-years |work=Daily Sabah |date=25 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327173204/https://www.dailysabah.com/automotive/2019/03/25/indigenous-automobile-to-add-50b-euros-to-turkish-economy-in-15-years |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Legality of ridesharing companies by jurisdiction#Turkey|legality of ridesharing companies]] is unclear,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menabytes.com/careem-exits-turkey/|title=After Oman, Careem exits Turkey too|last=|first=|date=2020-01-23|website=MENAbytes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-24|last3=Discovery|first3=A. Career|last4=Linkedin|first4=development platform for millennials in MENA He can be reached on|last5=zubairmenabytescom|first5=Twitter or}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newmobility.global/future-transportation/bcap-invests-turkish-rideshare-company-scotty/|title=BCAP invests in Turkish rideshare company Scotty|last=Alex|date=2020-01-16|website=New Mobility|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> and taxis could be better integrated with public transport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dijitalle\u015fme taksi sekt\u00f6r\u00fcn\u00fc nas\u0131l etkiliyor? |url=http://www.yesillojistikciler.com/haber/dijitallesme-taksi-sektorunu-nasil-etkiliyor-16123.html |publisher=Ye\u015fil Lojistik\u00e7iler |accessdate=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020142208/http://www.yesillojistikciler.com/haber/dijitallesme-taksi-sektorunu-nasil-etkiliyor-16123.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, fuel quality and emissions standards for new cars do not meet European Union standards.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\" /> {{As of|2018}}, most of the country has no fast charging stations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/11/zorlu-energy-poised-to-establish-fast-charging-stations-at-200-different-locations-in-turkey|title=Zorlu Energy poised to establish fast charging stations at 200 different locations in Turkey|date=11 October 2018|work=Daily Sabah|access-date=24 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327183753/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/11/zorlu-energy-poised-to-establish-fast-charging-stations-at-200-different-locations-in-turkey|archive-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Increasing greenhouse gas absorption by forests and soils===\n\n[[Carbon sink]]s, which in Turkey consist mainly of forests, offset about 20% of national emissions in 2017.<ref name=GHGsummary/> This figure is uncertain{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=489}} but {{As of|2019|alt=as of 2109}}, a new assessment is being made with the help of satellites and new soil measurements. Better information should be available in 2020.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019}}[[File:Reforestation Zone Doganbey Seferihisar Izmir Turkey.JPG|thumb|[[Do\u011fanbey, Seferihisar]] being [[reforestation#Turkey|reforested]]: but [[LULUCF]] can only reabsorb a small part of fossil fuel emissions]]\n\n[[Reforestation#Turkey|Reforestation in Turkey]] and changes in land use may offset 10% to 15% of fossil fuel emissions<ref>Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), p. 18</ref> but this figure is a rough estimate<ref name=\"CarbonBrief\">{{cite web |title=The Carbon Brief Profile: Turkey |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/carbon-brief-profile-turkey |website=Carbon Brief |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001142447/https://www.carbonbrief.org/carbon-brief-profile-turkey |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> as warmer and drier air in the south and west may make it difficult to sustain the present forest cover.<ref>{{cite web |title=PROVINCE BASED FOREST COVER (%) |url=http://climatechangeinturkey.com/effects-of-climate-change-forests.html |website=CLIMATE CHANGE IN TURKEY |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517191309/http://climatechangeinturkey.com/effects-of-climate-change-forests.html |archive-date=17 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NGO]]s such as the [[TEMA Foundation]] are encouraging reforestation and in 2015, the government stated that, by 2050, \u201cforests are envisioned to stretch across over four-fifths of the country's territory\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=What can Africa learn from Turkey's reforestation? |url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/10/what-can-africa-learn-from-turkeys-reforestation/ |publisher=World Economic Forum |date=29 October 2015 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122192832/https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/10/what-can-africa-learn-from-turkeys-reforestation/ |archive-date=22 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, according to [[Ege University]] Associate Professor Serdar G\u00f6khan Senol, sometimes the government is too focused on the economics and the [[Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry (Turkey)|Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry]] replants when sometimes it should just wait for regrowth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youris.com/environment/biodiversity/wildfires-in-izmir-a-green-plan-for-the-city-an-urban-plan-for-the-forests.kl|title=Wildfires in Izmir: a green plan for the city, an urban plan for the forests|website=www.youris.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nThree quarters of the land is deficient in [[Soil organic matter|soil organic carbon]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish soil at risk as worldwide desertification spreads |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/2018/06/19/turkish-soil-at-risk-as-worldwide-desertification-spreads |work=Daily Sabah |date=19 June 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330005959/https://www.dailysabah.com/life/2018/06/19/turkish-soil-at-risk-as-worldwide-desertification-spreads |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and this is being mapped to be added to Turkey's national soil database.<ref name=\"FAO\">{{cite journal |last1=SONMEZ |display-authors=et al |title=Turkey's National Geospatial Soil Organic Carbon Information System |journal=Global Symposium on Soil Organic Carbon |date=March 2017 |url=http://www.fao.org/3/a-br972e.pdf |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011172947/http://www.fao.org/3/a-br972e.pdf |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Economics==\n\nIn the late 20th and early 21st centuries growth of the [[Economy of Turkey|Turkish economy]] and population caused increased emissions from electricity generation,{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|pages=10,11}} industry and construction.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} However, when economic growth resumes after [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|Turkey's late 2010s recession]] it would be possible to further exploit the country's renewable energy potential and further invest in energy efficiency: so if the government implemented a suitable energy policy the economy could easily grow without increasing emissions.<ref name=\"Climate Action Tracker 2019 p. 63\"/>\n\nTurkey's [[social cost of carbon|carbon emissions]] cost Turkey money, even without [[carbon tariff]]s from other countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=New study finds incredibly high carbon pollution costs \u2013 especially for the US and India |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2018/oct/01/new-study-finds-incredibly-high-carbon-pollution-costs-especially-for-the-us-and-india |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 October 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208114443/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2018/oct/01/new-study-finds-incredibly-high-carbon-pollution-costs-especially-for-the-us-and-india |archive-date=8 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The long-term impact of climate change on any economy is highly uncertain and very difficult to estimate.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stoerk |first1=Thomas |last2=Wagner |first2=Gernot |last3=Ward |first3=Robert E T |title=Policy Brief\u2014Recommendations for Improving the Treatment of Risk and Uncertainty in Economic Estimates of Climate Impacts in the Sixth Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Assessment Report |journal=Review of Environmental Economics and Policy |date=1 August 2018 |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=371\u2013376 |doi=10.1093/reep/rey005 }}</ref> Although the short-term co-benefits of climate-change mitigation have been estimated at over US$50/tonne CO<sub>2</sub> abated for health alone for middle-income countries generally<ref>{{cite web |title=Multiple benefits from climate change mitigation: assessing the evidence |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/publication/multiple-benefits-from-climate-change-mitigation-assessing-the-evidence/ |publisher=[[London School of Economics]] |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710222455/http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/publication/multiple-benefits-from-climate-change-mitigation-assessing-the-evidence/ |archive-date=10 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MONETIZING THE HEALTH CO-BENEFITS OF A CARBON TAX |url=https://niskanencenter.org/blog/notes/monetizing-the-health-co-benefits-of-a-carbon-tax/ |publisher=Niskanen Center |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928201000/https://niskanencenter.org/blog/notes/monetizing-the-health-co-benefits-of-a-carbon-tax/ |archive-date=28 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> research to quantify them specifically for Turkey is still ongoing {{As of|2020||lc=y}}.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n[[Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University]] have developed a decision support tool and [[Integrated assessment modelling|integrated assessment model]] for energy and environmental policy for Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Isik |first1=Mine |title=Development of the Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University Energy Modeling System (BUEMS) and its Application on Economic and Technological Implications of Greenhouse Gas Emission Reductions in Turkey |url=https://www.researchgate.net/project/Development-of-the-Bogazici-University-Energy-Modeling-System-BUEMS-and-its-Application-on-Economic-and-Technological-Implications-of-Greenhouse-Gas-Emission-Reductions-in-Turkey |website=ResearchGate |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182307/https://www.researchgate.net/project/Development-of-the-Bogazici-University-Energy-Modeling-System-BUEMS-and-its-Application-on-Economic-and-Technological-Implications-of-Greenhouse-Gas-Emission-Reductions-in-Turkey |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i \u00dcniversitesi'nden T\u00fcrkiye'nin enerji politikalar\u0131na y\u00f6n verecek ara\u015ft\u0131rma |url=http://haberler.boun.edu.tr/tr/haber/bogazici-universitesinden-turkiyenin-enerji-politikalarina-yon-verecek-arastirma |publisher=Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182935/http://haberler.boun.edu.tr/tr/haber/bogazici-universitesinden-turkiyenin-enerji-politikalarina-yon-verecek-arastirma |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  One study puts the health benefits at 2.9 \u2013 3.6 billion EUR per year<ref>Jenson (2014), p. 6</ref> due mainly to a substantial increase in GDP because of reduced PM 2.5 [[Air pollution in Turkey|air pollution in the country]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Pollution and Health in Turkey Facts, Figures and Recommendations |url=https://www.env-health.org/IMG/pdf/150220_factsheet_air_and_health_turkey_en_final.pdf |publisher=Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL) |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822190726/http://env-health.org/IMG/pdf/150220_factsheet_air_and_health_turkey_en_final.pdf |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pant by numbers: the cities with the most dangerous air \u2013 listed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/datablog/2017/feb/13/most-polluted-cities-world-listed-region |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 February 2017 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223235324/https://www.theguardian.com/cities/datablog/2017/feb/13/most-polluted-cities-world-listed-region |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another study estimated that by creating a national emissions trading market at a US$50/tonne carbon price the INDC commitment could be met at a cost of 0.8% of GDP by 2030. But it did not estimate how much the benefits would offset that cost or what the cost of not having a market would be.<ref>{{cite news|title=Researchers examine Turkey to assess the impact of 2015 Paris climate commitments on a national economy|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-07-turkey-impact-paris-climate-commitments_1.html|publisher=[[MIT]]|date=31 July 2018|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182352/https://phys.org/news/2018-07-turkey-impact-paris-climate-commitments_1.html|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently there is only a voluntary market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climatescorecard.org/2020/03/a-voluntary-carbon-market-in-need-of-carbon-pricing-policy-in-turkey/|title=A Voluntary Carbon Market in need of Carbon Pricing Policy in Turkey|last=Duyan|first=\u00d6zlem|date=2020-03-19|website=Climate Scorecard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> A revenue neutral carbon tax might be best for the economy,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bavbek |first1=G\u00f6k\u015fin |title=Assessing the Potential Effects of a Carbon Tax in Turkey |journal=Centre for Economics and Foreign Policy Studies (EDAM) Energy and Climate Change Climate Action Paper |date=October 2016 |issue=6 |url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141946/http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and without a carbon tax or emissions trading the country could be vulnerable to future carbon tariffs imposed by the EU,<ref>{{cite news |title=Carbon tariffs are EU's secret weapon in trade battle |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/06/05/carbon-tariffs-eus-secret-weapon-trade-battle/ |work=Daily Telegraph |date=5 June 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506052457/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/06/05/carbon-tariffs-eus-secret-weapon-trade-battle/ |archive-date=6 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pollution Costs at Decade High Squeeze Industry, Coal in Europe |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-24/pollution-costs-at-decade-high-squeeze-industry-coal-in-europe |work=Bloomberg |date=24 August 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611051319/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-24/pollution-costs-at-decade-high-squeeze-industry-coal-in-europe |archive-date=11 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> the UK or other [[Economy of Turkey#External trade and investment|export partners]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Carbon Tariffs: A Climate Necessity? |url=http://regulatingforglobalization.com/2018/03/13/carbon-tariffs-climate-necessity/ |website=Kluwer Regulating for Globalization |accessdate=11 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011172855/http://regulatingforglobalization.com/2018/03/13/carbon-tariffs-climate-necessity/ |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, Turkey receives by far the most EU climate change financing<ref>{{cite news |title=Questions raised about EU climate financing as Turkey takes biggest share |url=https://www.devex.com/news/questions-raised-about-eu-climate-financing-as-turkey-takes-biggest-share-92562 |work=devex |date=18 April 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141838/https://www.devex.com/news/questions-raised-about-eu-climate-financing-as-turkey-takes-biggest-share-92562 |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[EBRD]] is investing.<ref name=\"Climate Home\">{{cite web|title=Turkey: Notes from a state of (climatic) emergency|url=http://www.climatechangenews.com/2016/11/10/turkey-notes-from-a-state-of-climatic-emergency/|publisher=Climate Home|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141830/http://www.climatechangenews.com/2016/11/10/turkey-notes-from-a-state-of-climatic-emergency/|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the government forecast that GHG emissions were expected to increase in parallel to the GDP growth in the next decade. {{sfnp|7th communication v2|2019|p=30}} In 2015 less than half of Turkey's carbon emissions from energy use were priced.<ref>OECD (2019), page 32</ref> Taxes meet the social cost of road transport carbon, although not the social cost of [[Air pollution in Turkey|Turkey's local air pollution]], but all other sectors have a large gap between the actual price and the cost if this [[negative externality]] had been fully included, thus the [[external cost]] of most greenhouse gas emissions is not being borne by the emitters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Effective Carbon Rates 2018 |url=https://www.oecd.org/tax/effective-carbon-rates-2018-9789264305304-en.htm |publisher=[[OECD]] |date=18 September 2018 |access-date=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106010542/https://www.oecd.org/tax/effective-carbon-rates-2018-9789264305304-en.htm |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Thus the [[polluter pays principle]] is being violated.\n\nIn 2017, a tenth of Turkey's electricity was generated by renewables, which reduced gas import costs. But being mainly [[hydroelectricity]], this percentage is vulnerable to drought. According to H\u00fclya Sayg\u0131l\u0131, an economist at [[Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey|Turkey's central bank]], although imports of solar and wind power components accounted for 12 percent of import costs in 2017, in EU countries this is largely due to one-time setup costs. She said that compared with Italy and Greece, Turkey has not invested enough in solar and wind power.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sayg\u0131l\u0131 |first1=H\u00fclya |title=RENEWABLE ENERGY USE IN TURKEY |url=http://www.tcmb.gov.tr/wps/wcm/connect/blog/en/main+menu/analyses/renewable_energy_us_+in_turkey |website=CBRT blog |accessdate=17 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021333/http://www.tcmb.gov.tr/wps/wcm/connect/blog/en/main+menu/analyses/renewable_energy_us_+in_turkey |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Co-benefits===\nAlthough improved health would be the primary benefit of cutting [[air pollution in Turkey]], because most of the air pollution is caused by burning fossil fuels a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions would be a co-benefit; for example of [[low emission zone]]s for city traffic, and replacing the distribution of free coal<ref>{{Cite journal|last=HAL\u0130S\u00c7EL\u0130K|first=Erg\u00fcl|date=2017|title=HOW TO DELIVER FREE COAL TO THE POOR FAMILIES? TURKEY CASE|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Erguel_Haliscelik/publication/322207751_HOW_TO_DELIVER_FREE_COAL_TO_THE_POOR_FAMILIES_TURKEY_CASE/links/5c6c0be34585156b57080d92/HOW-TO-DELIVER-FREE-COAL-TO-THE-POOR-FAMILIES-TURKEY-CASE.pdf|journal=Y\u00f6netim ve Ekonomi Ara\u015ft\u0131rmalar\u0131 Dergisi / Journal of Management and Economics Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> with a different support for poor families. Increasing the share of renewable energy could make the country more energy independent and increase employment<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=Cobenefits:Turkey |url=https://www.cobenefits.info/our-work/where-we-work/turkey/ |publisher=COBENEFITS |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013425/https://www.cobenefits.info/our-work/where-we-work/turkey/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> especially in [[solar power in Turkey|Turkey's solar PV and solar heating industries]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Renewable Energy and Jobs Annual Review 2018 |url=https://irena.org/-/media/Files/IRENA/Agency/Publication/2018/May/IRENA_RE_Jobs_Annual_Review_2018.pdf |publisher=[[International Renewable Energy Agency]] |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121203527/https://irena.org/-/media/Files/IRENA/Agency/Publication/2018/May/IRENA_RE_Jobs_Annual_Review_2018.pdf |archive-date=21 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\nThe [[Climate Change and Air Management Coordination Board (Turkey)|Climate Change and Air Management Coordination Board]] is responsible for coordination across government departments. It also includes three business organizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Te\u015fkilat Yap\u0131s\u0131 |url=https://iklim.csb.gov.tr/teskilat-yapisi-i-4368 |publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)]] |accessdate=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422073732/https://iklim.csb.gov.tr/teskilat-yapisi-i-4368 |archive-date=22 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey sees industrialized Western countries as solely responsible.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 24</ref> When limiting their actions on climate change, Turkey and some other countries have cited the [[United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement]] promised by [[Donald Trump|President Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change: 'Trump effect' threatens Paris pact |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46384828 |work=[[BBC]] |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=24 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424174404/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46384828 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that, although limiting emissions through directives to the state owned gas and electricity companies would be less effective than a carbon price or tax, it would be more politically acceptable.<ref>{{cite web |title=How to Talk to a Populist About Climate Change |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/29/how-to-talk-to-a-populist-about-climate-change/ |website=Foreign Policy |accessdate=31 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330162418/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/29/how-to-talk-to-a-populist-about-climate-change/ |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to former Economy Minister Kemal Dervish, the gains from the green transition will be spread across large parts of the population; while the losses will be concentrated on specific groups, making them more visible and politically disruptive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1163546.shtml|title=Distributional issues hurt fight to curb climate change - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=2019-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904143541/http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1163546.shtml|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> People in Turkey taking [[individual and political action on climate change]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/activists-turkey-demonstrate-call-unite-behind-science-climate-change|title=Activists in Turkey demonstrate with call to 'unite behind the science' on climate change|website=Middle East Eye|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> include children demanding action<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/climate-crisis/turkeys-11-year-old-activist-demands-grown-action-climate-change|title=Turkey's 11-year-old activist demands grown-up action on climate change|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904141307/https://ahvalnews.com/climate-crisis/turkeys-11-year-old-activist-demands-grown-action-climate-change|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and petitioning the UN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grist.org/article/what-the-climate-petition-filed-by-16-kids-at-the-u-n-really-means/|title=What the climate petition filed by 16 kids at the U.N. really means|date=2019-09-25|website=Grist|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Ratification of the Paris agreement===\nAccording to [[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Turkey's Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources]], climate change is one of the world's biggest problems.<ref>{{cite web |title=Climate Change and International Negotiations |url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Climate-Change-and-International-Negotiations |publisher=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)]] |accessdate=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928200850/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Climate-Change-and-International-Negotiations |archive-date=28 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Like neighboring Iran and Iraq, Turkey is one of the few [[List of parties to the Paris Agreement#Signatories|countries that have not ratified the Paris agreement on climate change]], and has said it will not ratify until it is given more access to international loans for emission reduction and renewable energy investments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iklimhaber.org/chief-climate-negotiator-turkey-does-not-have-a-luxury-to-be-a-laggard-in-terms-of-climate-action/|title=Chief Climate Negotiator: Turkey Does Not Have a Luxury to Be a Laggard in Terms of Climate Action|last=Bagat\u0131r|first=Bulut|date=2018-12-13|website=\u0130klim Haber|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Access to data===\nAbout 800 entities, including power plants over 20 MW, send measurements of their GHG emissions to the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icapcarbonaction.com/en/?option=com_etsmap&task=export&format=pdf&layout=list&systems%5B%5D=66|title=ETS Detailed Information: Turkey|website=International Carbon Action Partnership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Unlike conditions under the [[European Union Emission Trading Scheme]], where data must be openly shared with the public, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, monitoring, reporting and verification (MRV) data in Turkey is not open to public access,<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Emission Trading System Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-3_ETS-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430095304/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-3_ETS-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live |page=26}}</ref> although some companies report voluntarily. Quantitative estimates of the impacts of individual government policies on greenhouse gas emissions either have not been made or are not publicly available {{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}} and neither are projections of long-term (to 2050) policy impacts.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=21}} Up to date GDP and population growth forecasts have not been incorporated into models and assumptions such as future energy intensity, energy demand and electricity consumption are not known.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=23}} Whether [[sensitivity analysis]] of ghg scenarios has been done is also not known.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=23}} Turkey has told the UNFCCC that many details needed to understand GHG past trends and future projections \"could not be provided for confidentiality reasons.\"{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=27-28}}\n\n===Children's rights complaint===\nIn 2019 environmental activist [[Greta Thunberg]] and 15 other children made an official complaint against five nations that are not on track to meet the emission reduction targets they committed to in their Paris Agreement pledges: Argentina, Brazil, France, Germany, and Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations |title=16 children, including Greta Thunberg, file landmark complaint to the United Nations Committee on the Rights of the Child |website=www.unicef.org |language=en|access-date=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925123907/https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/09/1047292 |title=Countries violate rights over climate change, argue youth activists in landmark UN complaint |date=24 September 2019 |website=UN News |language=en|access-date=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925105953/https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/09/1047292|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The complaint challenges these five countries under the Third Optional Protocol to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]]. The Protocol is a quasi-judicial mechanism which allows children or their representatives, who believe their rights have been violated to bring a complaint before the relevant \u2018treaty body\u2019, the Committee on the Rights of the Child.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.childrightsconnect.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/CRC_OP3_info_pack_web.pdf |title=Information Pack about the Optional Protocol to the Convention on theRights of the Child on a Communications Procedure (OP3 CRC) |access-date=13 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013184521/https://www.childrightsconnect.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/CRC_OP3_info_pack_web.pdf |archive-date=13 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> If the complaint is successful, the countries will be asked to respond, but any suggestions are not legally binding.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/its-kids-vs-the-world-in-a-landmark-new-climate-lawsui-1838343565 |title=It's Kids vs. the World in a Landmark New Climate Lawsuit |first=Brian |last=Kahn |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=[[Gizmodo]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923170617/https://earther.gizmodo.com/its-kids-vs-the-world-in-a-landmark-new-climate-lawsui-1838343565 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/greta-thunberg-leads-young-people-in-climate-complaint-to-un |title=Greta Thunberg Leads Young People in Climate Complaint to UN |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190924041649/https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/greta-thunberg-leads-young-people-in-climate-complaint-to-un?utm_medium=ehsdesk&utm_campaign=530399D8-DE13-11E9-B270-A91350017A06&utm_source=twitter | archive-date = 24 September 2019 | url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nAccording to journalist Pelin Cengiz, the mainstream [[media of Turkey]] tends to cover newly opened [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] as increasing employment rather than causing climate change, and almost all owners have financial interests in fossil fuels.<ref>Cengiz (2019), p. 17,20</ref> According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at Sabanc\u0131 University, the media covers climate change only in times of extreme weather events, but does not include sufficient perspectives from civil society or expert opinion.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 28</ref> Some construction companies have been accused of [[greenwashing]] by advertising their buildings as environmentally friendly without actually obtaining any green building certificates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erden|first=O\u011fulkan|last2=Erkartal|first2=P\u0131nar \u00d6KTEM|date=2019-09-02|title=Greenwashing in Turkey: Sustainability as an Advertising Strategy in Architecture|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/pub/aarch/613890|journal=A+Arch Design International Journal of Architecture and Design|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|issn=2149-5904}}</ref>\n\n==Research and history==\nResearch is done at the [https://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/category/climate-change/index916b.html?lang=en&post_type=objective Istanbul Policy Center] and [https://www.shura.org.tr/eng/ Shura Energy Transition Center], both at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]]. \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Turkey|Global Warming}}\n\n*[[Climate change in Turkey]]\n*[[Energy policy of Turkey]]\n*[[Greenhouse gas inventory]]\n*[[List of countries by carbon dioxide emissions]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n====UNFCCC====\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Ministry of Environment and Urbanization\n |title=Seventh National Communication (version 2) of Turkey under the UNFCCC (this is also the third biennial report)\n |date=August 2019   \n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/14936285_Turkey-NC7-2-Seventh%20National%20Communication%20of%20Turkey.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|7th communication v2|2019}}  \n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the technical review of the seventh national communication of Turkey\n |date=June 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/idr7_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|Tech review 7th communication|2019}}\n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the technical review of the third biennial report of Turkey\n |date=June 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/trr3_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|Tech review 3rd report|2019}}\n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Turkish Statistical Institute\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory report [TurkStat report]\n |date=April 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2019-nir-13apr19.zip\n |ref={{harvid|Turkstat report|2019}}\n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Turkish Statistical Institute\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory 1990 - 2017 common reporting format (CRF) tables [TurkStat tables]\n |date=April 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2019-crf-13apr19.zip\n |format=TUR_2019_2017_13042019_080716.xlsx\n |ref={{harvid|Turkstat tables|2019}}\n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the individual review of the inventory submission of Turkey submitted in 2018\n |date=May 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/ARR2018_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|Inventory review|2019}}\n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Ministry of Environment and Urbanization\n |title=Turkey's fourth biennial report\n |date=December 2019   \n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/FOURTH%20BIENNIAL%20REPORT%20OF%20TURKEY.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|4th biennial report|2019}}  \n }}\n\n====Other sources====\n*{{cite journal \n |last1=Atilgan\n |first1=Burcin\n |last2=Azapagic\n |first2=Adisa \n |date=2016 \n |title=An integrated life cycle sustainability assessment of electricity generation in Turkey \n |journal=Energy Policy\n |volume=93\n|pages=168\u2013186\n |doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2016.02.055\n }}\n*{{Cite magazine\n |last1=Cengiz\n |first1=Pelin\n |last2=Z\u0131r\u0131\u011f\n |first2= Utku\n |last3=\u015eim\u015fek\n |first3=Soner\n |date=January 2019\n |title=THEMATIC JOURNALISM IN TURKEY: ENVIRONMENTAL-ECOLOGICAL REPORTING\n |url=https://www.hyd.org.tr/attachments/article/511/saha2en.pdf\n |magazine=saha\n |volume=Special Issue 2\n |pages=16\u201323\n |issn=2149-7885}}\n*{{cite web\n |last=\u015eahin\n |first=\u00dcmit \n |date=April 2016 \