se&remote=true&wind=false&countryCode=TR Live carbon emissions from electricity generation]\n* [https://www.climatewatchdata.org/countries/TUR Climate Watch: Turkey]\n* [https://carbon-turkey.org/en Capacity Development for the Implementation of a Monitoring, Reporting and Verification (MRV) System for Greenhouse Gas Emissions]\n* [http://turkishcarbonmarket.com/carbon-markets Carbon Market]\n* [http://www.skdturkiye.org/en/dusuk-karbon-ekonomisine-gecis-ve-verimlilik Business Council for Sustainable Development Turkey:Transition to Low Carbon Economy and Efficiency]\n\n{{Asia topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n{{Europe topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Climate change in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Chidgk1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenhouse_gas_emissions_by_Turkey"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on cruise ships}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\nThe passengers and crew of many [[cruise ship|cruise ships]] were found to be infected with the novel [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], many with substantial spread of the disease amongst passengers and crew.  The British-registered {{ship||Diamond Princess|ship|2}} was quarantined at [[Port of Yokohama|Yokohama]] for nearly a month from 4 February 2020. Substantial spread of the virus onboard drew headlines worldwide throughout February. Of the 3,700 passengers and crew, 700 people were infected and twelve died. On 20 February, the [[World Health Organisation]] stated that the one ship accounted for more than half of the reported infections around the world outside of China.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/20/coronavirus-live-updates-diamond-princess-cruise-ship-japan-deaths-latest-news-china-infections |title=Cruise ship accounts for more than half of virus cases outside China \u2013 as it happened |publisher=The Guardian |date=20 February 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304102207/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/20/coronavirus-live-updates-diamond-princess-cruise-ship-japan-deaths-latest-news-china-infections |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGovernments and ports initially responded by preventing many cruise ships from docking. The ''[[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cruise_ships#Zaandam|Zaandam]]'' was turned away from [[Chile]], then was delayed passage through the [[Panama Canal]] and had to negotiate to disembark at [[Port Everglades|Port Everglades, USA]]. [[Canada]] blocked all ships carrying more than 500 people from docking in Canada from 13 March to 1 July 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-1.5495881|title=What you need to know about COVID-19 in B.C. on March 13, 2020|website=[[CBC News]]|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314030733/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-1.5495881|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] declared that  foreign-flagged vessels carrying more than 50 people should not dock in [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[South Carolina]], and [[Puerto Rico]] from 29 March, and instead should prepare to treat any sick passengers and crew on board and try to medically evacuate the very sick to their home countries.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Coast Guard: Cruise ships must stay at sea with sick onboard |first=Freida |last=Frisaro |first2=Adriana |last2=Gomez Licon |last-author-amp=y |date=1 April 2020 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coast-guard-cruise-ships-must-122752320.html |work=Yahoo News |access-date=1 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401125152/https://news.yahoo.com/coast-guard-cruise-ships-must-122752320.html |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Australia banned cruise ships arriving from foreign ports from 15 March 2020, and on 27 March directed all foreign-flagged ships to leave the country.<ref name=Grad0704>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: legal action could undo government order that cruise ships leave Australian waters |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/coronavirus-legal-action-could-undo-government-order-that-cruise-ships-leave-australian-waters |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> However the 2,700 passengers offloaded at [[Sydney]] on 19 March by the Australian-based ''[[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cruise_ships#Ruby_Princess|Ruby Princess]]'' had caused over 10% of all COVID-19 cases across that country by 10 April, and some ship operators challenged the Australian government's order in court.<ref name=Grad0704/> \n\nThe crisis management team of the German federal government said on 4 March 2020, following several actual and suspected outbreaks on cruise ships, \"The Federal Foreign Office has included in its travel advice that there is an increased risk of quarantine on cruise ships.\"<ref name=berliner/> On 11 March 2020, [[Viking Cruises]] suspended operations for its 79-vessel fleet until the end of April, cancelling all ocean and river cruises, after it was revealed that a passenger on a cruise in Cambodia had been exposed to the virus while in transit via plane, placing at least 28 other passengers in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vikingrivercruises.com.au/my-trip/current-sailings/index.html|title=My Trip \u2013 Updates on Current Sailings|website=vikingrivercruises.com.au|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312181910/https://www.vikingrivercruises.com.au/my-trip/current-sailings/index.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/viking-cruises-coronavirus-suspends-operations-industry-struggles-2020-3 |title=Viking Cruises suspended operations worldwide due to the coronavirus, as infections ravage the cruise industry |first=Bill |last=Bostock |website=Business Insider |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174617/https://www.businessinsider.com/viking-cruises-coronavirus-suspends-operations-industry-struggles-2020-3 |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Similarly, on 12 March, [[Princess Cruises]], owner of virus-stricken ships ''Diamond Princess'' and {{ship||Grand Princess}}, suspended operations for all future cruises on its 18-ship fleet for 60 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/global-ship-operations-pause.html|title=Princess Cruises: Voluntary 60 Day Pause of Global Ship Operations \u2013 Notices & Advisories|publisher=Princess Cruises|date=12 March 2020|website=princess.com|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312190604/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/global-ship-operations-pause.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/12/coronavirus-viking-cruises-suspends-cruise-operations-until-may-1/5030006002/ |title=Princess Cruises suspends operations for 60 days; Viking Cruises cancels all cruises due to coronavirus |first1=Hannah |last1=Yasharoff |first2=Morgan |last2=Hines |last3=Tate |first3=Curtis |last-author-amp=y |website=[[USA Today]] |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312203258/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/12/coronavirus-viking-cruises-suspends-cruise-operations-until-may-1/5030006002/ |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A US Coast Guard report on 4 April 2020 stated that \"there are 114 cruise ships, carrying 93,000 crew members, either in or near U.S. ports and waters. ... Another 41 cruise ships, with 41,000 crew members, are underway and close to the U.S\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/another-cruise-ship-with-virus-victims-docking-in-florida-1.4882574 |title=Another cruise ship with virus victims docking in Florida |publisher=CTV News, The Associated Press |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=4 April 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405021519/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/another-cruise-ship-with-virus-victims-docking-in-florida-1.4882574 |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An estimated 21 cruise ships have had COVID-19 cases on board. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruisehive.com/21-cruise-ships-with-a-u-s-port-affected-by-covid-19/38939|title=21 Cruise Ships With a U.S. Port Affected By COVID-19|date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n{{toc limit}} \n\n== Incidents ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Cruise ship incidents with confirmed positive cases on board\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Ship\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Pass.\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Crew\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | People                                       \n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Date{{efn|Docking date (in 2020 unless otherwise noted)}}\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Location{{efn|Current location in italics if not currently docked|name=\"italics\"}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Owner/operator\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Tests\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Cases\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Dead\n|-\n! Dock{{efn|name=\"italics\"}}\n! Country\n|-\n| ''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|Diamond Princess]]''\n| 2,666<ref name=\"ship-diamond-princess\">{{cite web |url=https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/diamond-princess-update.html |title=Diamond Princess Updates:Confirmed Cases of Coronavirus on Diamond Princess (4th of February, 2020) |work=Princess.com |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302202526/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/diamond-princess-update.html |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>   \n| 1,045<ref name=\"ship-diamond-princess\" />\n| 3,711<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-outbreak-the-countries-affected/ |title=Coronavirus outbreak: The countries affected |work=Pharmaceutical Technology |date= |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304165909/https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/f