eb.archive.org/web/20200320164650/https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/luminosa/v1.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ship-costa-luminosa\" />\n| \n| 3\n| 1\n|-\n\n| {{ship||Ruby Princess}}\n| ~2,700<ref name=\"ship-ruby-princess\">{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/passengers-ruby-princess-cruise-sydney-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-3 |title=Officials are scrambling to round up 3,800 passengers and staff who disembarked from the Ruby Princess cruise in Sydney after 4 people tested positive for coronavirus |work=Business Insider |date= |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320100652/https://www.businessinsider.com/passengers-ruby-princess-cruise-sydney-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-3 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 1,100<ref name=\"ship-ruby-princess\" />\n| \n| 19 March<ref name=\"ship-ruby-princess\" />\n| [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]]{{efn|name=\"sydney\"}}<ref name=\"ship-ruby-princess\" />\n| Australia\n| [[Princess Cruises]]{{efn|name=\"carnival\"}}<ref name=\"ship-ruby-princess2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.princess.com/ships-and-experience/ships/ru-ruby-princess/ |title=Ruby Princess Cruise Ship |work=Princess.com |date= |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320030506/https://www.princess.com/ships-and-experience/ships/ru-ruby-princess/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| \n| 662<ref name=\"Guardian-4-4-20\"/>\n| 12<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-05\"/><ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\"/>\n|-\n\n| {{ship||Celebrity Solstice}}<ref name=\"ship-voyager-of-the-seas\" />\n| \n| \n| \n| 20 March<ref name=\"ship-voyager-of-the-seas\" />\n| [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]]{{efn|name=\"sydney\"}}<ref name=\"ship-voyager-of-the-seas\" />\n| Australia\n| [[Celebrity Cruises]]<ref name=\"cruise-owner-celebrity-cruises\">{{cite web |url=https://www.celebritycruises.com/cruise-ships/celebrity-solstice |title=Solstice |work=Celebrity Cruises |date= |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403114144/https://www.celebritycruises.com/cruise-ships/celebrity-solstice |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  \n| \n|11<ref name=\"nswhealth-2-4-2020\" />\n|1<ref name=\"Coronavirus can kill even the healthiest of us. Just ask the family of Perth man Ray Daniels\">{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-31/coronavirus-death-ray-daniels-family/12106860 |title=Coronavirus can kill even the healthiest of us. Just ask the family of Perth man Ray Daniels |work=abc.net.au |date= |access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{ship||Costa Magica}}<ref name=ThreeSmall/>\n| 2,309<ref name=\"ship-costa-magica\">{{cite web |url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/virus-affected-costa-magica-cruise-ship-in-ca-863815.html |title=Virus-Affected Costa Magica Cruise Ship In Caribbean Carrying 38 Russians - Embassy |work=UrduPoint.com |date= |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314174017/https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/virus-affected-costa-magica-cruise-ship-in-ca-863815.html |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 960<ref name=\"ship-costa-magica\" /> or 930<ref name=\"Costa_fox\" />\n| 3,269\n| \n| ''near [[Miami]]''{{efn|Denied entry to [[PortMiami|Port of Miami]]<ref name=\"cnn-3apr\"></ref>|name=\"denied.miami\"}}<ref name=\"cnn-3apr\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/cruise-ships-still-sailing/index.html |title=Cruise ships are still scrambling for safe harbor |accessdate=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402223549/https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/cruise-ships-still-sailing/index.html |archive-date=2 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| ''USA''\n| [[Costa Cruises]]{{efn|name=\"carnival\"}}<ref name=\"cruise-owner-costa-magica\">{{cite web |url=https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/magica/v1.html |title=Costa Magica |work=costacruises.com |date= |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710143640/https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/magica/v1.html |archive-date=10 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| \n| 2\n| \n|-\n| {{ship||Costa Favolosa}}\n| \n| 1,009\n| \n| \n| ''near [[Miami]]{{efn|name=\"denied.miami\"}}<ref name=\"cnn-3apr\" />\n| ''USA''\n| [[Costa Cruises]]{{efn|name=\"carnival\"}}<ref name=\"cruise-owner-costa-favolosa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/favolosa/v1.html |title=Costa Magica |work=costacruises.com |date= |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713172242/https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/favolosa/v1.html |archive-date=13 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| \n| 13\n| \n|-\n| {{ship||Costa Victoria}}\n| 726<ref name=\"Victoria_thelocal\" />\n| \n| \n| 25 March<ref name=\"Victoria_thelocal\" />\n| [[Civitavecchia]]{{efn|[[Metropolitan City of Rome Capital|Rome]]}}\n| [[Italy]]\n| [[Costa Cruises]]{{efn|name=\"carnival\"}}<ref name=\"cruise-owner-costa-victoria\">{{cite web |url=https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/victoria/v1.html |title=Costa Victoria |work=costacruises.com |date= |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327192657/https://www.costacruises.com/fleet/victoria/v1.html |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| {{MS|Zaandam||2}}\n| 1,243<ref name=\"Zaandam_CBC_1\" />\n| 586<ref name=\"Zaandam_CBC_1\" />\n| 1,829<ref name=\"Zaandam_CBC_1\" />\n| 2/3 April<ref name=\"cnn-3apr\" />\n| [[Port Everglades]]{{efn|Florida}}<ref name=\"cnn-3apr\" />\n| USA\n| [[Holland America Line|Holland America]]{{efn|name=\"carnival\"}}<ref name=\"Zaandam_CBC_1\" />\n| \n| 11\n| 2\n|-\n| {{ship|MV|Artania||2}}\n| 800<ref name=\"ABC-30-3-2020\"/>\n| 500<ref name=\"ABC-30-3-2020\"/>\n| 1,300<ref name=\"ABC-30-3-2020\"/>\n| 27 March\n| [[Fremantle]]{{efn|[[Western Australia]]}}\n| [[Australia]]\n| MS Artania Shipping<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/articles/31966/po-sells-artemis-to-artania-shipping |title=P&O sells Artemis to Artania Shipping |last=Archer |first=Jane |work=Travel Weekly |date=23 September 2009 |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115160712/http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/articles/31966/po-sells-artemis-to-artania-shipping |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| \n| 65<ref name=\"WA coronavirus deaths rise to six as Artania patient and overseas traveller die in Perth hospitals\">{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-07/wa-coronavirus-deaths-rise-to-six-as-two-die-in-perth-hospitals/12128886 |title=WA coronavirus deaths rise to six as Artania patient and overseas traveller die in Perth hospitals |work=ABC.net.au |date= |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Coronavirus crisis: WA records 11 new COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web |url=https://www.perthnow.com.au/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-crisis-wa-records-11-new-covid-19-cases-ng-b881516160z |title=Coronavirus crisis: WA records 11 new COVID-19 cases |work=Perth Now |date= |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 2<ref name=\"WA coronavirus deaths rise to six as Artania patient and overseas traveller die in Perth hospitals\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Greg Mortimer (ship)|Greg Mortimer]]''\n| \n| \n| 217<ref name=\"1odaily040720\"/>\n| \n| \n|\n| [[Aurora Expeditions]]\n| all<ref name=\"1odaily040720\">[https://10daily.com.au/news/a200407nktrf/nearly-130-including-australians-on-antarctic-cruise-ship-have-coronavirus-20200407\" The Australian operator of an Antarctica cruise ship says 128 of the 217 passengers on the Greg Mortimer -- many of them Australian -- have tested positive for coronavirus.\"] 10daily.com.au 7 April 2020</ref>\n| 128<ref name=\"1odaily040720\"/>\n| 0\n|}\n\n== ''Diamond Princess'' ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess}}\n{{ship||Diamond Princess|ship|2}} is a cruise ship registered in Britain owned and operated by [[Princess Cruises]] (incorporated in Bermuda and with headquarters in Santa Clarita, California, US), a brand of [[Carnival Corporation & plc]].\n\nSARS-CoV-2 was confirmed on 4 February 2020 to have spread within ''Diamond Princess'' during cruise M003,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bnonews.com/index.php/2020/01/timeline-coronavirus-epidemic/|title=Timeline: coronavirus epidemic|access-date=3 March 2020|date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303013717/https://bnonews.com/index.php/2020/01/timeline-coronavirus-epidemic/|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which had departed on 20 January 2020 from [[Yokohama]] (in [[Tokyo Bay]] near [[Tokyo]]) for a round trip.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bolsovercruiseclub.com/itinerary/Diamond-Princess/Roundtrip-Tokyo/20-January-2020/1345179?sessionkey=2C35A87F-0543c426A-923E-C48709603A7B&resultkey=default |title=Roundtrip Tokyo cruise on Diamond Princess, Princess Cruises departing 20th Jan 2020 (M003) |work=Princess |date= |access-date=1 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331180746/https://www.bolsovercruiseclub.com/itinerary/Diamond-Princess/Roundtrip-Tokyo/20-January-2020/1345179?sessionkey=2C35A87F-0543c426A-923E-C48709603A7B&resultkey=default |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 February the [[World Health Organisation]] stated that the ship accounted for more than half of the reported infections around the world, excluding China.<ref name=\"theguardian1\"/>\n\n==''World Dream''==\n[[File:World Dream.jpg|thumb|''World Dream'']]\nThe cruise ship ''[[World Dream]]'' (registered in the Bahamas, operated by [[Dream Cruises]]) was on a journey from [[Nansha District|Nansha]] Port, Guangzhou, Guangdong, China to Nha Trang and Da Nang in Vietnam during 19\u201324 January 2020 with 6,903 persons on board including 108 from Hubei, in which 28 were from Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://k.sina.com.cn/article_1644114654_m61ff32de02000wbav.html|title=\u4e16\u754c\u68a6\u53f7\u90ae\u8f6e\u5df2\u670911\u4eba\u786e\u8bca \u9014\u4e2d\u6700\u540e\u4e00\u591c\u72c2\u6b22\u89c6\u9891\u66dd\u5149|publisher=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=8 February 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084334/https://k.sina.com.cn/article_1644114654_m61ff32de02000wbav.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2020, the ship returned to Nansha Port. Port customs performed a temperature check for all disembarking passengers and crew, with 31 people sampled and tested for the virus, including those who had fever during the cruise and those who were in close contact with confirmed cases before they boarded for the cruise. All the test results were negative though some of them were later confirmed to be infected.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2020/02/07/686085.html|title=\u5371\u9669\u65e0\u4eba\u5bdf\u89c9\uff1a\"\u4e16\u754c\u68a6\u53f7\"\u8c6a\u534e\u90ae\u8f6e\u75ab\u60c5\u59cb\u672b|publisher=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=7 February 2020|author=\u674e\u4e91\u8776|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331183455/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2020/02/07/686085.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween 24 January 2020 and 2 February 2020, the ship made three additional cruises out of Guangzhou or Hong Kong, including two \"cruises to nowhere\" and one to the Philippines, although passengers from the journey were not disembarked at Manila due to local resident protests over fear on the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E7%AA%81%E7%99%BC/430817/%E6%AD%A6%E6%BC%A2%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E-%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C%E5%A4%A2%E8%99%9F%E4%B8%89%E6%AC%A1%E6%97%85%E7%A8%8B%E8%B3%87%E6%96%99%E6%9C%AA%E6%98%8E-%E9%80%B1%E6%9C%AB%E9%81%8A%E8%87%B3%E5%B0%91%E4%B8%89%E5%8D%83%E4%BA%BA%E7%99%BB%E6%B8%AF%E5%B2%B8|title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u4e16\u754c\u5922\u865f\u4e09\u6b21\u65c5\u7a0b\u8cc7\u6599\u672a\u660e\u9031\u672b\u904a\u81f3\u5c11\u4e09\u5343\u4eba\u767b\u6e2f\u5cb8|publisher=HK01|date=6 February 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084337/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%AA%81%E7%99%BC/430817/%E6%AD%A6%E6%BC%A2%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E-%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C%E5%A4%A2%E8%99%9F%E4%B8%89%E6%AC%A1%E6%97%85%E7%A8%8B%E8%B3%87%E6%96%99%E6%9C%AA%E6%98%8E-%E9%80%B1%E6%9C%AB%E9%81%8A%E8%87%B3%E5%B0%91%E4%B8%89%E5%8D%83%E4%BA%BA%E7%99%BB%E6%B8%AF%E5%B2%B8|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Confirmed cases ===\nOn 2 February 2020, the ship departed from Hong Kong for Taiwan with around 3,800 persons on board. On the same night, the cruise company was notified that there were confirmed cases from the ship's former passengers. On the next day, the Guangdong government officially announced that three former passengers from the Vietnam journey had been confirmed infected by the novel coronavirus after they were disembarked. Former passengers from the cruise in China were told to contact local health authority and observer quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/3048949/china-scrambles-locate-passengers-cruise-after-least-four|title=China scrambles to locate passengers on cruise after at least four diagnosed with coronavirus|publisher=South China Morning Post|date=4 February 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224000216/https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/3048949/china-scrambles-locate-passengers-cruise-after-least-four|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 11 February 2020, 12 cases associated with the cruise were confirmed, including 1 ground worker who had temporarily worked on the ship, and 4 relatives of passengers.<ref name=sina2020-02-17>{{cite news|url=https://tech.sina.cn/2020-02-17/detail-iimxxstf2110648.d.html|title=\"\u4e16\u754c\u68a6\u53f7\"\u90ae\u8f6e\u9a76\u5165\u67ec\u57d4\u5be8\u6d77\u57df \u8239\u5458\u63a5\u53d7\u65b0\u51a0\u75c5\u6bd2\u7b5b\u67e5|date=17 February 2020|publisher=[[China Radio International|CRI]] online|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084326/https://tech.sina.cn/2020-02-17/detail-iimxxstf2110648.d.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Quarantine and preventive actions ===\nAfter the Guangdong government official announcement of confirmed cases among former passengers, on 4 February 2020, Taiwan blocked the ship's [[Port#Port of call|port of call]] in [[Kaohsiung]] due to concern on the virus. On 5 February 2020, ''World Dream'' returned to Hong Kong and all 3,800 passengers and crew on board the ship at the time were put under quarantine at [[Kai Tak Cruise Terminal]].<ref name=\"WashPost_61DPrincess_3exWorldDream\">{{cite news | last1= Denyer | first1= Simon | title= Honeymooner among 61 people on cruise ship confirmed as having coronavirus | date= 7 February 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] | url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/honeymooner-among-61-people-on-cruise-ship-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus/2020/02/07/30a980b4-4961-11ea-8a1f-de1597be6cbc_story.html |access-date=7 February 2020  |archive-url= https://archive.today/20200207164834/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/honeymooner-among-61-people-on-cruise-ship-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus/2020/02/07/30a980b4-4961-11ea-8a1f-de1597be6cbc_story.html |archive-date= 7 February 2020  |url-status=live |url-access =limited}}</ref> The quarantine was lifted on 9 February 2020 after all 1,800 crew members tested negative for the virus. The majority of the passengers were not tested as they had had no contact with the infected Chinese passengers who had been on the ship during 19\u201324 January.<ref name=\"World Dream quarantine lifted\">{{cite news |title=Passengers leave Hong Kong cruise ship after coronavirus quarantine lifted |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/coronavirus-hong-kong-1.5457471 |access-date=9 February 2020 |publisher=CBC News |date=9 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210000225/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/coronavirus-hong-kong-1.5457471 |archive-date=10 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Evacuation of crew members ===\nAfter all passengers were disembarked, ''World Dream'' cruised to Malaysia. The crew were not allowed to leave the ship in several countries, after one passenger who had disembarked tested positive for COVID-19. The ship finally anchored near Bintan Island, Indonesia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indozone.id/news/OjsJnB/kisah-kapal-world-dream-sang-petualang-laut-usai-ditolak-bersandar/read-all |title=Kisah Kapal World Dream, Jadi Petualang Laut Usai Ditolak Bersandar |date=21 February 2020}}</ref> The evacuation of 188 Indonesia crew members from the cruise ship was performed by an Indonesian naval hospital ship and all tested negative for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://koran.tempo.co/read/nasional/450518/awak-kapal-world-dream-dibawa-ke-kepulauan-seribu? |title=Awak Kapal World Dream Dibawa ke Kepulauan Seribu |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> On 28 February 2020 they were quarantined for 14 days on the uninhabited Sebaru Kecil Islet, Thousands Islands, Jakarta.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/jakartas-island-starts-housing-evacuees-from-world-dream-cruise-ship.html |title=Jakarta's island starts housing evacuees from World Dream cruise ship |author=Nina A. Loasana |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403202531/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/jakartas-island-starts-housing-evacuees-from-world-dream-cruise-ship.html |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== MS ''Westerdam'' ==\n[[File:Westerdam Nov 24 2015.png|thumb|MS ''Westerdam'' pictured on 24 November 2015]]\nIn February 2020, the [[Holland America Line]] ship {{ship|MS|Westerdam}}, departing after a stop in Hong Kong on 1 February, was not allowed to call in the Philippines, Japan, and Guam over concerns regarding coronavirus infections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cruise ship that visited Hong Kong searches for a port after Philippines, Japan deny entry |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2020/02/06/coronavirus-cruise-ship-denied-by-japan-philippines-holland-america/4676988002/ |date=6 February 2020 |website=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=6 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212014728/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2020/02/06/coronavirus-cruise-ship-denied-by-japan-philippines-holland-america/4676988002/ |archive-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Guam denies entry to ship over coronavirus concerns |author=Jerick Sablan |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/02/07/guam-denies-entry-ship-over-coronavirus-concerns/4687803002/ |publisher=[[Pacific Daily News]] |date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> After initially receiving approval on 10 February to let the passengers disembark in Thailand, as the ship was heading to Laem Chabang port near Bangkok, permission to dock was refused the next day. However, the ship was still maintaining its course to Bangkok and at around 10:30&nbsp;am [[Central European Time|CET]] on 11 February, ''Westerdam'' sailed around the southern tip of Vietnam.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thailand bars Westerdam cruise ship, China virus toll tops 1,000 |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/thailand/general/1855034/thailand-bars-westerdam-cruise-ship-china-virus-toll-tops-1-000 |newspaper=[[Bangkok Post]] |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Thailand refuses entry to cruise ship with no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-thailand-cruiseship/thailand-refuses-entry-to-cruise-ship-with-no-coronavirus-cases-idUSKBN20503T?il=0 |accessdate=11 February 2020 |agency=Reuters |date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331183505/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-thailand-cruiseship/thailand-refuses-entry-to-cruise-ship-with-no-coronavirus-cases-idUSKBN20503T?il=0 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2322512|title=Nederlanders vast op cruiseschip Westerdam: 'We hebben behoorlijk spijt'|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> According to Flip Knibbe, a Dutch passenger on the ship, all the passengers had their temperatures checked a second time. Speaking to [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] on 11 February, Knibbe said \"''Dit schip is virusvrij''\": 'This ship is virus-free'. Unlike ''Diamond Princess'', those on board were not in quarantine. Everyone could move freely, shops and restaurants were open and the entertainment programme continued.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter ''Westerdam'' was refused at several points of call, on 13 February, the ship was allowed to dock in [[Sihanoukville (city)|Sihanoukville]], Cambodia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51484625|title=Cruise ship rejected by five ports docks at last|date=13 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213062133/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51484625|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At this point, only the 20 passengers who reported feeling ill were tested, and all of them tested negative.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50691572/health-ministry-asks-malaysia-to-re-test-specimens-of-us-woman-confirmed-positive-for-coronavirus|title=Health Ministry asks Malaysia to re-test specimens of US woman from MS Westerdam confirmed positive for coronavirus|last=Narim|first=Khuon|work=Khmer Times|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216110208/https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50691572/health-ministry-asks-malaysia-to-re-test-specimens-of-us-woman-confirmed-positive-for-coronavirus|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html|title=Scramble to Track Cambodia Cruise Ship Passengers After Coronavirus Case Reported|last1=Harris|first1=Ebrahim|last2=Sriring|first2=Orathai|last3=Setboonsarng|first3=Chayut|last4=Johnson|first4=Kay|last5=Feast|first5=Lincoln|agency=Reuters|work=The New York Times|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217074600/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February, Malaysia reported that an 83-year-old US citizen who disembarked from ''Westerdam'' and flew into Malaysia on 14 February had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3050814/coronavirus-us-passenger-westerdam-cruise-ship-infected|title=Coronavirus: Westerdam cruise passenger infected, Malaysia confirms|date=15 February 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215160347/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3050814/coronavirus-us-passenger-westerdam-cruise-ship-infected|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-malaysia/american-woman-from-cruise-ship-tests-positive-again-for-coronavirus-in-malaysia-idUSKBN20A06Q|title=American woman from cruise ship tests positive again for Covid-19 in Malaysia|last1=Tostevin|first1=Matthew|last2=Harris|first2=Ebrahim|last3=Ananthalakshmi|first3=A.|last4=Anantharaman|first4=Muralikumar|agency=Reuters|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216110952/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-malaysia/american-woman-from-cruise-ship-tests-positive-again-for-coronavirus-in-malaysia-idUSKBN20A06Q|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/9b8ab0035389-update1-passenger-from-westerdam-confirmed-by-malaysia-to-have-coronavirus.html|title=Passenger from Westerdam confirmed by Malaysia to have coronavirus|agency=Kyodo News|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216030203/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/9b8ab0035389-update1-passenger-from-westerdam-confirmed-by-malaysia-to-have-coronavirus.html|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a second test, requested by both the [[Holland America Line]] and [[Ministry of Health (Cambodia)|Cambodian authorities]] the woman tested positive again.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Woman from Cruise Ship Tests Positive Again for Coronavirus in Malaysia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=16 February 2020 |accessdate=16 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217074600/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/d4cacae28b40-westerdam-passenger-tests-positive-twice-for-virus-malaysia.html|title=Westerdam passenger tests positive twice for virus: Malaysia|agency=Kyodo News|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216135011/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/d4cacae28b40-westerdam-passenger-tests-positive-twice-for-virus-malaysia.html|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite these findings, Cambodian Prime Minister [[Hun Sen]] visited the ship, discouraged use of masks, and encouraged the passengers to tour the city, sparking concerns that another spoke was being added to the contagion network.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Beech|first=Hannah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/17/world/asia/coronavirus-westerdam-cambodia-hun-sen.html|title=Cambodia's Coronavirus Complacency May Exact a Global Toll|date=17 February 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=18 February 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218010645/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/17/world/asia/coronavirus-westerdam-cambodia-hun-sen.html|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further cruise passengers were denied entry to Malaysia from Cambodia as a result.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 22 February, after treatment with antiviral medications that were speculated to have an effect against COVID-19, the woman's medical condition improved and she was tested negative for SARS-CoV-2. The United States [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) initially stated that the woman had never been infected by SARS-CoV-2, but withdrew the claim, clarifying that the CDC \"[has] no visibility on whether the initial test of the woman was anything other than positive\".<ref name=\"USA_Today_Westerdam_woman\">{{cite news | last1= Hines | first1= Morgan | last2= Mandell | first2= Andrea | title= Westerdam cruise ship passenger now negative for coronavirus | date= 25 February 2020 |newspaper= [[USA Today]] | url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/21/coronavirus-holland-america-ms-westerdam-cruise-passenger-cleared/4834124002/ |accessdate=25 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20200225103203/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/21/coronavirus-holland-america-ms-westerdam-cruise-passenger-cleared/4834124002/ |archivedate= 25 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Due to possible background politics, it is uncertain whether these results were a false negative,<ref name=Time-5789745>{{cite news |url= https://time.com/5789745/westerdam-coronavirus-false-positive/ |title= An American Westerdam Cruise Ship Passenger Does Not Have COVID-19 |work= Time Magazine |author= Jaime Ducharme |date= 24 February 2020 |access-date= 3 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200228030236/https://time.com/5789745/westerdam-coronavirus-false-positive/ |archive-date= 28 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> or whether the passenger cleared the virus from her system after 72 hours of intensive treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/22/health-ministry-explains-american-covid-19-patient-recovering-after-treatme/1839855|title=Health Ministry explains American Covid-19 patient recovering after treatment, after US, Cambodia insist she wasn't infected at all|last=Ar|first=Zurairi|work=The Malay Mail|date=22 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223040751/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/22/health-ministry-explains-american-covid-19-patient-recovering-after-treatme/1839855|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== ''Grand Princess'' ==\n[[File:Grand Princess (ship, 1998) IMO 9104005, in Split, 2011-10-13.jpg|thumb|''Grand Princess'' in [[Split, Croatia]], 2011]]\n[[File:Maryland National Guard (49676182507).jpg|thumb|A member of the [[Maryland National Guard]] before transporting passengers from ''Grand Princess'']]\nPublic health officials from [[Placer County, California|Placer County]], [[California]] reported that an elderly resident with underlying health conditions who had died on 4 March 2020 had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 after returning from a cruise from [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] to [[Mexico]] and back on {{ship||Grand Princess}} between 11 and 21 February.<ref name=\"press.democrat.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10784064-181/first-coronavirus-death-in-california|title=Locals on same cruise ship as man who died from coronavirus concerned about spread|date=5 March 2020|website=Santa Rosa Press Democrat|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307011343/https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10784064-181/first-coronavirus-death-in-california|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sun>{{cite web |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/04/coronavirus-princess-cruises-ship-met-protest-over-no-testing/4950651002/ |title=Coronavirus: Californian who died likely got it on Princess Cruise |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=4 March 2020 |author=Morgan Hines |access-date=4 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305192959/https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/04/coronavirus-princess-cruises-ship-met-protest-over-no-testing/4950651002/ |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Placer County reports 2nd coronavirus case. 'Critically ill' patient was on cruise ship|last=Yoon-Hendricks|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/article240871226.html|work=[[The Sacramento Bee]]}}</ref> This marked the first death in California attributable to the virus.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite press release|author=<!-- No byline -->|title=Placer County Confirms Second Case of COVID-19; Declares Local Health Emergency to Ensure Adequate Resources|url=https://www.placer.ca.gov/6437/Placer-County-confirms-second-case-of-CO|agency=[[Placer County, California]]|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304070536/https://www.placer.ca.gov/6437/Placer-County-confirms-second-case-of-CO|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{cite press release|author=<!-- No byline -->|title=Death of Patient with COVID-19|url=https://www.placer.ca.gov/6438/Death-of-patient-with-COVID-19|agency=[[Placer County, California]]|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305022748/https://www.placer.ca.gov/6438/Death-of-patient-with-COVID-19|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The source of the new case's infection appeared to be the same as that of a resident of [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma County]] who tested positive on 2 March and who was also aboard ''Grand Princess'' on the same dates.<ref>{{cite web|date=3 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Sonoma County coronavirus patient was passenger on Princess Cruises ship|last=Johnson|first=Julie|url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10779399-181/sonoma-county-coronavirus-patient-was|work=[[The Press Democrat]], Santa Rosa, Calif.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=California county says person who died from coronavirus had recently taken cruise to Mexico|last1=Maxouris|first1=Christina|last2=Hanna|first2=Jason|last3=Almasy|first3=Steve|work=[[CNN]]|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/health/us-coronavirus-update-wednesday/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304152135/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/health/us-coronavirus-update-wednesday/index.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConsequently, Princess Cruises, the owner and operator of ''Grand Princess'', working with the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC), the government of California, and public health officials in San Francisco, terminated a port call in [[Ensenada, Baja California|Ensenada]], Mexico planned for 5 March and ordered the ship to return to San Francisco over concerns about the potential for an outbreak on board.<ref name=\"usa.today.1\" />\n\nAfter ''Grand Princess'' docked in San Francisco on 21 February, 62 passengers who had been on the previous cruise to Mexico reboarded the ship as it set sail for [[Hawaii]], making stops at [[Kauai]], [[Oahu]], [[Maui]], and [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]] (on the [[Hawaii (island)|Big Island]]) between 26 and 29 February.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Consillio |first1=Kristen |title=Gov. David Ige issues emergency proclamation in response to coronavirus |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/04/breaking-news/watch-live-gov-david-ige-and-hawaii-health-officials-give-update-on-coronavirus-in-hawaii/ |website=Star Advertiser |publisher=Star Advertiser |accessdate=6 March 2020 |date=4 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134355/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/04/breaking-news/watch-live-gov-david-ige-and-hawaii-health-officials-give-update-on-coronavirus-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"khon2.1\">{{cite web |last1=Mattison |first1=Sara |title=California man on same cruise ship that came to Hawaii has died from COVID-19 |url=https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/california-man-on-same-cruise-ship-that-came-to-hawaii-has-died-from-covid-19/ |website=KHON2 |publisher=KHON |accessdate=6 March 2020 |location=Honolulu, HI |date=4 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306230152/https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/california-man-on-same-cruise-ship-that-came-to-hawaii-has-died-from-covid-19/ |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> These passengers, who may have made been exposed to the same environment as were the Placer or Sonoma County cases during the previous cruise, were quarantined in their own on-board staterooms on 4 March by order of the CDC.<ref name=\"usa.today.1\">{{cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Thousands may have been exposed to coronavirus on Princess cruise ship; 62 passengers confined|last1=Hines|first1=Morgan|work=[[USA Today]]|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/04/coronavirus-princess-cruises-ship-met-protest-over-no-testing/4950651002/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305030815/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/04/coronavirus-princess-cruises-ship-met-protest-over-no-testing/4950651002/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, eleven passengers and ten crew members were exhibiting potential symptoms, and ''Grand Princess'' was ordered by the government of California to remain offshore while the [[California National Guard]]'s [[129th Rescue Wing]] airlifted test kits by helicopter to the ship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/world/coronavirus-news.html|title=Cruise Ship Held Off California Becomes New Focus of Concern|date=6 March 2020|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304052003/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/world/coronavirus-news.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Princess Cruises ship held up off California coast with sick passengers, awaiting coronavirus tests|last=Simpson|first=Hannah|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/travel/2020/03/04/princess-cruises-ship-held-up-off-california-coast-awaiting-coronavirus-tests/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305112533/https://www.washingtonpost.com/travel/2020/03/04/princess-cruises-ship-held-up-off-california-coast-awaiting-coronavirus-tests/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/video/2020/03/06/see-air-national-guard-members-board-a-cruise-ship-with-coronavirus-test-kits-newsbreak/|title=See Air National Guard members board a cruise ship with coronavirus test kits &#124; Newsbreak|website=Military Times|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309212758/https://www.militarytimes.com/video/2020/03/06/see-air-national-guard-members-board-a-cruise-ship-with-coronavirus-test-kits-newsbreak/|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Princess Cruises confirmed that there were 3,533 people on board the ship\u20142,422 passengers and 1,111 crew members\u2014representing 54 nationalities in total.<!-- note: reference made no mention of distance from San Francisco at the time and the ship is unlikely to have anchored in water too deep for the anchor to reach to the bottom --><ref name=\"princess.1\">{{cite web |title= Grand Princess Updates & Health Advisory |publisher= Princess Cruise Lines |url= https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/grand-princess-updates.html |access-date= 5 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200304221115/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/grand-princess-updates.html |archive-date= 4 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] announced that of the 46 tests run on selected passengers and crew members on ''Grand Princess'', 19 crew members and two passengers had tested positive, 24 had tested negative, and one test was inconclusive.<ref name=\"task.force.briefing.1\" /> Pence announced at a [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] briefing that the ship would be brought to a non-commercial port, and that everyone on the ship would be tested and quarantined as necessary.<ref name=\"task.force.briefing.1\">{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAsq7-_3XTI |title= Vice President Pence and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force Hold a Press Briefing |date= 6 March 2020 |first1= Mike |last1= Pence |publisher= Youtube |work= The White House |access-date= 6 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200306205750/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAsq7-_3XTI&app=desktop |archive-date= 6 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> On 6 March, [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] said that, despite what experts told him about limiting the spread of COVID-19, he wanted those on board ''Grand Princess'' to stay on the ship so that they would not be counted as American cases, which would otherwise \"double because of one ship that wasn't our fault.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-keep-passengers-on-grand-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-2020-3|title=Trump wants to keep people on coronavirus-hit Grand Princess cruise ship|website=Business Insider|date=7 March 2020|author=Morgan McFall-Johnsen|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307123701/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-keep-passengers-on-grand-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-2020-3|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, Princess Cruises confirmed that ''Grand Princess'' was still at sea roughly {{convert|50|mi}} from San Francisco, and that it was scheduled to dock in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] on 9 March, with its passengers to be transferred to facilities on land while the crew would be quarantined and treated on board.<ref name=\"princess.1\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Disembarkation will continue Monday for other guests. According to Governor's Office of Emergency Services, following health screenings, guests who are California residents will go to a federally operated facility within California for testing and isolation... |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PrincessCruises/status/1236535750650290181 |website=Twitter.com |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331183609/https://mobile.twitter.com/PrincessCruises/status/1236535750650290181 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Exact timing is still being determined in a coordinated manner with all operations resources. These guests will be transported to medical facilities in California |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PrincessCruises/status/1236535749433909249 |website=Twitter.com |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331183610/https://mobile.twitter.com/PrincessCruises/status/1236535749433909249 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The logistics plan went into further review by the state and federal authorities and the ship will not berth in Oakland on Sunday. It will now be Monday \u2013 time to be determined. |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PrincessCruises/status/1236542318900948992 |website=Twitter.com}}</ref>  The [[United States Coast Guard]] had airlifted supplies, including [[personal protective equipment]], to the ship, and had [[medical evacuation|medivacked]] a critically ill passenger and his travel companion for treatment unrelated to COVID-19.<ref name=\"princess.1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the ship docked at the [[Port of Oakland]] and passengers started disembarking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus-Stricken Grand Princess Arrives At Port Of Oakland; Passenger Says 'It Looks Like A War Zone' |url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2020/03/09/coronavirus-stricken-grand-princess-golden-gate-bridge-sick-passengers-oakland/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310004559/https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2020/03/09/coronavirus-stricken-grand-princess-golden-gate-bridge-sick-passengers-oakland/ |archive-date=10 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> More than 3,000 people on board were to be quarantined, with passengers at land facilities and the crew on board.<ref name=WP202010th>{{cite web |last1=Albergotti |first1=Reed |title=Grand Princess cruise ship carrying coronavirus patients docks in Oakland |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/03/09/grand-princess-cruise-ship-infected-with-coronavirus-docks-oakland/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310034324/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/03/09/grand-princess-cruise-ship-infected-with-coronavirus-docks-oakland/ |archive-date=10 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=WP202010th/> As of 22:00, 407 people had disembarked.<ref name=\"princess.1\"/>\n\nPrincess Cruises confirmed on 10 March that 1,406 people had disembarked from ''Grand Princess'',<ref name=\"princess.1\"/> increasing to 2,042 on 12 March.<ref name=\"princess.1\"/>\n\n=== Disembarked cases<!-- Mentioning the virus by name repeatedly is not necessary. It is obvious that patients are being tested for or diagnosed with SARS-CoV-2. --> ===\n\n==== 2 March ====\n* California: The [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma County]] Department of Health confirmed that a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'', on the cruise from San Francisco to Mexico, was a (presumptive) case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sonomacounty.ca.gov/Health/Press-Releases/Local-Emergency-Declared-for-COVID-19/|title=Local Emergency Declared for COVID-19 &#124; Press Releases &#124; Health Services &#124; County of Sonoma|website=sonomacounty.ca.gov|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305024129/http://sonomacounty.ca.gov/Health/Press-Releases/Local-Emergency-Declared-for-COVID-19/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== 3 March ====\n* California: [[Placer County, California|Placer County]] officials confirmed that a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'', also on the cruise from San Francisco to Mexico, was a (presumptive) case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.placer.ca.gov/6437/Placer-County-confirms-second-case-of-CO|title=Placer County confirms second case of COVID-19; declares local health emergency to ensure adequate resources &#124; Placer County, CA|website=placer.ca.gov|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304070536/https://www.placer.ca.gov/6437/Placer-County-confirms-second-case-of-CO|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials confirmed the next day that the passenger had died.<ref name=\"press.democrat.1\" /><ref name=\"sun\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==== 5 March ====\n* Canada:\n** [[Alberta]]: Alberta reported its first presumptive case, a woman in her 50s who lives in the [[Calgary]] area, was on board ''Grand Princess'' and returned to Alberta on 21 February.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-reports-first-presumptive-case-of-covid-19-1.5487787|title=Alberta reports 1st presumptive case of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=5 March 2020|website=CBC|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221134501/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-reports-first-presumptive-case-of-covid-19-1.5487787|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* United States:\n** California:\n*** Placer County: Officials reported an additional three presumptive positive cases, with all three having travelled on the same cruise on the same dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.placer.ca.gov/6439/3-new-COVID-19-cases-all-with-ties-to-cr|title=Placer County Public health confirms 3 new COVID-19 cases, all with ties to cruise ship &#124; Placer County, CA|website=placer.ca.gov|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308003914/https://www.placer.ca.gov/6439/3-new-COVID-19-cases-all-with-ties-to-cr|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*** Sonoma County: Health officials announced another positive presumptive case who was a passenger on the same cruise between 11 and 21 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kron4.com/health/coronavirus/cruise-ship-passenger-from-sonoma-county-tests-presumptive-positive-for-coronavirus/|title=Former cruise ship passenger from Sonoma County tests presumptive positive for coronavirus|date=5 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306152620/https://www.kron4.com/health/coronavirus/cruise-ship-passenger-from-sonoma-county-tests-presumptive-positive-for-coronavirus/|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*** [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]]: [[Department of Public Safety]] officers reported that they performed [[Cardiopulmonary resuscitation|CPR]] on an unconscious 72-year-old patient who was not breathing, but were ultimately unsuccessful in reviving him.<ref name=\"sunnyvale.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/sunnyvale-officers-possibly-exposed-to-coronavirus|title=Sunnyvale officers possibly exposed to coronavirus while giving CPR to dying man|date=6 March 2020}}</ref> After the man died, a family member informed officials that the victim had been a passenger on ''Grand Princess'' with two other people currently suspected of being infected.<ref name=\"sunnyvale.1\" />\n** [[Nevada]]: The [[Washoe County, Nevada|Washoe County]] Health District announced that a presumptive positive patient, a male in his 50s, has been linked to ''Grand Princess''.<ref name=\"washoe.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washoecounty.us/outreach/2020/03/2020-03-05-covid-19-confirmed.php|title=Washoe County Has Presumptive Case of COVID-19|website=washoecounty.us|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100546/https://www.washoecounty.us/outreach/2020/03/2020-03-05-covid-19-confirmed.php|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He self-isolated at home.<ref name=\"washoe.1\" /> An elementary school in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] was closed because one of the man's family members is a student there.<ref name=\"washoe.1\" />\n\n==== 6 March ====\n* Canada:\n** [[Ontario]]: Health officials confirmed that two new cases, a married man and woman in their 60s, were aboard ''Grand Princess'' from 11\u201321 February and returned to Canada on 28 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-confirms-new-positive-cases-of-covid-19-4.html|title=Ontario Confirms New Positive Cases of COVID-19|date=6 March 2020|website=news.ontario.ca|accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162854/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-confirms-new-positive-cases-of-covid-19-4.html|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* United States:\n** California:\n*** [[Alameda County, California|Alameda County]]: Officials confirmed that a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'', an older patient with underlying health problems, has tested positive.<ref name=\"alameda.county.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/second-SARS-CoV-2-case-confirmed-in-alameda-county|title=Second coronavirus case confirmed in Alameda County|date=7 March 2020|website=East Bay Times|language=en-US|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The former passenger was on the ship during the trip to Mexico from 11\u201321 February 2020. The patient was hospitalised and family members were quarantined.\n*** [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa County]]: Health officials announced that two new cases have been identified, with both having traveled on the same cruise on the same dates.<ref name=\"contra.costa.2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/coronavirus-contra-costa-has-three-new-cases-including-two-cruise-ship-patients|title=Coronavirus: Contra Costa has three new cases, including two cruise ship patients|date=6 March 2020|website=The Mercury News|language=en-US|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n*** [[Marin County, California|Marin County]]: The health department announced that two Marin County residents that were on the cruise and displayed symptoms have also been tested, but Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] has prioritised the testing of the passengers currently aboard ''Grand Princess'', and all the tests are going through the same lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/50-marin-cruise-passengers-exposed-to-coronavirus|title=50 Marin cruise passengers exposed to coronavirus|date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Hawaii]]: Governor [[David Ige]] announced the state's first case, a male [[Oahu]] resident who was a passenger on ''Grand Princess''.<ref name=\"hawaii.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/gov-ige-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-hawaii/|title=VIDEO: Hawaii resident, passenger aboard Grand Princess confirmed as first coronavirus case in Hawaii|date=7 March 2020|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307193138/https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/gov-ige-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-hawaii/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"hawaii.2\"/> Although the ship stopped in Hawaii in late February, the man disembarked ''Grand Princess'' in Mexico earlier in February (before it returned in San Francisco on 21 February) and flew back home to [[Honolulu]] from Mexico.<!-- note that the princess cruises brochure lists puerto vallarta, manzanillo, mazatl\u00e1n, and cabo san lucas as the mexican ports of call for the 10-day mexican riviera cruise beginning 2020.02.11, so it's unlikely he disembarked at ensenada --><ref name=\"hawaii.1\"/><ref name=hawaii.2>{{cite web |author1=The Civil Beat Staff |title=Cruise Ship Passenger Is Hawaii's First Coronavirus Case |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/03/21-test-positive-for-coronavirus-on-cruise-ship-that-stopped-in-hawaii/ |website=Civil Beat |publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat |accessdate=7 March 2020 |location=Honolulu, HI |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307023039/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/03/21-test-positive-for-coronavirus-on-cruise-ship-that-stopped-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"brochure\">{{cite web |title=2019-2020 Hawaii, Mexico & California coast |url=https://book.princess.com/images/cc/brochure/downloads/hi-mex-cal-coast-brochure-2019-20-v2.pdf |website=book.princess.com |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307093815/https://book.princess.com/images/cc/brochure/downloads/hi-mex-cal-coast-brochure-2019-20-v2.pdf |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n** [[Illinois]]: The Illinois and Chicago public-health departments announced that a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'' tested (presumptive) positive. The passenger, a woman in her 50s, had traveled on the same cruise to Mexico and disembarked at San Francisco on 21 February. She was hospitalized and isolated in stable condition. She is a special education assistant in the Chicago public school system, and the school where she worked was to be closed the following week, with all at-risk staff requested to self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5990270/|title=Coronavirus update: CPS employee is 6th confirmed case of COVID-19 in Illinois, mayor says|date=6 March 2020|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307035148/https://abc7chicago.com/5990270/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n** [[Utah]]: The Department of Health confirmed that the first (presumptive) case in Utah is a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'' living in Davis County.<ref name=\"utah.1\">{{cite web |title=Utah Health Officials Announce First Case of COVID-19 - Utah Department of Health |url=https://health.utah.gov/featured-news/utah-health-officials-announce-first-case-of-covid-19 |website=health.utah.gov |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307191818/https://health.utah.gov/featured-news/utah-health-officials-announce-first-case-of-covid-19 |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== 7 March ====\n* Canada:\n** [[British Columbia]]: Health officials announced that two cases are former passengers of ''Grand Princess''. Both in their 60s, the two patients rode the ship to Mexico and back to California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6645114/coronavirus-bc-cases-update-march-7/|title=B.C. declares COVID-19 outbreak at North Vancouver care home, 6 new cases announced|date=7 March 2020|website=Global News|accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308003913/https://globalnews.ca/news/6645114/coronavirus-bc-cases-update-march-7/|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* United States:\n** California:\n*** [[Fresno County, California|Fresno County]]: Officials confirmed that a former passenger of ''Grand Princess'' had tested positive.<ref name=\"fresno.county.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/health-officials-confirm-first-case-of-covid-19-in-fresno-county-second-in-central-valley/|title=Health officials confirm first case of COVID-19 in Fresno County, second in Central Valley|date=7 March 2020|website=Your Central Valley|language=en-US|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308122055/https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/health-officials-confirm-first-case-of-covid-19-in-fresno-county-second-in-central-valley/|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The former passenger was on the ship during the trip to Mexico from 11\u201321 February 2020. The family of the patient is reported to be self-monitoring.\n\n====21 and 23 March====\nTwo passengers from ''Grand Princess'' died from complications of coronavirus: one on 21 March and the other on 23 March. Both were in their early sixties. Of the 1,103 passengers who elected to be tested, 103 tested positive, 699 tested negative. The remaining results are pending, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)]] said.<ref name=Hines2020-03-25>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/two-grand-princess-cruise-passengers-223754516.html |title=Two Grand Princess cruise passengers with coronavirus die; 103 have tested positive for COVID-19 |first=Morgan |last=Hines |first2=Andrea |last2=Mandell |last-author-amp=y |work=USA Today |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |via=Yahoo News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327045116/https://news.yahoo.com/two-grand-princess-cruise-passengers-223754516.html |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== 1 April ====\n\nOne crew member died in a San Francisco hospital after contracting COVID-19 on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8f2dc5a4477d68b6393712dfbfc11f4a|title=Grand Princess crew ends quarantine; ship to sail out to sea|date=4 April 2020|website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\n== MS ''River Anuket'' ==\n[[File:MS River Anuket R01.jpg|thumb|MS ''River Anuket'', pictured March 2018]]\n{{Anchor|MS River Anuket|River Anuket|MS Asara|Asara|Anuket}}\n{{see also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Egypt#Nile River cruise ship}}\n\nA Taiwanese-American tourist, who had been a passenger on a [[Nile River]] cruise ship variously known as {{MS|River Anuket}}<ref name=\"washington.post.1\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/uae-raises-virus-cases-to-45-new-cases-from-9-nationalities/2020/03/07/52affb1c-6035-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html |title= Egypt says cruise ship quarantined over new virus cluster |first1= Maggie |last1= Michael |first2= Samy |last2= Magdy |agency= AP |newspaper= Washington Post |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date= 7 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200308193805/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/uae-raises-virus-cases-to-45-new-cases-from-9-nationalities/2020/03/07/52affb1c-6035-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html |archive-date= 8 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> or ''Asara'',<ref name=\"washington.post.2\">{{cite news |first1= Sudarsan |last1= Raghavan |first2= Meryl |last2= Kornfield |title= On the Nile, American tourists are among those quarantined on ship hit by coronavirus |newspaper= Washington Post |date= 7 March 2020 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/on-the-nile-american-tourists-among-those-quarantined-on-ship-hit-by-coronavirus/2020/03/07/51b0f29a-60a1-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html |access-date= 8 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200308182848/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/on-the-nile-american-tourists-among-those-quarantined-on-ship-hit-by-coronavirus/2020/03/07/51b0f29a-60a1-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html |archive-date= 8 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> discovered that she was positive for SARS-CoV-2 after she returned to [[Taiwan]]. [[World Health Organization]] officials informed Egyptian authorities of the situation, and all crew members and 150 passengers aboard the cruise ship were tested for SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"washington.post.1\"/> On 7 March 2020, health authorities announced that 45 people on board had tested positive despite being asymptomatic,<ref name=Twitter1236347954593759232>{{cite tweet|user=DailyNewsEgypt|number=1236347954593759232|date= 7 March 2020 |title=The total number of infected cases from the Nile cruise}}</ref> and that the ship had been placed in quarantine at a dock in [[Luxor]].<ref name=\"washington.post.1\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== MS ''Braemar'' ==\n[[File:BREAMAR (36487157951).jpg|thumb|{{MS|Braemar}} in [[Nieuwe Waterweg]]]]\n\nOn 13 March 2020, five passengers tested positive for the COVID-19 virus aboard {{MS|Braemar}}. As a result, the ship was denied entry into its destination, [[the Bahamas]]. The infected patients were discovered after a former passenger of the cruise tested positive in the Canadian province of [[Alberta]]. The infected passenger disembarked off the cruise in [[Kingston, Jamaica]], but it was unknown where they contracted the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/2020/mar/12/breaking-five-bahamas-bound-cruise-ship-test-posit/|title=Cruise Ship Carrying Persons With Coronavirus 'Will Not Be Permitted To Dock'|date=13 March 2020|website=The Tribune|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327190153/http://www.tribune242.com/news/2020/mar/12/breaking-five-bahamas-bound-cruise-ship-test-posit/|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Sint Maarten]] also denied a request from the cruise to allow passengers to fly out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedailyherald.sx/islands/st-maarten-denies-ms-braemar-request-to-allow-passengers-to-fly-out|title=St. Maarten denies 'MS Braemar' request to allow passengers to fly out|date=12 March 2020|website=The Daily Herald|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323010158/https://thedailyherald.sx/islands/st-maarten-denies-ms-braemar-request-to-allow-passengers-to-fly-out|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Cuba]] finally allowed the ship to dock and evacuated all travelers to the [[United Kingdom]] on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-infected-cruise-ship-stranded-sea-weeks-dock/story?id=69640092 |title=Coronavirus-infected cruise ship stranded at sea for weeks to dock in Cuba |date=17 March 2020 |website=ABC News |language=en |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317164151/https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-infected-cruise-ship-stranded-sea-weeks-dock/story?id=69640092 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== ''Ruby Princess'' ==\nFrom 15 March 2020, Australia banned cruise ships arriving from foreign ports. However, exemptions were granted to allow four ships, already en route to Australia, to dock and disembark its passengers. On 19 March 2020, {{ship||Ruby Princess}}, which was one of the four ships given the exemption, docked at the [[Overseas Passenger Terminal]] in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], after a cruise to New Zealand. The cruise ship was forced to return to Sydney early after some passengers reported respiratory problems, but when disembarking passengers were not told that anyone on board presented any symptoms during the voyage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12321712 |title=Covid 19 coronavirus: Ruby Princess mistake caused infection cases to explode |author=Vanessa Brown |date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144203/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12321712 |archive-date=2 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 March, it was announced that three passengers and a crew member of ''Ruby Princess'' had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/ruby-princess-advisory.html |title=Ruby Princess Advisory |publisher=Princess Cruises |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320052806/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/ruby-princess-advisory.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ship had docked in [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]], and the passengers had disembarked before the results came back positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/coronavirus-four-people-test-positive-for-covid19-after-ruby-princess-cruise/09f9951a-ec5e-4205-9fb8-87a6620ef6b3 |title=Four people test positive for COVID-19 after Ruby Princess cruise |last=Noble |first=Freya |work=9News.com.au |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320052808/https://www.9news.com.au/national/coronavirus-four-people-test-positive-for-covid19-after-ruby-princess-cruise/09f9951a-ec5e-4205-9fb8-87a6620ef6b3 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ship had returned to Sydney with 1,100 crew members and 2,700 passengers, and 13 people who were sick were tested for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6689361/positive-virus-tests-on-aust-nz-cruise/?cs=14231 |title=Positive virus tests on Aust-NZ cruise |work=The Canberra Times |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321044017/https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6689361/positive-virus-tests-on-aust-nz-cruise/?cs=14231 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, one person who was a passenger on the 8\u201319 March cruise aboard ''Ruby Princess'' died after a coronavirus diagnosis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.watoday.com.au/national/ruby-princess-passenger-dies-after-coronavirus-diagnosis-20200324-p54ddu.html |title=Ruby Princess passenger dies after coronavirus diagnosis |publisher=WA Today |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025057/https://www.watoday.com.au/national/ruby-princess-passenger-dies-after-coronavirus-diagnosis-20200324-p54ddu.html |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 30 March, at least 440 passengers (211 in New South Wales, 71 in South Australia, 70 in Queensland, 43 in Western Australia, 22 in the Australian Capital Territory, 18 in Victoria, three in Tasmania and two in the Northern Territory) had tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/31/more-than-400-coronavirus-cases-australia-total-ruby-princess-cruise-ship|title=More than 400 coronavirus cases \u2013 10% of Australia\u2019s total \u2013 are from Ruby Princess cruise ship|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331073816/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/31/more-than-400-coronavirus-cases-australia-total-ruby-princess-cruise-ship|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 31 March 2020, five of them had died, one in the Australian Capital Territory, two in Tasmania, one in New South Wales and one in Queenland.<ref name=\"seven2020-03-31\">{{cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-death-in-act-was-a-passenger-on-the-under-fire-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-c-901621|title=Coronavirus death in ACT was a passenger on the under-fire Ruby Princess cruise ship|publisher=[[Seven Network]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401011434/https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-death-in-act-was-a-passenger-on-the-under-fire-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-c-901621|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 2 April, the number of cases in New South Wales had risen to 337 passengers and 3 crew members, so total passenger cases in Australia had risen to at least 576 cases.<ref name=\"nswh-2-4-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) statistics|publisher=NSW Health|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404032526/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 4 April the total cases rose to 662 with 7 passengers have died.<ref name=\"Guardian-4-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/04/nsw-health-minister-defends-experts-who-handled-ruby-princess-coronavirus-outbreak|title=NSW health minister defends experts who handled Ruby Princess coronavirus outbreak|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Ben Smee|date=4 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404075508/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/04/nsw-health-minister-defends-experts-who-handled-ruby-princess-coronavirus-outbreak|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It is a ninth of the national total of 5,548 confirmed COVID-19 cases, increase from a tenth, five days before.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-australia/australia-coronavirus-cases-stable-cruise-ships-sent-home-idUSKBN21M030 |title=Australia coronavirus cases stable, cruise ships sent home |author=Lidia Kelly |date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404072916/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-australia/australia-coronavirus-cases-stable-cruise-ships-sent-home-idUSKBN21M030 |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> This did not include passengers who left Australia without being tested. Another three passengers from the ship were reported dead in New South Wales<ref name=\"ABC-5-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-health-reports-four-more-coronavirus-deaths/12122966|title=NSW coronavirus death toll rises, with three people dying after travelling on the Ruby Princess|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405073008/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-health-reports-four-more-coronavirus-deaths/12122966|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a fourth in Queensland<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/ruby-princess-cruise-coronavirus-deaths-investigated-nsw-police/12123212|title=Ruby Princess coronavirus deaths to be subject of criminal investigation by NSW Police homicide squad|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406112215/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/ruby-princess-cruise-coronavirus-deaths-investigated-nsw-police/12123212|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on 5 April.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster|title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405083311/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A man was reported to have died in Western Australian on 6 April.<ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-06/wa-fourth-coronavirus-death-at-royal-perth-hospital/12124280|title=WA coronavirus deaths rise to four as man from Ruby Princess dies of COVID-19 at Royal Perth Hospital|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406071212/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-06/wa-fourth-coronavirus-death-at-royal-perth-hospital/12124280|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> An additional death was announced in Tasmania on 7 April,<ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-07/coronavirus-tasmania-third-death/12127782 |title=Tasmanian man in his 80s becomes state's third coronavirus fatality|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> bringing total deaths to 13.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-05\"/><ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\"/><ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\"/> 11 cases of secondary transmission from people infected on the ship had been reported, which had not led to any deaths.<ref name=\"ABC-5-4-20\"/> \n\n[[Australian Border Force]] is responsible for [[passport control]] and customs, while the federal [[Department of Agriculture (Australia, 2019\u201320)|Department of Agriculture]] is responsible for [[biosecurity in Australia]] under the ''[[Biosecurity Act 2015]]''; however, it is up to each state's health department to prevent illness in the community. Responsibility for the breakdown in communications will be determined by a later enquiry.<ref name=davies>{{cite web | last=Davies | first=Anne | title=Finger-pointing over the Ruby Princess debacle won't help solve coronavirus crisis | website=the Guardian | date=25 March 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/finger-pointing-over-the-ruby-princess-debacle-wont-help-solve-coronavirus-crisis | access-date=1 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401204732/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/finger-pointing-over-the-ruby-princess-debacle-wont-help-solve-coronavirus-crisis | archive-date=1 April 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe ship was relocated to [[Port Kembla (seaport)|Port Kembla]] on 6 April. As of 8 April, the ship's crew of about 1,000 remained on-board, with 200 exhibiting flu-like symptoms; 18 had tested positive for COVID-19. The vessel remained in Australia but was expected to move to [[Bermuda]] seven days later. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> A criminal investigation was underway by [[New South Wales Police]] to determine why the ship had been permitted to dock, and passengers to disembark, without quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.police.nsw.gov.au/news/news_article?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGZWJpenByZC5wb2xpY2UubnN3Lmdvdi5hdSUyRm1lZGlhJTJGODQxMTMuaHRtbCZhbGw9MQ%3D%3D |title=Strike Force Bast underway to investigate actions surrounding Ruby Princess |date=8 April 2020 |publisher=NSW Government |access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> Investigators from Task Force Bast seized the vessel's \"black box\" recorder (similar to a [[Flight recorder]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==''Greg Mortimer''==\nOn 7 April 2020, ''[[Greg Mortimer (ship)|Greg Mortimer]]'' which holds up to 216 passengers was stranded in Uruguay for a week and asking for help after people exhibiting symptoms like fever cases which prompted authorities to ban them from disembarking.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/greg-mortimer-81-people-test-positive-for-covid-19-on-australian-cruise-ship-off-uruguay |title=Greg Mortimer: 81 people test positive for COVID-19 on Australian cruise ship off Uruguay |work=SBS News |last=Blakkarly |first=Jarni |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> After the Uruguayan medical teams boarded the cruise ship to test passengers on 1 April, 81 people tested positive for [[COVID-19]] with six people being evacuated and transferred to hospitals being seriously ill with the [[coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/more-than-80-passengers-on-board-greg-mortimer-cruise-ship-test-positive-for-covid-19-20200406-p54hk4.html |title=More than 80 passengers on board Greg Mortimer cruise ship test positive for COVID-19 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |last=Noyes |first=Jenny |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA news report on 8 April stated that the ship had not yet received permission to dock, although an evacuation flight to Australia and New Zealand was being arranged by Uruguayan authorities. By that time, 128 persons on the vessel had tested positive for COVID-19. Six had been transferred to a hospital in [[Montevideo]]. Passengers from Europe and America who had positive tests would not be allowed to travel to their home countries until their subsequent tests indicated negative results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/americas/greg-mortimer-cruise-ship-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Passengers to be evacuated from Antarctic cruise ship after almost 60% test positive for coronavirus |date=8 April 2020 |work=CNN |last=Griffiths |first=James |last2=Castillo |first2=Jackie |last-author-amp=y |access-date=8 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Other ships with confirmed cases on board ==\n<!-- ordered roughly by date of first positive test -->\n<!--each one can be moved to a dedicated section if serious enough. Do not leave blank lines between asterisked entries (see [[MOS:LISTBULLET]])-->\n\n=== ''Pullmantur Horizon'' ===\nA report on 4 April 2020 stated that this ship had roughly 150 persons who had tested positive for the COVID-19 virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://crew-center.com/ship-crew-news |title=Pullmantur Horizon Crew Reports COVID-19 Positive Cases Onboard |work=crew-center.com |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214111311/http://crew-center.com/ship-crew-news |archive-date=14 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Coral Princess'' ===\nNews reports in early April 2020 indicated that {{ship||Coral Princess}}, with 1,020 passengers and 878 crew, with some suffering flu-like symptoms, was hoping to be allowed to dock at [[Port Everglades]] in [[Fort Lauderdale]] to allow passengers to disembark. A news item on 2 April 2020 stated that \"Passengers have been confined to their rooms...when the company noticed a higher than normal number of flu-like cases on board\". Reports then specified that that \"out of 13 passengers and crew tested for COVID-19 on board the Coral Princess, 12 were positive.\" Officials in [[Broward County, Florida]] said that a plan was not yet in place to handle the situation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coral-princess-cruise-ship-12-183437177.html |title=Coral Princess cruise ship with 12 COVID-19 cases on board hopes to dock in Florida |last=Dolven |first=Taylor |work=Miami Herald |date=2 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 |via=Yahoo News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/canadian-passengers-covid-19-princess-coral-cruise-1.5520023 |title=Canadian passengers on virus-stricken Coral Princess cruise ship worry how they'll get home |work=CBC News |date=3 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403165915/https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/canadian-passengers-covid-19-princess-coral-cruise-1.5520023 |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Coral Princess'' was diverted and finally docked at the [[Port of Miami]] on the afternoon of 4 April with its over 1,000 passengers and 878 crew members. A ''CNN'' report that evening indicated that two passengers had died and some others were ill, including the 12 that had tested positive for COVID-19. Those who were not ill were to disembark when flights to their destinations were available; this was expected to take some days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/04/us/coral-princess-cruise-ship-docks-miami-coronavirus/index.html |title=Coral Princess docks in Miami with 2 dead and several ill of coronavirus, after ports shunned it for days |work=CNN |last=Hanna |first=Jason |last2=Alonso |first2=Melissa |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404230618/https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/04/us/coral-princess-cruise-ship-docks-miami-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A subsequent news report later that evening stated that four passengers were scheduled to be taken to Florida hospitals and added that 67 persons would not be allowed to disembark.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/after-two-deaths-on-board-coral-princess-cruise-ship-gets-miami-welcome/ar-BB12aMiq |title=After two deaths on board, Coral Princess cruise ship gets Miami welcome |last=Freeman |first=Marc |work=South Florida Sun-Sentinel |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 |via=MSN News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the death of a third passenger was announced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coral-princess-cruise-passenger-dies-of-coronavirus-after-disembarking-delay-daughter-says/ar-BB12a5w2?li=BBnb7Kz&fbclid=IwAR1cCisT0fx18h_kN8IsCkl3zHNfFBkim9yQOhb1XjzlQYpeidpF8DWG5EI |title=Coral Princess cruise passenger dies of coronavirus after disembarking delay, daughter says |agency=USA Today |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=6 April 2020 |work=MSN}}</ref> By that afternoon, 684 passengers had disembarked, those who needed medical care had been taken from the vessel and 274 were still on the ''Coral Princess''. Charter flights had departed to Canada, California, Australia and the United Kingdom; others were expected to leave Florida the next day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/coral-princess-coronavirus-disembarkation/index.html |title=Passengers on the Coral Princess cruise ship are still trying to get home |work=CNN |date=7 April 2020 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Costa Magica'' ===\nOn 12 March, two passengers aboard {{ship||Costa Magica}} were reported to be tested positively for COVID-19 while quarantined in [[Martinique]]. The ship that departed from Guadeloupe with 3,300 people on board had been disallowed entry in several sea ports including in [[Grenada]], [[Tobago]], [[Barbados]] and [[Saint Lucia]], due to over 300 Italian nationals on board.<ref>{{cite news |title=BREAKING NEWS: Two passengers on ship turned away from St. Lucia test positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-two-passengers-on-ship-turned-away-from-st-lucia-test-positive-for-coronavirus/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia News Online |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322184635/https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-two-passengers-on-ship-turned-away-from-st-lucia-test-positive-for-coronavirus/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAll the passengers were disembarked, and 930 crew members stayed aboard.<ref name=\"Costa_fox\" /> Eventually, the ship stopped {{convert|3|mi|spell=in}} offshore from Miami, and on 26 March, the U.S. Coast Guard reported evacuation of six sick crew members from ''Costa Magica''.<ref name=\"Costa_nbc\">{{cite news |last1=Massarelli |first1=Katelyn |title=Multiple sick crew members on Costa Magica, Costa Favolosa to be evacuated off Miami |url=https://www.nbc-2.com/story/41943042/multiple-sick-crew-members-on-costa-magica-costa-favolosa-to-be-evacuated-off-miami |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=NBC2 |date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327195430/https://www.nbc-2.com/story/41943042/multiple-sick-crew-members-on-costa-magica-costa-favolosa-to-be-evacuated-off-miami |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Costa_usatoday\">{{cite news |last1=Hines |first1=Morgan |title=Two Costa cruise ships to anchor with sick crew in Miami for 'life-critical' care |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/26/coronavirus-costa-magica-costa-favolosa-miami-sick-crew/2914625001/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=USA Today |date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326231246/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/26/coronavirus-costa-magica-costa-favolosa-miami-sick-crew/2914625001/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Costa_fox\">{{cite news |last1=Bartiromo |first1=Michael |title=2 Costa cruise ships heading toward Florida with dozens of sick crew members on board |url=https://www.foxnews.com/travel/2-costa-cruise-ships-toward-florida-sick-crew-members |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327002445/https://www.foxnews.com/travel/2-costa-cruise-ships-toward-florida-sick-crew-members |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Costa Favolosa'' ===\n{{ship||Costa Favolosa}} departed from Guadeloupe. Six of the disembarked occupants of the ship were tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"Costa_fox\" /> On 26 March, as the ship stopped three miles offshore from Miami, the U.S. Coast Guard reported evacuation of seven sick crew member, out of 1,009 who stayed aboard.<ref name=\"Costa_nbc\" /><ref name=\"Costa_usatoday\" /><ref name=\"Costa_fox\" />\n\n=== ''Costa Luminosa'' ===\nOn 8 March, an Italian woman was quarantined in the [[Unincorporated territories of the United States|U.S. Territory]] of [[Puerto Rico]] while being tested for the virus. She had arrived there via {{ship||Costa Luminosa}}, a cruise ship that had departed from [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], [[United States|U.S.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/puerto-rico-takes-preventative-measures-for-possible-case-of-covid-19/2202458/|title=Puerto Rico takes Preventative Measures for Possible Case of COVID-19|website=NBC 6 South Florida|language=en-US|access-date=9 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310151737/https://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/puerto-rico-takes-preventative-measures-for-possible-case-of-covid-19/2202458/|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 March she, her husband and a third person's tests came back positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/trespacientesarrojanpositivoacoronavirusenpuertorico-2552670/ |title=Tres pacientes arrojan positivo a coronavirus en Puerto Rico |language=Spanish |work=elnuevodia.com |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314173514/https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/trespacientesarrojanpositivoacoronavirusenpuertorico-2552670/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March the ship disembarked more than 350 passengers from the United States and Canada only at Marseille, France, using buses and then a chartered plane to fly them to Atlanta, Georgia without testing of COVID-19. While in flight, the results from those who were tested in Marseille were positive, so those who positive results were sat in separated seats. At Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport, the passengers met people with hazmat suits to check their body temperatures, perform visual assessment and ask if any have COVID-19 symptoms. Those without symptoms were to go to customs and then take their baggage. Several of the passengers became positive for COVID-19 later and some of them died.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/03/us/costa-luminosa-passengers-ordeal/index.html |title=A Florida man dies days after hundreds of people exposed to coronavirus walked around the world's busiest airport |first=Faith |last=Karimi |first2=Dianne |last2=Gallagher |date=3 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403171833/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/03/us/costa-luminosa-passengers-ordeal/index.html |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There are 36 confirmed cases of COVID-19 of those who disembarked from the ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ship-technology.com/news/covid-19-costa-luminosa-36-cases/ |title=Covid-19: Authorities confirm 36 coronavirus cases on Costa Luminosa |work=ship-technology.com |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324155745/https://www.ship-technology.com/news/covid-19-costa-luminosa-36-cases/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March local news in Puerto Rico reported the death of the woman, aged 68.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/fallecelaturistaitalianaquediopositivoacoronavirusenpuertorico-2554666/ |title=Fallece la turista italiana que dio positivo a coronavirus en Puerto Rico |trans-title=Italian tourist who tested positive for coronavirus dies in Puerto Rico |work=elnuevodia.com |language=Spanish |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322043327/https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/fallecelaturistaitalianaquediopositivoacoronavirusenpuertorico-2554666/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Costa Victoria'' ===\n{{ship||Costa Victoria}} left [[Dubai]] on 7 March 2020. A female Argentine national was tested positive and disembarked in [[Crete]]. 726 passengers were quarantined and managed to leave only after the ship docked in [[Civitavecchia]], near Rome, Italy on 25 March.<ref name=\"Victoria_thelocal\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Fears on cruise ship docked at Italian port after case confirmed |url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200325/coronavirus-fears-on-cruise-ship-docked-in-rome-after-case-confirmed |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=The Local Italy |agency=AFP |date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327192655/https://www.thelocal.it/20200325/coronavirus-fears-on-cruise-ship-docked-in-rome-after-case-confirmed |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Messurier |first1=Danielle |title=West Live: Perth couple stranded on Costa Victoria cruise ship where COVID-19 case confirmed |url=https://thewest.com.au/news/coronavirus/west-live-perth-couple-stranded-on-costa-victoria-cruise-ship-where-covid-19-case-confirmed-ng-b881500084z |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326163115/https://thewest.com.au/news/coronavirus/west-live-perth-couple-stranded-on-costa-victoria-cruise-ship-where-covid-19-case-confirmed-ng-b881500084z |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Silver Shadow'' ===\n[[Silversea Cruises]] ship {{ship||Silver Shadow|ship|2}} was blocked from disembarking its 608 passengers and crew at the port of [[Recife]] in [[Brazil]], as a 78-year-old Canadian aboard had been suspected of having the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Idoso passa mal em cruzeiro, e navio com centenas de pessoas atracado no Recife \u00e9 isolado por suspeita de coronav\u00edrus |url=https://g1.globo.com/pe/pernambuco/noticia/2020/03/12/idoso-passa-mal-em-cruzeiro-e-navio-com-centenas-de-pessoas-ancorado-no-recife-e-isolado-por-suspeita-de-coronavirus.ghtml |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[Rede Globo|globo.com]] |date=12 March 2020 |language=pt-br |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318015329/https://g1.globo.com/pe/pernambuco/noticia/2020/03/12/idoso-passa-mal-em-cruzeiro-e-navio-com-centenas-de-pessoas-ancorado-no-recife-e-isolado-por-suspeita-de-coronavirus.ghtml |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two passengers were later medically disembarked, and one of them tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"ship-silver-explorer\"/>\n\n=== ''Silver Explorer'' ===\n{{ship||Silver Explorer}} docked in [[Castro, Chile]], with 111 passengers and 120 crew, after an 83-year-old man fell ill and tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"ship-silver-explorer\"/>\n\n=== ''Zaandam'' ===\nThe [[Holland America Line|Holland America]] cruise ship {{MS|Zaandam||2}} was stranded off the coast of Chile after being denied entry to ports since 14 March. Of the 1,829 people (1,243 passengers, 586 crew) aboard, 13 passengers and 29 crew members fell ill with \"flu-like symptoms\".<ref name=\"Zaandam_CBC_1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cruise-ship-holland-america-covid-19-canadians-1.5506674 |title='Get us the hell off': Canadians on board stranded cruise ship with 42 sick passengers, crew |last=Harris |first=Sophia |work=CBC News |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323210317/https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cruise-ship-holland-america-covid-19-canadians-1.5506674 |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The vessel sailed for [[Port Everglades, Florida]] hoping to dock on 30 March with a total of 77 sick persons aboard as of 24 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/tourism-cruises/article241457871.html |title=A cruise ship with 77 sick on board hopes to dock in Port Everglades on March 30 |work=Miami Herald |last=Dolven |first=Taylor |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401202532/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/tourism-cruises/article241457871.html |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Four passengers died while waiting for permission to transit the [[Panama Canal]], while the number of sick aboard climbed to 148.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bradenton.com/news/coronavirus/article241559956.html |last=Harris |first=Alex |title=Four passengers died on Zaandam cruise ship with 148 people sick with flu-like symptoms |work=Bradenton Herald |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327200326/https://www.bradenton.com/news/coronavirus/article241559956.html |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two passengers tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/zaandam-cruise-ship-passengers-holland-america-deaths-1.5512490 |title=4 passengers die on stranded cruise ship carrying 247 Canadians |work=CBC News |last=Harris |first=Sophia |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327175937/https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/zaandam-cruise-ship-passengers-holland-america-deaths-1.5512490 |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, on 27 March, the ship was denied transit through the Panama Canal due to the number of sick people on board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=53903&SEO=zaandam-cruise-ship-denied-crossing-panama-canal-due-to-quarantine |title=Zaandam cruise ship denied crossing Panama Canal due to quarantine |work=Prensa Latina |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329070829/https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=53903&SEO=zaandam-cruise-ship-denied-crossing-panama-canal-due-to-quarantine |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 28 March 2020, both ''Zaandam'' and the accompanying vessel ''Rotterdam'' were cleared by the Panama Department of Health to transit through the Panama Canal towards their destination in Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get permission to transit Panama Canal |work=USA Today |date=28 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329000223/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Anchored {{convert|8|mi|spell=in|order=flip}} off the coast, on 28 March asymptomic passengers and some medical staff were transferred from ''Zaandam'' to ''Rotterdam.'' 53 guests and 85 crew members aboard ''Zaandam'' reported flu-like symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52072703?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world/latin_america&link_location=live-reporting-story |title=Coronavirus: Cruise ship off Panama coast transfers passengers |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405090223/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52072703?intlink_from_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.com%2Fnews%2Fworld%2Flatin_america&link_location=live-reporting-story |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 31 March 2020, the number reported as being \"ill\" had increased to 193.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=31 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331095439/https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Rotterdam'' followed ''Zaandam'' on its way to Florida. An unstated number of passengers from ''Zaandam'' were transferred to the second vessel on 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get OK to transit Panama Canal for Florida |last=Hines |first=Morgan |date=28 March 2020 |work=USA Today |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330022237/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/zaandam-cruise-ship-sick-passengers/index.html |title=A cruise ship headed to Florida has reported more sick people on board after 4 die and 2 test positive for Covid-19 |date=30 March 2020 |work=CNN |last=Silverman |first=Hollie |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330083610/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/zaandam-cruise-ship-sick-passengers/index.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At that time, the crew of ''Zaandam'' included four physicians and four nurses while ''Rotterdam'' had two physicians and four nurses.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/28/passengers-on-cruise-ship-in-panama-transferred-to-new-vessel.html |title=Passengers on cruise ship in Panama transferred to new vessel |date=28 March 2020 |last=Winsa |first=Patty |work=Toronto Star |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330054951/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/28/passengers-on-cruise-ship-in-panama-transferred-to-new-vessel.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of 30 March 2020, Holland America had not received permission to dock either vessel at Port Everglades in Fort Lauderdale as planned. According to an [[Associated Press]] report, the city's mayor, Dean Trantalis, \"said he didn't want the ship to dock near his city, at least without extensive precautions\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wfla.com/community/health/coronavirus/authority-stranded-ships-begin-transiting-panama-canal/ |title=Authority: Stranded ships begin transiting Panama Canal |date=30 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |work=WFLA News Channel 8 |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331153439/https://www.wfla.com/community/health/coronavirus/authority-stranded-ships-begin-transiting-panama-canal/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nealdolven>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article241605286.html |title=Fort Lauderdale mayor not ready to accept the coronavirus-hit Zaandam at Port Everglades |date=30 March 2020 |last=Neal |first=David J. |last2=Dolven |first2=Taylor |last-author-amp=y |work=Miami Herald |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406070837/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article241605286.html |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The governor of Florida was also hesitant to accept ''Zaandam'' at Fort Lauderdale because the state already had so much to deal with during the pandemic; as of 31 March 2020, a decision had not yet been made. The president of Holland America made a public plea for acceptance of the ship and expressed concern that various ports in several countries had been reluctant to provide provisions and medical supplies.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=CBC News |access-date=31 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331095439/https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPresident Donald Trump said on 1 April 2020 that \"we have to help the people\" [on the ships] and that discussions were underway about [[Canada]] and the [[United Kingdom]] \"arranging flights to retrieve their citizens from the ship\". News reports on 2 April stated that the ships would be allowed to dock at Port Everglades that afternoon. The cruise line was making arrangements for passengers who fit to travel from other countries to leave via chartered aircraft, directly from the ship to bus and then to airplane.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/cruise-ship-sick-passengers-sister-ship-will-be-allowed-dock-n1174796 |title=Cruise ship with sick passengers and sister ship will be allowed to dock in Florida |last=Burke |first=Minyvonne |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162022/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/cruise-ship-sick-passengers-sister-ship-will-be-allowed-dock-n1174796 |archive-date=2 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> From the 442 passengers on ''Zaandam'' and 808 passengers on ''Rotterdam'' there are 107 passengers and 143 crew from 1,186 crew that had influenza-like symptoms, those who had mild symptoms were quarantined in staterooms, and will be released later. All crew, no matter their condition, must stay on board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/news/coronavirus-hit-ships-finally-dock-in-port-everglades/ |title=Coronavirus-hit cruise ships finally permitted to disembark healthy passengers in Florida |author=Katherine Lawrey |date=April 3, 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404142455/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/news/coronavirus-hit-ships-finally-dock-in-port-everglades/ |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA report on 4 April stated that \"14 critically ill people\" were taken to area hospitals while the others were allowed to disembark when flights to their destinations were available.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bnd.com/news/article241769916.html |title=Another cruise ship with virus victims docks in Florida |work=Belleville News-Democrat |last=Anderson |first=Curt |agency=Associated Press |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406070847/https://www.bnd.com/news/article241769916.html |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''Artania''===\n{{ship|MV|Artania||2}} docked at [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] in Western Australia on 27 March. Most of the 850 passengers flew home from [[Perth]] to Germany on 28\u201329 March. 41 passengers and crew tested positive to COVID-19 and are being treated in Perth hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/2c7aac9cd9ac8d6d78f599a5f218d06b |title=Australia prepares to fly cruise passengers to Germany |agency=Associated Press |date=27 March  2020 |access-date=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328203735/https://apnews.com/2c7aac9cd9ac8d6d78f599a5f218d06b |archive-date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ABC-30-3-2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-29/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-on-artania-cruise-ship-top-41/12101342|title=Coronavirus patients from Artania cruise ship sent to Joondalup hospital after 29 new COVID-19 positive tests|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401063505/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-29/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-on-artania-cruise-ship-top-41/12101342|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 1 April, the ship had 450 crew and about a dozen passengers on board. The Australian Government directed ''Artania'' to leave port, but the ship demanded to stay another 14 days, presumably so that they could be treated if COVID-19 symptoms developed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-01/coronavirus-cruise-ship-artania-refusing-to-leave-fremantle-port/12110206|title=Coronavirus cruise ship Artania refuses to leave WA port of Fremantle in letter to Australian Border Force|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401025756/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-01/coronavirus-cruise-ship-artania-refusing-to-leave-fremantle-port/12110206|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[Attorney-General for Australia|Australian Attorney-General]], [[Christian Porter]], \"there are still 12 passengers on board some of whom are very unwell. And their level of either illness or frailty is such that they cannot get in a plane.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youngwitness.com.au/story/6707149/unwell-on-covid-infected-cruise-ship-in-wa/?cs=9397|title=Unwell on COVID-infected cruise ship in WA|newspaper=The Young Witness|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Ovation of the Seas''===\nIn March 2020 thousands of passengers were ordered to self-isolate after disembarking from {{ship||Ovation of the Seas||2}} in [[Sydney]], Australia on 18 March due to [[COVID-19]] fears.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/cruise-passengers-not-tested-for-coronavirus-before-disembarking/12081426 |title=Thousands of cruise ship passengers told to self-isolate due to coronavirus days after disembarking |last=Farrell |first=Paul |last2=McDonald |first2=Alex |last-author-amp=y |work=[[Australian Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010855/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/cruise-passengers-not-tested-for-coronavirus-before-disembarking/12081426 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 79 passengers subsequently tested positively for the virus. As of 1 April, the ship was located off the coast of [[New South Wales]]. The [[International Transport Workers' Federation]] had called on the Australian government to allow the crew members to be disembarked so that could be flown to their countries of residence.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-01\"/> \n\nThe ship departed Australia on 4 April 2020 with its crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |date=5 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=At least 11 passengers from ship have now died, more than 30% of Australia's total Covid-19 deaths |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405083311/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''Voyager of the Seas''===\nPassengers disembarked from {{ship||Voyager of the Seas||2}} in [[Sydney]], Australia on 18 March.<ref name=\"ferrell1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/cruise-passengers-not-tested-for-coronavirus-before-disembarking/12081426 |title=Thousands of cruise ship passengers told to self-isolate due to coronavirus days after disembarking |last=Ferrell |first=Paul |last2=McDonald |first2=Alex |last-author-amp=y |work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]].net |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010855/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/cruise-passengers-not-tested-for-coronavirus-before-disembarking/12081426 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[Toowoomba]], Queensland man was infected on the ship and was sent into intensive care unit of a Toowoomba hospital after disembarking but died.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-25/queensland-man-dies-from-coronavirus-covid-19/12090804 |title=Coronavirus claims life of Toowoomba man infected on cruise ship who was allowed to travel home |work=ABC.net |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205344/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-25/queensland-man-dies-from-coronavirus-covid-19/12090804 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 April 34 passengers and 5 crew members had tested positively for the virus in New South Wales alone.<ref name=\"nswhealth-2-4-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) statistics - News|last=|first=|date=2020-04-02|website=NSW Health|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404032526/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|archive-date=4 April 2020|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThe ship departed Australia on 4 April 2020 with its crew.<ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |date=5 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=At least 11 passengers from ship have now died, more than 30% of Australia\u2019s total Covid-19 deaths |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405083311/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''Celebrity Solstice''===\n{{ship||Celebrity Solstice||2}} disembarked its passengers in [[Sydney]], Australia on 20 March.<ref name=\"ferrell1\"/> On 2 April 11 cases had tested positively for the virus in New South Wales alone.<ref name=\"nswhealth-2-4-2020\"/>\n\nThe ship left Australia during the weekend of 4 April 2020 with its crew as did four other vessels.<ref name=\"theguardian2\"/>\n\n== Ships without confirmed cases on board ==\n<!--each one can be moved to a dedicated section if serious enough. Do not leave blank lines between asterisked entries (see [[MOS:LISTBULLET]])-->\n\n=== Suspected cases ===\n<!-- ordered alphabetically. (Wouldn't chronological order be better?) -->\n* {{ship||AIDAmira}}: Six passengers on the ship were isolated, after flying on a plane with a sailor who later tested positive with the virus. More than 1,700 are now trapped on the cruise ship, docked at [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title= 1,700 trapped on Cape Town cruise ship in Covid-19 drama|url= https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-17-1700-trapped-on-cape-town-cruise-ship-in-covid-19-drama/|website= The Sunday Times|date= 18 March 2020|access-date= 18 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200318012422/https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-17-1700-trapped-on-cape-town-cruise-ship-in-covid-19-drama/|archive-date= 18 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref>\n* {{ship||Costa Diadema}}: On 24 March 2020, the ship docked at [[Limassol]], [[Cyprus]], and a crew member suspected of suffering from the coronavirus was taken to hospital. Several other crew members were also reported to be ill. ''Costa Diadema'' was sailing from Dubai to [[Savona]], Italy, without passengers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: crew member from Italian cruise liner taken to Limassol hospital |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2020/03/24/coronavirus-crew-member-from-italian-cruise-liner-taken-to-limassol-hospital/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=CyprusMail |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship||Golden Princess|2000|2}}: At least three passengers have been quarantined by the ship's doctor, according to local health officials. It was en route for [[Melbourne]] on 18 March 2020.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Multiple cruise ships are left stranded as coronavirus cases increase |url=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/cruise-ships-stranded-coronavirus-trnd/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |first=Christina |last=Zdanowicz |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327213136/https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/cruise-ships-stranded-coronavirus-trnd/index.html |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 1 April 2020, it was docked in Melbourne.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-01\"/>\n* {{MV|Mahabaahu||2}}: Several passengers and crew members were quarantined after an American passenger who have traveled in the ship in [[Brahmaputra River]] in [[Assam]], [[India]] was tested positive in [[Bhutan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/foreign-tourists-in-assam-face-hassles-amid-fear-of-coronavirus-spread/story-v8QyfMjs39BOKCZthcL7mJ.html|title=Foreign tourists in Assam face hassles amid fear of coronavirus spread|date=13 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320083931/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/foreign-tourists-in-assam-face-hassles-amid-fear-of-coronavirus-spread/story-v8QyfMjs39BOKCZthcL7mJ.html|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guwahatiplus.com/daily-news/coronavirus-outbreak-crew-passengers-of-m-v-mahabaahu-quarantined|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Crew, Passengers of M V Mahabaahu Quarantined|website=G Plus|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320083932/https://www.guwahatiplus.com/daily-news/coronavirus-outbreak-crew-passengers-of-m-v-mahabaahu-quarantined|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[File:MSC Magnifica and MV Seabourn Encore anchored at Garden Island, Western Australia, March 2020.jpg|thumb|''MSC Magnifica'' and MV ''Seabourn Encore'' anchored off the coast of Western Australia]]{{ship||MSC Magnifica}}: More than 250 suspected cases are on board. As of 23 March 2020, the ship was heading for [[Fremantle]], [[Australia]] to disembark patients to hospitals and isolation.<ref>{{cite web|title= Cruise ship with more than 250 suspected COVID-19 patients steams for Fremantle|url= https://www.watoday.com.au/national/western-australia/cruise-ship-with-more-than-250-suspected-covid-19-patients-steams-for-fremantle-20200323-p54cym.html|website= WA Today|date= 23 March 2020|access-date= 23 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200323025439/https://www.watoday.com.au/national/western-australia/cruise-ship-with-more-than-250-suspected-covid-19-patients-steams-for-fremantle-20200323-p54cym.html|archive-date= 23 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> Later that day, the cruise ship was denied entry into Australia.<ref>{{cite web |title= WA resists cruise ship with sick on board |url= https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6691294/wa-resists-cruise-ship-with-sick-on-board/?cs=14264 |website= The Canberra Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The ship was subsequently denied entry to Dubai and as of 25 March continued to be in the Perth area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/passengers-to-be-quarantined-on-rottnest-island-as-cruise-ship-disaster-looms|title=Three cruise ships are proving a nightmare for the WA government, with two forced to stay at anchor, while 800 passengers on a third will be quarantined|newspaper=[[SBS (Australian TV channel)|SBS]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402003937/https://www.sbs.com.au/news/passengers-to-be-quarantined-on-rottnest-island-as-cruise-ship-disaster-looms|archive-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== No currently suspected cases ===\n<!-- ordered alphabetically -->\n* {{ship||AIDAaura}}: The German cruise ship ''AIDAaura'', with about 1,200 people on board, was held on 3 March 2020 in the harbour of [[Haugesund]], [[Norway]], while two asymptomatic German passengers were tested who had been in contact with a person who subsequently developed COVID-19; their test results were negative.<ref name=berliner>{{cite web|url=https://www.morgenpost.de/vermischtes/article228600469/Coronavirus-Corona-Kreuzfahrtschiffe-Ministerium-warnt-Deutsche-vor-Kreuzfahrten.html|title=Coronavirus: Au\u00dfenministerium warnt Deutsche vor Kreuzfahrten|language=German|trans-title=Coronavirus: crisis team advises against cruises|newspaper=Berliner Morgenpost|author=|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306052600/https://www.morgenpost.de/vermischtes/article228600469/Coronavirus-Corona-Kreuzfahrtschiffe-Ministerium-warnt-Deutsche-vor-Kreuzfahrten.html|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20200303/coronavirus-german-cruise-ship-held-in-norwegian-harbour-as-passengers-tested|title=Coronavirus: German cruise ship held in Norwegian harbour as passengers tested|author=|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=3 March 2020|newspaper=The Local De|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303133842/https://www.thelocal.de/20200303/coronavirus-german-cruise-ship-held-in-norwegian-harbour-as-passengers-tested|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{ship||Carnival Panorama}}: On 7 March 2020, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) halted passengers disembarking from the cruise ship ''Carnival Panorama'' docked at [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] Cruise Terminal in California when a female passenger was reported to be sick.<ref name=\"lbpost.1\">{{cite web |title=UPDATE: Coronavirus test comes back negative \u2022 Long Beach Post News |url=https://lbpost.com/news/cdc-coronavirus-cruise-ship-testing-carnival-panorama |website=lbpost.com |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121351/https://lbpost.com/news/cdc-coronavirus-cruise-ship-testing-carnival-panorama |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The sick passenger was transported to a hospital to be tested, and all passengers were held on board the ship pending test results.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official City Statement from the City of Long Beach Regarding Carnival Cruise Ship |url=http://longbeach.gov/press-releases/official-city-statement-from-the-city-of-long-beach-regarding-carnival-cruise-ship/ |website=longbeach.gov |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403230813/http://longbeach.gov/press-releases/official-city-statement-from-the-city-of-long-beach-regarding-carnival-cruise-ship/ |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Twitter-1236401838682804225>{{cite web |url= https://mobile.twitter.com/LongBeachCity/status/1236401838682804225 |work= @LongBeachCity |author= City of Long Beach |date= 7 March 2020 |publisher= Twitter |title= 1236401838682804225 }}</ref>  The test came back negative late that evening, and disembarkation was scheduled to resume the next morning.<ref name=\"lbpost.1\" /> ''Carnival Panorama'' was returning from a trip to Mexico with scheduled stops at [[Cabo San Lucas]], [[Mazatl\u00e1n]] and [[Puerto Vallarta]], which were also scheduled stops for ''Grand Princess'' during the previous month.<ref name=\"lbpost.1\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Carnival Cruises 2019\u20132020 |url=https://www.carnivalcruiseline.is/sites/default/uploads/catalogue/CCL_2019_2020_Katalog_IS/mobile/index.html#p=39 |website=carnivalcruiseline.is |pages=38\u201339 |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331185318/https://www.carnivalcruiseline.is/sites/default/uploads/catalogue/CCL_2019_2020_Katalog_IS/mobile/index.html#p=39 |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"brochure\" />\n* {{ship||Costa neoRomantica}}: On 26 March 2020, the ship with no passengers on board, previously quarantined at [[Nagasaki]], [[Japan]], anchored at the roadstead  of [[Vladivostok]], [[Russia]] to refresh the ship with water, fuel, and food. However, it was denied entrance as the [[Rospotrebnadzor|Russian sanitary officials]] stipulated the dock workers to be quarantined for 14 days. No COVID-19 cases on board were reported.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041b\u0430\u0439\u043d\u0435\u0440 Costa Neoromantica \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0431\u044b\u043b \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \"\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\" |url=https://primpress.ru/article/51980 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=PrimPress |date=26 March 2020 |language=ru |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327190554/https://primpress.ru/article/51980 |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0412\u043e \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0443 Costa Neoromantica \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0442\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d |url=https://ria.ru/20200326/1569162758.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=RIA Novosti |date=26 March 2020 |language=ru |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327215010/https://ria.ru/20200326/1569162758.html |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* {{ship||Costa Fortuna}}: The Italian cruise ship ''Costa Fortuna'' attempted to dock at [[Phuket Province|Phuket]], [[Thailand]], on 6 March 2020, but was denied by Thai officials because it was carrying passengers who had left Italy within the past two weeks.<ref name=\"costa.fortuna.1\">{{cite web |last1=Corcoran |first1=Kieran |title=An Italian cruise ship was turned away from ports in Malaysia and Thailand even though it has no cases of coronavirus on board |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-costa-fortuna-cruise-ship-denied-by-malaysia-thailand-ports-2020-3 |website=Business Insider |date=7 March 2020 |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308200609/https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-costa-fortuna-cruise-ship-denied-by-malaysia-thailand-ports-2020-3 |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 7 March, the ship attempted to dock at [[Penang]] in northern [[Malaysia]], but was denied pursuant to a complete ban on cruise ships.<ref name=\"costa.fortuna.1\" /> The vessel docked in Singapore on 10 March and the passengers disembarked, with some being bused directly to the airport. There were no confirmed cases of COVID-19 aboard the ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coronavirus-covid-19-costa-fortuna-cruise-dock-12520634 |title=Costa Fortuna cruise ship docks in Singapore; some passengers immediately bussed to airport |work=Channel News Asia |last2=Kit |first2=Tang See |last=Mahmud |first=Aqil Haziq |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325153759/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coronavirus-covid-19-costa-fortuna-cruise-dock-12520634 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||Costa Serena}}: Fifteen passengers aboard ''Costa Serena'' on 24 January were suspected to have SARS-CoV-2. The ship arrived at its destination, [[Tianjin]], [[China]], on 25 January. With 17 suspected cases, and 146 (of 3,706) passengers from [[Hubei province]] where the disease originated, an emergency was declared. The cruise ship was locked down for 19 hours before the passengers were allowed to disembark; no confirmed cases were found.<ref name=CGTN-20200226>{{cite news |url= https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-02-26/The-fate-of-the-three-cruise-ships-amidst-the-global-COVID-19-outbreak-OoJQnnSgaQ/index.html |title= The fate of the three cruise ships amidst the global COVID-19 outbreak |publisher= China Global Television Network |agency= CGTN |access-date= 28 February 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200228004443/https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-02-26/The-fate-of-the-three-cruise-ships-amidst-the-global-COVID-19-outbreak-OoJQnnSgaQ/index.html |archive-date= 28 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||Costa Smeralda|ship|2}}: In January, ''Costa Smeralda'' and her 6,000 passengers were quarantined at the port of [[Civitavecchia]] in [[Rome]], [[Italy]], following two suspected cases.<ref name=\"corona\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/30/6000-passengers-stuck-on-cruise-ship-in-italy-over-coronavirus-fears |title=6,000 passengers stuck on cruise ship in Italy over coronavirus fears |website=theguardian.com |accessdate=30 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130145634/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/30/6000-passengers-stuck-on-cruise-ship-in-italy-over-coronavirus-fears |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A spokesperson from Costa Cruises stated that a 54-year-old woman aboard the ship was suffering from a fever and that she and her husband were both being tested. They were found to be uninfected, and passengers were allowed to go on shore the next day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/30/asia/wuhan-coronavirus-update-china-spread-intl-hnk/index.html|title=7,000 held on cruise ship in Italy as global fears spread over coronavirus|author1=James Griffiths|author2=Angela Dewan|author3=Gianluca Mezzofiore|author4=Livia Borghese|website=CNN|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130111950/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/30/asia/wuhan-coronavirus-update-china-spread-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{ship||Grandeur of the Seas}}: On 12 March 2020, ''Grandeur of the Seas'' was denied a request to berth at the [[Transportation in the United States Virgin Islands#Cruise ships|Austin \"Babe\" Monsanto Marine Terminal]] in the [[United States Virgin Islands]] because a crew member had  travelled to Japan within the previous two weeks, even though no confirmed cases of coronavirus were on board.<ref name=\"vipa\">{{cite web |url=https://doh.vi.gov/news/vipa-confirms-coast-guard-denied-entry-grandeur-seas-cruise-ship |title=VIPA Confirms That Coast Guard Denied Entry To Grandeur Of The Seas Cruise Ship |publisher=United States Virgin Islands Department of Health |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315192801/https://doh.vi.gov/news/vipa-confirms-coast-guard-denied-entry-grandeur-seas-cruise-ship |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/22587-virgin-islands-deny-grandeur-of-the-seas-call.html |title=Virgin Islands Deny Grandeur of the Seas Call |work=Cruise Industry News |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222945/https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/22587-virgin-islands-deny-grandeur-of-the-seas-call.html |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The ship, however, was eventually allowed to return to transport a seriously-injured passenger to a hospital for treatment.<ref name=\"vipa\" />\n* {{MS|Europa|1999|2}}: The ship docked in [[Purta Vallarta]], Mexico. The government announced on 25 March that it would receive cruise ships \u201cfor humanitarian reasons,\u201d but that passengers would be individually \"fumigated\" before being taken directly to airports to be returned to their home countries. The protocol would apply to ''Europa'' and other ships in Mexican waters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/01aea6b6217f0464be47180c27af389f |title=Mexico will receive cruise ships, but fumigate passengers |agency=Associated Press |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328225325/https://apnews.com/01aea6b6217f0464be47180c27af389f |archive-date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship|MS|Maasdam||2}}: 842 guests and 542 crew members from Holland America Line's ''Maasdam'' were not allowed to disembark in [[Honolulu]] on 19 March 2020.<ref name=honolulu>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/despite-no-reported-coronavirus-hawaii-wont-let-cruise-155328921--abc-news-topstories.html |title=Despite no reported coronavirus, Hawaii won't let cruise ship passengers disembark |first=Christina |last=Carrega |work=ABC News |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |via=Yahoo News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320214237/https://news.yahoo.com/despite-no-reported-coronavirus-hawaii-wont-let-cruise-155328921--abc-news-topstories.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{MS|Marco Polo||2}}: Kenyan authorities screened passengers on ''Marco Polo'' for coronavirus when the cruise ship docked at [[Mombasa]] on 13 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news | title= Cruise ship docks in Mombasa, passengers cleared of coronavirus | url= https://www.kbc.co.ke/cruise-ship-docks-in-mombasa-passengers-cleared-of-coronavirus/ | work= KBC Channel | publisher= Kenya Broadcasting Corporation | publication-date= 13 February 2020 | agency= Kenya News Agency | access-date= 30 March 2020 | quote= The Port of Mombasa Thursday morning welcomed a cruise ship christened 'Ms Marco Polo with 575 passengers and 346 crew members on board. [...] Kenya Ports Authority managing director Daniel Manduku [...] said that the port health department has taken measures to screen all passengers before disembarking from the ship in order to avert entry of diseases such as coronavirus which has greatly affected China. | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200214180454/https://www.kbc.co.ke/cruise-ship-docks-in-mombasa-passengers-cleared-of-coronavirus/ | archive-date= 14 February 2020 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n* {{ship|MS|Monarch||2}}: On 14 March, Panama repatriated 1,504 Colombian tourists from the cruise ship ''Monarch.'' Since the port of [[Cartagena, Colombia]] is closed, the people have to fly from [[Col\u00f3n, Panama]]. About 300 people were still waiting to buy tickets.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mundo/panam%c3%a1-repatria-a-turistas-de-crucero-por-nuevo-coronavirus/ar-BB11c7oo |trans-title=Panama repatriates cruise tourists for new coronavirus |title=Panam\u00e1 repatria a turistas de crucero por nuevo coronavirus |language=Spanish |work=AFP/MSN Noticias |date=14 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315170847/https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mundo/panam%c3%a1-repatria-a-turistas-de-crucero-por-nuevo-coronavirus/ar-BB11c7oo |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||MSC Meraviglia}}: On 26 February, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico|Mexican]] authorities granted permission for ''MSC Meraviglia'', registered in [[Malta]], to dock in [[Cozumel]], Quintana Roo, because she carried a passenger presumed to be infected with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]]. The ship was previously denied access to ports in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jamaica|Jamaica]] and the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Cayman Islands|Cayman Islands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/msc-meraviglia-cruise-ship-dock-cozumel-mexico-despite-coronavirus-fears |title=MSC Meraviglia cruise ship to dock in Cozumel, Mexico despite coronavirus fears |work=El Universal (English) |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023755/https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/msc-meraviglia-cruise-ship-dock-cozumel-mexico-despite-coronavirus-fears |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two cases of common seasonal flu were found.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/mexico-no-coronavirus-on-msc-meraviglia |title=Mexico: No Coronavirus on MSC Meraviglia |work=The Maritime Executive |date=29 February 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320213241/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/mexico-no-coronavirus-on-msc-meraviglia |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||Norwegian Jewel}}: The cruise ship was stranded in the middle of the Pacific Ocean, after being denied entry into [[Papeete]], [[French Polynesia]] and [[Lautoka]], [[Fiji]], due to fears of possible infection.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> On 19 March the 1,700 passengers were prevented from disembarking in [[Honolulu]].<ref name=honolulu /> On 23 March, the passengers were allowed to disembark in Honolulu in order to catch chartered flights to return to the home locations. There were no confirmed cases of COVID-19 aboard ''Norwegian Jewel''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/23/breaking-news/norwegian-jewel-cruise-ship-passengers-disembark-at-honolulu-harbor-bused-to-airport/ |title=Norwegian Jewel cruise ship passengers disembark at Honolulu Harbor, bused to airport |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |last=Sinco Kelleher |first=Jennifer |agency=Associated Press |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324154109/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/23/breaking-news/norwegian-jewel-cruise-ship-passengers-disembark-at-honolulu-harbor-bused-to-airport/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||Pacific Princess}}: Though there have been no confirmed cases on board, the ship has been rejected to dock at numerous destinations including [[Bali]], [[Singapore]], [[Phuket Province|Phuket, Thailand]], and [[Sri Lanka]]. The ship was as at 20 March 2020 en route to an uncertain future for [[Fremantle]], [[Australia]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n* {{ship||Regal Princess|2013|2}}: On 7 March, two crew members of ''Regal Princess'' were tested and the docking of the ship at [[Port Everglades]] in [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], [[United States|U.S.]], was delayed for about a day while waiting for test results. The tests were negative, and the crew did not have respiratory complications, so the ship was allowed to dock.\n* {{ship||Royal Princess|2012|2}}: As a crew member from ''Grand Princess'' had transferred to ''Royal Princess'' fifteen days earlier, the CDC issued a \"no-sail order\" for ''Royal Princess'' on 8 March 2020, prompting Princess Cruises to cancel the ship's seven-day cruise to Mexico before it departed Los Angeles.<ref name=\"brochure\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Cruise out of Port of LA canceled after CDC issues 'no-sail order' over coronavirus concerns |url=https://abc7.com/health/cruise-out-of-port-of-la-canceled-after-cdc-issues-no-sail-order/5995426/ |website=ABC7 Los Angeles |language=en |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309151545/https://abc7.com/health/cruise-out-of-port-of-la-canceled-after-cdc-issues-no-sail-order/5995426/ |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Munguia |first1=Hayley |title=Finally! Cruise passengers eagerly disembark the Carnival Panorama in Long Beach |url=https://www.presstelegram.com/2020/03/08/finally-cruise-passengers-eagerly-disembark-the-carnival-panorama-in-long-beach/ |website=Press Telegram |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309014610/https://www.presstelegram.com/2020/03/08/finally-cruise-passengers-eagerly-disembark-the-carnival-panorama-in-long-beach/ |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{ship||Sun Princess}}: Princess Cruises ship ''Sun Princess'' was not allowed to dock at a port in [[Madagascar]] on 13 February 2020, as it had visited Thailand less than 14 days before. The ship docked at the French island of [[R\u00e9union]] on 1 March, but passengers were met by a crowd of about 30 who insisted that the passengers be tested and tried to prevent them from leaving the port area. Objects were thrown at passengers, and the police deployed tear gas. Princess Cruises said that there was no evidence of SARS-CoV-2 on the ship.<ref name=sun/>\n* {{ship||Vasco da Gama|ship|2}}: The cruise ship docked in [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] in late March 2020. Almost 100 New Zealand passengers were flown from [[Perth]] on 29 March and arrived in [[Auckland]] on 30 March. As of 31 March, about 200 West Australian passengers were to be ferried to [[Rottnest Island]], which had been converted to a quarantine zone. Another 600 Australians were to be taken to Perth hotels for 14 days of quarantine.<ref name=\"ABC-30-3-2020\"/>\n\n== Hazard controls ==\n{{Further|Workplace hazard controls for COVID-19}}\nAccording to the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], proper [[Hierarchy of hazard controls|hazard controls]] for cruise ships and other commercial vessels include postponing travel when sick, and self-isolating and informing the onboard medical center immediately if one develops a fever or other symptoms while on board.  Ideally, medical follow-up should occur in the isolated person's cabin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/maritime/recommendations-for-ships.html|title=Interim Guidance for Ships on Managing Suspected Coronavirus Disease 2019|last=|first=|date=2020-02-18|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301220052/https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/maritime/recommendations-for-ships.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}} {{PD-inline}}</ref>\n\nA new regulation issued by the CDC on 6 April 2020 stated that passengers on cruise ships would not be able to travel home on commercial flights. They were to travel only by \"charter flights and private transportation\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-pandemic-04-06-20/index.html |title=South Florida could be the most impacted by new restrictions on cruise travelers |date=6 April 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 April 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406022613/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-pandemic-04-06-20/index.html |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Financial fallout==\n{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nCruise line stock fell sharply on 27 March 2020 when the US$2 trillion relief package passed by the U.S. Congress and signed by [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] excluded companies that are not \"organized\" under United States law. [[Carnival Corporation & plc]] is registered in Panama, England and Wales; [[Royal Caribbean International]] is chartered in Liberia, and [[Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings]] is domiciled in Bermuda. Senator [[Sheldon Whitehouse]], (D-RI), tweeted: \"The giant cruise companies incorporate overseas to dodge US taxes, flag vessels overseas to avoid US taxes and laws, and pollute without offset. Why should we bail them out?\" Senator [[Josh Hawley]] (R-MO) tweeted that cruise lines should register and pay taxes in the United States if they expect a financial bailout. U.S-based employees and American-owned passenger ships will still be eligible for financial assistance.<ref>{{cite web |website=Associated Press |title=Cruise stocks sink after missing out on economic-relief bill |first1=David |last1=Koening |first2=Kevin |last2=Freking |last-author-amp=y |date=27 March 2020 |url=https://apnews.com/819d004059e6b165d9509f2d346a7d41 |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329192618/https://apnews.com/819d004059e6b165d9509f2d346a7d41 |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Carnival Cruise Line]] stock fell 75% between 1 January and 31 March 2020 and dividend payments to shareholders were suspended. On 13 March the company drew down its $3 billion revolving credit line and [[Moody's Investors Service|Moody's]] and [[S&P Global]] downgraded Carnival's debt rating. On 31 March Carnival announced plans to issue $1.25 billion in stock and $4.75 billion in notes due in 2023. The [[Cruise Lines International Association]], a cruise line [[trade association]], claims that the cruise industry supports 400,000 jobs in the United States.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/31/cruise-ship-company-carnival-to-raise-6-billion-in-stock-and-debt-shares-jump.html?recirc=taboolainternal Beleaguered cruise ship company Carnival to raise $6 billion in stock and debt, shares jump] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401170947/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/31/cruise-ship-company-carnival-to-raise-6-billion-in-stock-and-debt-shares-jump.html?recirc=taboolainternal |date=1 April 2020 }} by William Feuer, [[CNBC]], 31 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n== Average age of cruise passengers ==\n\nA report from [[Cruise Lines International Association]] from 2019 states the [[Arithmetic mean|average]] age of cruise passengers is 46.9 years, while the largest age bracket is 60\u201369 years (19%) followed by 50\u201359 years (18%).<ref>Darcy Alexander: ''[https://www.cruise1st.co.uk/blog/cruise-holidays/how-old-is-the-average-cruise-passenger/ How Old is the Average Cruise Passenger?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403212942/https://www.cruise1st.co.uk/blog/cruise-holidays/how-old-is-the-average-cruise-passenger/ |date=3 April 2020 }}'', Cruise 1st, 23 August 2019</ref> Research from 2001 studying the epidemiology of passenger mortalities on cruise ships, indicated a median age of 65 years of cruise participants. It also stated, that between April 1995 to April 2001 \"there was an average of one death every six months per ship\", with an average of 800 passengers on each ship.<ref>Eilif Dahl: ''[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11817837 Passenger mortalities aboard cruise ships]'', University of Oslo, Department of Surgery, The [[Oslo University Hospital, Rikshospitalet|National Hospital (Rikshospitalet)]], Norway, published in [[International Maritime Health Association|International Maritime Health]], 2001</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' (CVN-71)]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania]]\n{{end div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents involving cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Lists of cruise ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on cruise ships}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\nThe passengers and crew of many [[cruise ship|cruise ships]] were found to be infected with the novel [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], many with substantial spread of the disease amongst passengers and crew.  The British-registered {{ship||Diamond Princess|ship|2}} was quarantined at [[Port of Yokohama|Yokohama]] for nearly a month from 4 February 2020. Substantial spread of the virus onboard drew headlines worldwide throughout February. Of the 3,700 passengers and crew, 700 people were infected and twelve died. On 20 February, the [[World Health Organisation]] stated that the one ship accounted for more than half of the reported infections around the world outside of China.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/20/coronavirus-live-updates-diamond-princess-cruise-ship-japan-deaths-latest-news-china-infections |title=Cruise ship accounts for more than half of virus cases outside China \u2013 as it happened |publisher=The Guardian |date=20 February 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304102207/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/20/coronavirus-live-updates-diamond-princess-cruise-ship-japan-deaths-latest-news-china-infections |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGovernments and ports initially responded by preventing many cruise ships from docking. The ''[[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cruise_ships#Zaandam|Zaandam]]'' was turned away from [[Chile]], then was delayed passage through the [[Panama Canal]] and had to negotiate to disembark at [[Port Everglades|Port Everglades, USA]]. [[Canada]] blocked all ships carrying more than 500 people from docking in Canada from 13 March to 1 July 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-1.5495881|title=What you need to know about COVID-19 in B.C. on March 13, 2020|website=[[CBC News]]|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314030733/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-1.5495881|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] declared that  foreign-flagged vessels carrying more than 50 people should not dock in [[Florida]], [[Georgia]], [[South Carolina]], and [[Puerto Rico]] from 29 March, and instead should prepare to treat any sick passengers and crew on board and try to medically evacuate the very sick to their home countries.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Coast Guard: Cruise ships must stay at sea with sick onboard |first=Freida |last=Frisaro |first2=Adriana |last2=Gomez Licon |last-author-amp=y |date=1 April 2020 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coast-guard-cruise-ships-must-122752320.html |work=Yahoo News |access-date=1 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401125152/https://news.yahoo.com/coast-guard-cruise-ships-must-122752320.html |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Australia banned cruise ships arriving from foreign ports from 15 March 2020, and on 27 March directed all foreign-flagged ships to leave the country.<ref name=Grad0704>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: legal action could undo government order that cruise ships leave Australian waters |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/coronavirus-legal-action-could-undo-government-order-that-cruise-ships-leave-australian-waters |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> However the 2,700 passengers offloaded at [[Sydney]] on 19 March by the Australian-based ''[[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cruise_ships#Ruby_Princess|Ruby Princess]]'' had caused over 10% of all COVID-19 cases across that country by 10 April, and some ship operators challenged the Australian government's order in court.<ref name=Grad0704/> \n\nThe crisis management team of the German federal government said on 4 March 2020, following several actual and suspected outbreaks on cruise ships, \"The Federal Foreign Office has included in its travel advice that there is an increased risk of quarantine on cruise ships.\"<ref name=berliner/> On 11 March 2020, [[Viking Cruises]] suspended operations for its 79-vessel fleet until the end of April, cancelling all ocean and river cruises, after it was revealed that a passenger on a cruise in Cambodia had been exposed to the virus while in transit via plane, placing at least 28 other passengers in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vikingrivercruises.com.au/my-trip/current-sailings/index.html|title=My Trip \u2013 Updates on Current Sailings|website=vikingrivercruises.com.au|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312181910/https://www.vikingrivercruises.com.au/my-trip/current-sailings/index.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/viking-cruises-coronavirus-suspends-operations-industry-struggles-2020-3 |title=Viking Cruises suspended operations worldwide due to the coronavirus, as infections ravage the cruise industry |first=Bill |last=Bostock |website=Business Insider |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174617/https://www.businessinsider.com/viking-cruises-coronavirus-suspends-operations-industry-struggles-2020-3 |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Similarly, on 12 March, [[Princess Cruises]], owner of virus-stricken ships ''Diamond Princess'' and {{ship||Grand Princess}}, suspended operations for all future cruises on its 18-ship fleet for 60 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/global-ship-operations-pause.html|title=Princess Cruises: Voluntary 60 Day Pause of Global Ship Operations \u2013 Notices & Advisories|publisher=Princess Cruises|date=12 March 2020|website=princess.com|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312190604/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/global-ship-operations-pause.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/12/coronavirus-viking-cruises-suspends-cruise-operations-until-may-1/5030006002/ |title=Princess Cruises suspends operations for 60 days; Viking Cruises cancels all cruises due to coronavirus |first1=Hannah |last1=Yasharoff |first2=Morgan |last2=Hines |last3=Tate |first3=Curtis |last-author-amp=y |website=[[USA Today]] |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312203258/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/12/coronavirus-viking-cruises-suspends-cruise-operations-until-may-1/5030006002/ |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A US Coast Guard report on 4 April 2020 stated that \"there are 114 cruise ships, carrying 93,000 crew members, either in or near U.S. ports and waters. ... Another 41 cruise ships, with 41,000 crew members, are underway and close to the U.S\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/another-cruise-ship-with-virus-victims-docking-in-florida-1.4882574 |title=Another cruise ship with virus victims docking in Florida |publisher=CTV News, The Associated Press |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=4 April 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405021519/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/another-cruise-ship-with-virus-victims-docking-in-florida-1.4882574 |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An estimated 21 cruise ships have had COVID-19 cases on board. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruisehive.com/21-cruise-ships-with-a-u-s-port-affected-by-covid-19/38939|title=21 Cruise Ships With a U.S. Port Affected By COVID-19|date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n{{toc limit}} \n\n== Incidents ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Cruise ship incidents with confirmed positive cases on board\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Ship\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Pass.\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Crew\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | People                                       \n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Date{{efn|Docking date (in 2020 unless otherwise noted)}}\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Location{{efn|Current location in italics if not currently docked|name=\"italics\"}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Owner/operator\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Tests\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Cases\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Dead\n|-\n! Dock{{efn|name=\"italics\"}}\n! Country\n|-\n| ''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|Diamond Princess]]''\n| 2,666<ref name=\"ship-diamond-princess\">{{cite web |url=https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/diamond-princess-update.html |title=Diamond Princess Updates:Confirmed Cases of Coronavirus on Diamond Princess (4th of February, 2020) |work=Princess.com |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302202526/https://www.princess.com/news/notices_and_advisories/notices/diamond-prin