n]]\n[[Category:Pakistani anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Generals of the Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]]\n[[Category:Genocide perpetrators]]\n[[Category:People of the Cold War]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Afghan cricketer|Yahya Khan (cricketer)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Yahya Khan\n| honorific-prefix    = [[General officer|General]]\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| native_name         = {{nq|\u06cc\u062d\u06cc\u06cc\u0670 \u062e\u0627\u0646 }}\n| native_name_lang    = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n| image               = Yahya_Khan_(cropped_version).jpg\n| imagesize           = 200px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| order               = 3rd\n| office              = President of Pakistan\n| term_start          = 25 March 1969\n| term_end            = 20 December 1971\n| alongside           = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n| primeminister       = [[Nurul Amin]] (1971)\n| succeeding          = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n| parliamentarygroup  = \n| constituency        = \n| majority            = \n| predecessor         = [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]]\n| successor           = [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]]\n| prior_term          = <!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n| order2              = \n| office2             = [[Commander-in-Chief of the Pakistan Army]]\n| term_start2         = 18 June 1966\n| term_end2           = 20 December 1971\n| deputy2             = [[General]] [[Abdul Hamid Khan (general)|Abdul Hamid Khan]]\n| predecessor2        = General [[Muhammad Musa|Musa Khan]]\n| successor2          = [[Lieutenant-General|Lt-Gen.]] [[Gul Hassan Khan|Gul Hassan]]\n<!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->| birth_name          = Agha Muhammad Yahya Khan\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1917|02|04|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Chakwal]], [[British Punjab|Punjab]], [[British India]] <br />(now in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1980|08|10|1917|2|4|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n| resting_place       = [[Peshawar, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality         = [[Indian people|Indian]] {{small|(1917\u20131947)}}<br />[[Pakistan]] {{small|(1947\u20131980)}}\n| party               = None\n| otherparty          = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n| spouse              = \n| partner             = [[General Rani]] (1967-1971)<br />[[Noor Jehan]]<!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| parents             = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = Col. Brown Cambridge School, Dehra Dun, Punjab University<br />Indian Military Academy<br />United States Army Command and General Staff College{{!}}Command and General Staff College\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| cabinet             = \n| committees          = \n| portfolio           = \n| blank1              = \n| data1               = \n| signature           = \n| signature_alt       = \n| website             = <!--Military service-->\n| nickname            = \n| allegiance          = \n| branch              = {{army|British India}} (1938-1947)<br />{{army|PAK}} (1947-1971)\n| serviceyears        = 1938\u20131971\n| rank                = [[File:OF-9 Pakistan Army.svg|25px]] [[File:US-O10 insignia.svg|45px]] [[General]]\n| unit                = [[129th Duke of Connaught's Own Baluchis|4th battalion]], [[10th Baluch Regiment]] {{small|([[Service number|S/No.]] PA\u201398)}}\n| commands            = [[Commander-in-Chief of the Pakistan Army|Deputy C-in-C of the army]]<br />7th Infantry Division, [[Peshawar]]<br />15th Infantry Division, [[Sialkot]]<br />14th Infantry Division, [[Dacca]]<br />105th Independent Brigade\n| battles             = [[World War II]]\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II|Mediterranean theatre]]\n[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]]\n* [[Battle of Chawinda]]\n[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]\n* [[Bangladesh Liberation War]]\n| awards              = [[File:Order of Pakistan.png|25px]]  [[Nishan-e-Pakistan|Nishane-e-Pakistan]] {{small|(withdrawn)}}<br />[[File:Yellow Crescent, Symbol of Islam.png|15px]] [[Civil decorations of Pakistan|Hilal-e-Pakistan]] {{small|(withdrawn)}}<br />[[File:Order of Pahlavi (Iran).gif|25px]] [[Order of Pahlavi|Neshan-e-Pahlavi]]\n| military_blank1     = \n| military_data1      = \n| pronunciation       = <!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n| height              = <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| mother              = <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father              = <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives           = \n| education           = Col.Brown Cambridge School, Dehra Dun,  Punjab  University\n| known_for           = \n| blank2              = \n| data2               = \n| blank3              = \n| data3               = \n| blank4              = \n| data4               = \n| blank5              = \n| data5               = \n| mawards             = [[File:Hilal-Jurat Ribbon.gif|20px]] [[Hilal-e-Jurat]] {{small|(withdrawn)}}\n| military_blank2     = \n| military_data2      = \n| military_blank3     = \n| military_data3      = \n| military_blank4     = \n| military_data4      = \n| military_blank5     = \n| military_data5      = <!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n| module4             = \n| module5             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Agha Muhammad Yahya Khan''' {{small|[[Order of Pahlavi|NePl]]}} ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0622\u063a\u0627 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u06cc\u062d\u06cc\u06cc\u0670 \u062e\u0627\u0646}}}}; 4 February 1917 \u2013 10 August 1980), widely known as '''Yahya Khan''', was a [[Pakistani]] general who served as the [[List of Presidents of Pakistan|third]] [[President of Pakistan]], serving in this post from 25 March 1969 until turning over his presidency in December 1971.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan Foundation\">{{cite web |url=http://www.storyofpakistan.com/person.asp?perid=P018 |title=Yahya Khan |work=Story of Pakistan |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nHaving participated in the [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II|Mediterranean theatre]] of [[World War II]] on behalf of Great Britain's [[British Indian Army]], he opted for [[Pakistani citizenship]] and joined [[Pakistani military|its military]] after the United Kingdom [[Partition of India|partitioned India]] in 1947, and helped in executing the [[Operation Grand Slam|covert infiltration]] in [[Indian held Kashmir|Indian Kashmir]] that sparked the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1965|war with India in 1965]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Shaikh Aziz |date=25 December 2011 |title=A chapter from history: Yahya Khan's quick action |url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/12/25/a-chapter-from-history-yahya-khans-quick-action.html |work=Dawn |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> After being controversially appointed to assume the [[Commander-in-Chief of the Pakistan Army|army command]] in 1966, he took over the presidency from unpopular former dictator and elected President [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]], who was not able to deal with the [[1969 Mass uprising in East Pakistan|1969 uprising]] in [[East Pakistan]], forced to resign by protests and offered him the office. Yahya Khan subsequently enforced [[Martial law in Pakistan|martial law]] by suspending the [[Constitution of Pakistan of 1962|constitution]]. Holding the nation's first [[1970 Pakistani general election|nationwide elections]] in 1970, 23 years after independence, he delayed the power transition to victorious [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] from East Pakistan, which further inflamed the civil violent unrest in the East, and authorized the East Pakistani authorities to [[Operation Searchlight|violently]] suppress the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|rebellion]] in which somewhere from several hundred thousand to about 3,000,000 were killed in what is today widely considered the [[1971 Bangladesh genocide]].\n\nPakistan suffered a decisive defeat in the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Bangladesh Liberation War of 1971]], resulting in the dissolution of the [[Pakistan Eastern Command|Eastern Command]] of the Pakistan Army and the [[Independence of Bangladesh|secession]] of East Pakistan as [[Bangladesh]] \u2013 thus Yahya Khan's rule is widely regarded as a leading cause of the break-up of the unity of Pakistan.<ref name=\"I.B.Tauris, Shah\">{{cite book |last1=Shah |first1=Mehtab Ali |year=1997 |title=The Foreign Policy of Pakistan: Ethnic Impacts on Diplomacy 1971\u20131994 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7czT4fipTyoC&pg=PA15 |publisher=I.B.Tauris |page=15 |isbn=978-1-86064-169-5 |access-date=7 November 2016 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvard University Press, Raghavan\">{{cite book|last1=Raghavan|first1=Srinath|year=2013|title=1971: The Global History of Creation of the Bangladesh|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674731271|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u6gQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT110&dq=pakistan+geopolitical+influence+1971#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20geopolitical%20influence%201971&f=false|accessdate=7 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Following these events, he turned over the leadership of the country to [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]], the leading politician from [[West Pakistan]], and resigned from the [[Commander in Chief (Pakistan)|command of the military]] in disgrace, both on 20 December 1971.<ref name=\"Zulfikar Ali Bhutto becomes President [1971]\">{{cite web |title=Zulfikar Ali Bhutto becomes President [1971] |url=http://www.storyofpakistan.com/articletext.asp?artid=A071 |date=June 2003 |website=Story of Pakistan}}</ref> He was then stripped of his [[Military awards of pakistan|service honours]] and put under [[House arrest|house surveillance]] for most of the 1970s.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan Foundation\" />\n\nAfter being released from these restrictions in 1977, he died in [[Rawalpindi]] in 1980.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ahmed |first=Munir |authorlink= |editor= |title=\u062c\u0646\u0631\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u06cc\u062d\u0670\u06cc\u06cc \u062e\u0627\u0646: \u0634\u062e\u0635\u06cc\u062a \u0648 \u0633\u06cc\u0627\u0633\u06cc \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 |year=2001 |edition= |series= |publisher= \u0622\u0635\u0641 \u062c\u0627\u0648\u06cc\u062f \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0626\u06d2 \u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u0634\u0627\u062a \u067e\u0628\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0632|location= Lahore, Pakistan|language= Urdu|isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |page= 240|chapter=\u062e\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u06cc \u06a9\u06c1\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u06d2 \u0628\u06cc\u0679\u06d2 \u0639\u0644\u06cc \u06cc\u062d\u0670\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc \u0632\u0628\u0627\u0646\u06cc |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref> He is viewed largely negatively by Pakistani historians and is considered among the least successful of the country's leaders.<ref name=\"storyofpakistan.com\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nAgha Muhammad Yahya Khan was born in [[Chakwal]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Indian Empire]]<ref name=\"storyofpakistan.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://storyofpakistan.com/yahya-khan/ |title=General Yahya Khan &#124; Former Army Chief of Pakistan enforcing Martial Law in 1969 |website=Story of Pakistan |date=26 October 2013}}</ref> on 4 February 1917, according to the references written by Russian sources.<ref name=\"ABC-CLIOm 2011\">{{cite book|editor-last=Mikaberidze|editor-first=Alexander |title=Conflict and Conquest in the Islamic World a Historical Encyclopedia.|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIOm 2011|location=Santa Barbara|isbn=978-1598843378|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jBBYD2J2oE4C&pg=PA955&dq=Yahya+Khan#v=onepage&q=Yahya%20Khan&f=true}}</ref><ref>Democracy, security, and development in India. By Raju G. C. Thomas.</ref> He and his family were of [[Karlani]] [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] origin.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=n5uU2UteUpEC&dq=yahya+khan+punjabi|title=South Asia: A Short History|last1=Tinker|first1=Hugh|date=1990|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0824812874|location=|page=248|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sbEvmBKPgBoC&dq=yahya+khan+punjabi|title=India and Pakistan: Continued Conflict or Cooperation?|last1=Wolper|first1=Stanley|date=2010|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0520948006|location=|page=35|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rk-sBwAAQBAJ&dq=yahya+khan+punjabi|title=Historical Dictionary of Pakistan|last1=Burki|first1=Shahid Javed|date=2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1442241480|edition=4|location=|page=596|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Jaffrelot|first1=Christophe|title=The Pakistan Paradox: Instability and Resilience|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0190235185|pages=226\u2013227|url=https://books.google.com/?id=i5GMCwAAQBAJ&dq=yahya+khan+pashtun}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=The Longest August: The Unflinching Rivalry Between India and Pakistan|date=2015|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=978-1568585031|page=183|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PpPCBAAAQBAJ&dq=yahya+khan+pashtun|quote=A burly, double chinned, bushy-browed slothful Yahya Khan was, like Ayub Khan, an ethnic Pashtun.}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=Few Pakistanis knew anything about Yahya Khan when he was vaulted into the presidency two years ago. The stocky, bushy\u2013browed Pathan had been the army chief of staff since 1966...|sign=Editorial, [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']], 2 August 1971<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite magazine |title=Good Soldier Yahya Khan |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878409,00.html |url-access=subscription |magazine=Time |date=2 August 1971 |page=32 |access-date=17 April 2014}}</ref> |source=}}\n\nAccording to Indian writer Dewan Berindranath's book ''Private Life of Yahya Khan'' (published in 1974), Yahya's father worked in the British Indian Police, in Punjab province. He joined as a head constable and retired as a deputy superintendent. Yahya's father was posted in [[Chakwal Punjab]] when Yahya Khan was born.  Yahya studied in the prestigious [[Colonel Brown Cambridge School|Col. Brown Cambridge School Dehradun]] and later enrolled at the [[Punjab University, Lahore|University of Punjab]] from where he passed B.A.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berindranath|first1=Dewan|title=Private Life of Yahya Khan|date=2006|publisher=Sterling Publishers|location=New Delhi|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/?id=w5scAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Career before Pakistan's independence===\nYahya Khan was commissioned into the [[British Indian Army]] from [[Indian Military Academy|Indian Military Academy, Dehradun]] in 1938.<ref name=\"storyofpakistan.com\"/> An infantry officer from the 4th/10th Baluch Regiment ([[129th Duke of Connaught's Own Baluchis|4th Battalion]] of [[10th Baluch Regiment]], later amalgamated with the modern and current form of [[Baloch Regiment]], 'Baloch' was spelled as 'Baluch' in Yahya's time), Yahya saw action during World War II in North Africa where he was captured by the [[Axis Forces]] in June 1942 and interned in a prisoner of war camp in [[Italy]] from where he escaped in the third attempt.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan Foundation\"/><ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\">{{cite book|last=Bhattacharya, IA|first=Brigadier (retd.) Samir|title=Nothing But! Book Three: What Price Freedom.|year=2013|publisher=Partridge Publishing|location=New Delhi India|isbn=978-1482816259|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HESVAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA616&dq=General+Yahya+Khan+Punjabi#v=onepage&q=General%20Yahya%20Khan%20Punjabi&f=false}}{{Self-published source|date=August 2017}}</ref>{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}}\n\nYahya Khan served in [[World War II]] as a lieutenant and later captain in the [[4th Infantry Division (India)]]. He served in Iraq, Italy, and North Africa. He was POW in Italy before returning to India.\n\n===After birth of Pakistan===\nAfter the [[partition of India]], he decided to join the [[Pakistan Army]] in 1947, he had already been reached to the rank of Major (acting Lieutenant-colonel). In this year he was instrumental in not letting the Indian officers shift books from the famous library of the ''British Indian Army Staff College'' (now [[Command and Staff College]]) at [[Quetta]], where Yahya was posted as the only Muslim instructor at the time of partition of India. There were other Muslim instructors besides him.<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}} At the age of 34, he was promoted to [[Brigadier]] and is still considered the youngest one-star officer in the history of [[Pakistan Armed Forces]]. He was appointed as commander of the 105 Independent Brigade that was deployed in [[Line of Control|LoC]] ceasefire region in [[Jammu and Kashmir (princely state)|Jammu and Kashmir]] in 1951\u20131952.<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}} He was described as a \"hard drinking soldier\" who liked young women's company and wine, though he was a meritorious and professional soldier.\n\nLater Yahya, as Deputy Chief of General Staff, was selected to head the army's planning board set up by [[Ayub Khan (general)|Ayub Khan]] to modernize the Pakistan Army in 1954\u201357. Yahya also performed the duties of Chief of General Staff from 1958 to 1962 from where he went on to command two infantry divisions from 1962 to 1965 including one in East Pakistan.<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}} Yahya also renamed the [[Command and Staff College]] from 'Army Staff College' in Quetta, [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]].<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan Foundation\"/> He played a pivotal role in sustaining the support for President Ayub Khan's campaign in the [[1965 Pakistani presidential election|1965 presidential elections]] against [[Fatima Jinnah]].<ref name=\"ABC-CLIOm 2011\" /> He was made [[General officer commanding|GOC]] of [[7th Infantry Division (Pakistan)|7th Infantry Division]] of Pakistan Army, which he commanded during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965|1965 war with India]]. At this assignment, he was not instrumental in planning and executing the military infiltration operation, the [[Operation Grand Slam|''Grand Slam'']], which failed miserably due to General Yahya's delay owing to change of command decision, the [[Indian Army]] crossed the [[india\u2013Pakistan border|intentional border]] and made a beeline for [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}}\n\nDespite his failures, Yahya was promoted to [[lieutenant-general]] after his promotion papers were personally approved by President Ayub Khan in 1966, at a stint as an appointed Deputy Army Commander in Chief.<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}} He was appointed as [[Commander-in-Chief (Pakistan Army)|commander-in-chief]] of Pakistan Army in March 1966 and took command in June.<ref name=\"Partridge Publishing\" />{{Self-published-inline|certain=y|date=August 2017}}  At promotion, Yahya Khan superseded two of his seniors: Lieutenant-General Altaf Qadir and Lieutenant-General Bakhtiar Rana.<ref name=\"dawn.com\">Brig A.R. Siddiqui. [http://www.dawn.com/2004/04/25/fea.htm#2 \"Army's top slot: the seniority factor\"] ''Dawn'', 25 April 2004</ref>\n\nAfter becoming the c-in-c Yahya energetically started reorganizing the Pakistan Army in 1966. The post-1965 situation saw major organisational as well as technical changes in the Pakistan Army. Until 1965 it was thought that divisions could function effectively while getting orders directly from the army's [[General Headquarters (Pakistan Army)|GHQ]]. This idea failed miserably in the 1965 war and the need to have intermediate corps headquarters in between the GHQ and the fighting combat divisions was recognised as a foremost operational necessity after the 1965 war. In 1965 war the Pakistan Army had only one corps headquarters (the [[I Corps (Pakistan)|I Corps]]).<ref name=\"dawn.com\"/>\n\nSoon after the war had started the United States had imposed an embargo on military aid to both India and Pakistan. This embargo did not affect the Indian Army but produced major changes in the Pakistan Army's technical composition. US Secretary of State [[Dean Rusk]] well summed it up when he said, \"Well if you are going to fight, go ahead and fight, but we\u2019re not going to pay for it\".<ref>Dennis Kux, India and the United States: Estranged Democracies (Washington, DC: National Defense University Press, 1992), 239.</ref>\n\nPakistan now turned to China for military aid and the Chinese tank [[T-59 (tank)|T-59]] started replacing the US [[M47 Patton|M-47/48]] tanks as the Pakistan Army's MBT (Main Battle Tank) from 1966. 80 tanks, the first batch of T-59s, a low-grade version of the Russian [[T-54/55]] series were delivered to Pakistan in 1965\u201366. The first batch was displayed in the Joint Services Day Parade on 23 March 1966. The 1965 War had proved that Pakistan Army's tank-infantry ratio was lopsided and more infantry was required. Three more infantry divisions (9, 16 and 17 Divisions) largely equipped with Chinese equipment and popularly referred to by the rank and file as \"The China Divisions\" were raised by the beginning of 1968. Two more corps headquarters: the [[II Corps (Pakistan)|2nd Corps]] Headquarters (Jhelum-Ravi Corridor) and the [[IV Corps (Pakistan)|4th Corps]] Headquarters (Ravi-Sutlej Corridor) were raised, also in [[East Pakistan]] a corps-sized formation titles as the [[Eastern Command (Pakistan)|Eastern Command]] was created.\n\n==President of Pakistan==\n[[File:President Nixon meets with President of Pakistan Yahya Khan - NARA - 194693.tif|thumb|President of Pakistan Yahya Khan with United States President [[Richard Nixon]] in October 1970.]]{{POV section|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]] was President of Pakistan for most of the 1960s, but by the end of the decade, popular resentment had boiled over against him. Pakistan had fallen into a state of disarray, and long ongoing civil unrest in East Pakistan evolved into a [[1969 Mass uprising in East Pakistan|mass uprising]] in January of the year. After having held unsuccessful talks with the opposition, Ayub Khan handed over power to Yahya Khan in March, who immediately imposed [[martial law]]. When Yahya assumed the office on 25 March 1969, he inherited a two-decade constitutional problem of inter-provincial ethnic rivalry between the [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]]-[[Pashtuns|Pashtun]]-[[Muhajir people|Mohajir]] dominated West Pakistan province and the ethnically [[Bengali people|Bengali]] Muslim East Pakistan province. In addition, Yahya also inherited an 11 year old problem of transforming an essentially one man ruled country to a democratic country, which was the ideological basis of the anti-Ayub movement of 1968\u201369. As an Army Chief Yahya had all the capabilities, qualifications and potential. But Yahya inherited an extremely complex problem and was forced to perform the multiple roles of ''caretaker'' head of the country, ''drafter'' of a provisional constitution, resolving the ''One Unit question'', satisfying the frustrations and the sense of exploitation and discrimination successively created in the ''East Wing'' by a series of government policies since 1948.\n\nThe American political scientist [[Lawrence Ziring]] observed that,\n{{quote|text=Yahya Khan has been widely portrayed as a ruthless uncompromising insensitive and grossly inept leader ... While Yahya cannot escape responsibility for these tragic events, it is also on record that he did not act alone ... All the major actors of the period were creatures of a historic legacy and a psycho-political milieu which did not lend itself to accommodation and compromise, to bargaining and a reasonable settlement. Nurtured on conspiracy theories, they were all conditioned to act in a manner that neglected agreeable solutions and promoted violent judgments.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ziring |first=Lawrence |year=1980 |title=Pakistan: The Enigma of Political Development |publisher=Dawson |page=104 |isbn=978-0-7129-0954-9}}</ref>\n}}\n\nYahya Khan attempted to solve Pakistan's constitutional and inter-provincial/regional rivalry problems once he took over power from [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]] in March 1969. The tragedy of the whole affair was the fact that all actions that Yahya took, although correct in principle, were too late in timing, and served only to further intensify the political polarisation between the East and West wings.\n* He dissolved the one unit restoring the pre-1955 provinces of West Pakistan\n* He promised free direct, one man one vote, fair elections on adult franchise, a basic human right which had been denied to the Pakistani people since the pre-independence 1946 elections by political inefficiency, double play and intrigue, by civilian governments from 1947 to 1958 and by Ayub's one-man rule from 1958 to 1969.\n\nHowever, dissolution of one unit did not lead to the positive results that it might have led to in case \"One Unit\" was dissolved earlier. Yahya also made an attempt to accommodate the East Pakistanis by abolishing the principle of parity, thereby hoping that greater share in the assembly would redress their wounded ethnic regional pride and ensure the integrity of Pakistan. Instead of satisfying the Bengalis it intensified their separatism since they felt that the west wing had politically suppressed them since 1958. Thus came the rise of anti-West Wing sentiment in the East Wing.\n\nDuring the course of 1968, the [[political pressure]] exerted by Zulfikar Ali Bhutto had weakened the President Ayub Khan, who had earlier sacked Bhutto after disagreeing with President Ayub's decision to implement on [[Tashkent Agreement]], facilitated by the [[Soviet Union]] to end the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965|hostilities]] with India.<ref name=\"Mittal Publications\">{{cite book|last=Akbar|first=M.K.|title=Pakistan from Jinnah to Sharif|year=1997|publisher=Mittal Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-8170996743|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BcIniHQAHfUC&pg=PA50&dq=Yahya+Khan#v=onepage&q&f=true}}</ref> To ease the situation, President Ayub had tried reaching out to terms with the major parties, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) and the [[Awami League]] (AL), but remained unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Mittal Publications\"/> In poor health, President Ayub abrogated his own [[Constitution of Pakistan of 1962|constitution]] and suddenly resigned from the presidency.<ref name=\"Diane Publication Co.\">{{cite book|last=Peter R. Blood|title=Pakistan: A Country Study|year=1996|publisher=Diane Publication Co.|location=United States|isbn=978-0788136313|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DRMTO7mn7hIC&pg=PA206&dq=Yahya+Khan#v=onepage&q=Yahya%20Khan&f=true}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 1969, President Ayub directed a letter to General Yahya Khan, inviting him to deal with the situation, as it was \"beyond the capacity of (civil) government to deal with the... Complex situation.\"<ref name=\"KLUWER LAW INTERNATIONAL\">{{cite book|last=Omar|first=Imtiaz|title=Emergency powers and the courts in India and Pakistan|year=2002|publisher=KLUWER LAW INTERNATIONAL|location=England|isbn=978-9041117755|url=https://books.google.com/?id=o6-wZP7Tz8YC&pg=PA59&dq=Yahya+Khan#v=onepage&q=Yahya%20Khan&f=true}}</ref> On 26 March 1969, General Yahya appeared in [[Pakistan Television Corporation|national television]] and announced to enforce [[Military coups in Pakistan|martial law]] in all over the country. The 1962 Constitution was abrogated, the [[Parliament of Pakistan|parliament]] dissolved, and President Ayub's civilian officials dismissed.<ref name=\"KLUWER LAW INTERNATIONAL\"/> In his first nationwide address, Yahya maintained: \"I will not tolerate disorder. Let everyone remain at his post.\"<ref name=\"Lancer Publ.\">{{cite book|last=KrishnaRao|first=K.V.|title=Prepare or perish : a study of national security|year=1991|publisher=Lancer Publ.|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-8172120016}}</ref>\n\nOn immediate effect, he installed a [[military dictatorship|military government]] and featured active duty military officials:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Yahya Khan administration\n|-\n! Ministers !!Portrait !![[Cabinet of Pakistan|Ministries and departments]] !! [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Inter-services]]\n|-\n|General Yahya Khan<ref name=\"Dr. GN. Kazi\">{{cite web|last=Dr. GN. Kazi|title=Pakistan's Smallest Cabinet|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/pimu/2510812824/?rb=1smal|publisher=Dr. GN. Kazi |date=21 May 2008 |access-date=17 April 2014}}</ref>  ||  ||[[President of Pakistan|President]] and [[Chief Martial Law Administrator]]<br />[[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (Pakistan)|Information and Broadcasting]]<br />[[Law Minister of Pakistan|Law]] and [[Ministry of Justice (Pakistan)|Justice]]<br />[[Foreign Minister of Pakistan|Foreign]] and [[Defence Minister of Pakistan|Defence]] || {{Army|PAK}}\n|-\n|General [[Abdul Hamid Khan (general)|Abdul Hamid Khan]]<ref name=\"Dr. GN. Kazi\"/> || ||  Deputy [[Chief Martial Law Administrator|CMLA]]<br />[[Interior Minister of Pakistan|Interior]] and [[Ministry of States and Frontier Regions|Kashmir Affairs]] || {{Army|PAK}}\n|-\n|Vice-Admiral [[Syed Mohammad Ahsan]]<ref name=\"Dr. GN. Kazi\"/> ||<!-- [[File:ARKhan.jpg|50px]] --> || Deputy [[Chief Martial Law Administrator|CMLA]]<br />[[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance]] and [[Planning Commission (Pakistan)|Planning Commission]]<br />[[Ministry of Statistics (Pakistan)|Statistics]], [[Ministry of Commerce (Pakistan)|Commerce]], and [[Industry Minister of Pakistan|Industry]] || [[File:Naval Jack of Pakistan.svg|20px]] [[Pakistan Navy]]\n|-\n|Air-Marshal [[Nur Khan]]<ref name=\"Dr. GN. Kazi\"/> ||[[File:Noor khan.jpg|50px]] ||  Deputy [[Chief Martial Law Administrator|CMLA]]<br />[[Ministry of Communications (Pakistan)|Communications]] and [[Ministry of Health (Pakistan)|Health]]<br />[[Ministry of Labour (Pakistan)|Labour]] and [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Science and Technology]]|| {{air force|PAK}}\n|}\n\n===National Security Council and LFO===\nPresident Yahya was well aware of this explosive situation and decided to bring changes all over the country. His earlier initiatives directed towards establishing the [[National Security Council (Pakistan)|National Security Council]] (NSC) with Major-General Ghulam Omar being its first advisor.<ref name=\"PILDT\">{{cite web|last=PILDT|title=The Evolution of National Security Council in Pakistan|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Y3lfJakmBHEJ:www.pildat.org/publications/publication/CMR/NaionalSecurityCouncil-debateonInstitutionsandprocessesfordecisionmakingonsecurityissues.pdf+national+security+council+of+pakistan+abolished&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShggkYLQkSMWbAFmB-4iD6lT1DEaPvelTxBGXYN_kuH8RwqjdggCetmcHTJskvJB2-wd5DLAlSxRAl4hOffUKZk3YYEjP3YPtCx4TZw4NQZttnWDGQc2svqysWcvR4fM-MSe_rD&sig=AHIEtbTpoD1sB-vSB9bx3iBp1XKjssR3aQ|work=Pakistan Institute of Legislative Development and Transparency.|publisher=PILDT|accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> It was formed to analyse and prepare assessments towards issues relating the political and national security.<ref name=\"PILDT\"/>\n\nSecondly in 1969, President Yahya promulgated the [[Legal Framework Order, 1970|Legal Framework Order No. 1970]] which disestablished the [[One Unit]] programme where [[West Pakistan]] was formed.<ref name=\"Cambridge University Press\"/> Instead, LFO No. 1970 hence removed the prefix ''West'', instead adding Pakistan.<ref name=\"Cambridge University Press\"/> The decree has no effect on [[East Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Cambridge University Press\">{{cite book|last=Newberg|first=Paula R.|title=Judging the state : courts and constitutional politics in Pakistan|year=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0521894401|edition=1st paperback}}</ref> Following this, President Yahya announced to held nationwide [[1970 Pakistani general election|general elections]] in 1970, and appointed Judge [[Abdus Sattar (president)|Abdus Sattar]] as [[Chief Election Commissioner of Pakistan|Chief Election Commissioner]] of [[Election Commission of Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Mittal Publications\" />  Changes were carried out by President Yahya to reverse the country back towards [[parliamentary democracy]].<ref name=\"Mittal Publications\" />\n\n==Last days of East Pakistan==\n\n===1970 general elections===\nBy 28 July 1969, President Yahya had set a framework for elections that were to be held in December 1970. Finally, the [[1970 Pakistani general election|general elections]] were held in all over the country. In East Pakistan, the [[Awami League]] led by [[Mujibur Rahman]] held almost all [[Mandate (politics)|mandate]], but no seat in any of [[Four Provinces (Pakistan)|four provinces]] of [[West Pakistan]]. The socialist [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) had won the [[exclusive mandate]] in the four provinces of Pakistan, but none in the East Pakistan. The [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)|Pakistan Muslim League]] (PML) led by [[Nurul Amin]] was the only party to have representation from all over the country, though it had failed to gain the mandate to run the government. The Awami League had 160 seats, all won from the East Pakistan; the socialist PPP had secured 81; the conservative PML had 10 seats in the [[National Assembly of Pakistan|National Assembly]]. The [[1970 Pakistani general elections|general elections]]'s results truly reflected the ugly political reality: the division of the Pakistani electorate along regional lines and political polarisation of the country between the two states, East Pakistan and Pakistan.\n\nIn political terms, therefore, Pakistan as a nation stood divided as a result. Series of bilateral talks between PPP and Mujibur Rahman produced no results and were unable to come to an agreement of [[Transfer of Power|transfer of power]]  from to East Pakistan's representatives on the basis of the [[Six point movement|Six-Point]] programme. In Pakistan, the people had felt that the Six-point agenda was a step towards secession.\n\n===Massacres in East Pakistan===\nWhile, the political deadlock remains between the Awami League, PPP, and the military government after the general elections in 1970. During this time, Yahya began coordinating several meetings with his military strategists over the issue in East Pakistan. On 25 March 1971, President Yahya initiated the [[Operation Searchlight|''Searchlight'']] in order to restore the writ of the government. The situation in East Pakistan worsened and the gulf between the two wings now was too wide to be bridged. Agitation was now transformed into a vicious insurgency as Bengali elements of [[Pakistan armed forces]] and [[Pakistan police|Police]] mutinied and formed [[Bangladesh Forces]] along with common people of all classes to launch both unconventional and hit and run operations. {{Citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\nThe ''Searchlight'' ordered by Yahya was a violent planned military pacification carried out by the Pakistan Armed Forces to curb the Bengali nationalist movement in erstwhile East Pakistan in March 1971.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bose |first=Sarmila |date=8 October 2005 |title=Anatomy of Violence: Analysis of Civil War in East Pakistan in 1971 |url=http://www.epw.org.in/showArticles.php?root=2005&leaf=10&filename=9223&filetype=html |journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301084941/http://www.epw.org.in/showArticles.php?root=2005&leaf=10&filename=9223&filetype=html |archive-date=1 March 2007}}</ref> Ordered by the government in Pakistan, this was seen as the sequel to Operation Blitz which had been launched in November 1970.\n\nThe original plan envisioned taking control of the major cities on 26 March 1971, and then eliminating all opposition, political or military,<ref>{{cite book |last=Salik |first=Siddiq |title=Witness to surrender |publisher=University Press |location=Dhaka |year=1997 |pages=63, 228\u20139 |isbn=978-984-05-1373-4}}</ref> within one month. The prolonged Bengali resistance was not anticipated by Pakistani planners.<ref>Pakistan Defence Journal, 1977, Vol 2, p2-3</ref> The main phase of Operation Searchlight ended with the fall of the last major town in Bengali hands in mid-May.\n\nThe total number of people killed in East Pakistan is not known with any degree of accuracy.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bass|2013|pp=350\u2013351}} reviews the various estimates here [https://books.google.com/books?id=9PnNZTp3BQYC&pg=PT443].</ref> Bangladeshi authorities claim that [[1971 Bangladesh genocide|3 million people were killed]],<ref name=MathewWhite>White, Matthew, ''[http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/warstat2.htm#Bangladesh Death Tolls for the Major Wars and Atrocities of the Twentieth Century]''</ref> while the [[Hamoodur Rahman Commission]], an official Pakistan Government investigation, put the figure as low as 26,000 civilian casualties.<ref name=deathcount-pakistani>[http://www.bangla2000.com/Bangladesh/Independence-War/Report-Hamoodur-Rahman/default.shtm Hamoodur Rahman Commission Report], [http://www.bangla2000.com/Bangladesh/Independence-War/Report-Hamoodur-Rahman/chapter2.shtm chapter 2], paragraph 33</ref> According to [[Sarmila Bose]], between 50,000 and 100,000 combatants and civilians were killed by both sides during the war.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jack |first=Ian |date=20 May 2011 |title=It's not the arithmetic of genocide that's important. It's that we pay attention |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/may/21/ian-jack-bangladesh-war-genocide |work=The Guardian}}</ref> A 2008 ''British Medical Journal'' study by Ziad Obermeyer, Christopher J. L. Murray, and Emmanuela Gakidou estimated that up to 269,000 civilians died as a result of the conflict; the authors note that this is far higher than a previous estimate of 58,000 from Uppsala University and the Peace Research Institute, Oslo.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Obermeyer |first1=Ziad |last2=Murray |first2=Christopher J. L. |last3=Gakidou |first3=Emmanuela |display-authors=1 |date=June 2008 |title=Fifty years of violent war deaths from Vietnam to Bosnia: analysis of data from the world health survey programme |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=336 |issue=7659 |pages=1482\u20131486 |doi=10.1136/bmj.a137 |pmid=18566045 |pmc=2440905}}</ref>\n\nKhan arrested Sheikh Mujibur Rahman on charges of [[sedition]] and appointed Brigadier [[Rahimuddin Khan]] (later General) to preside over a special tribunal dealing with Mujib's case. Rahimuddin awarded Mujib the [[death sentence]],{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} and President Yahya put the verdict into abeyance. Yahya's crackdown, however, had led to a [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] within Pakistan and India drew into the war and fought on behalf of Bangladeshis against Pakistan which would later extend in to the Indo Pak war of 1971.\n\nThe aftermaths of this war were mainly that East Pakistan became independent as Bangladesh and India captured approximately 15,000+ square kilometres (5,000+ square miles) of land of West Pakistan (now Pakistan). Though the captured territory of West Pakistan was given back to Pakistan in the Simla Agreement.\n\nThe war lead to increased tensions between the countries but nonthless Pakistan accepted the independence of Bangladesh. But this event led to high tensions between Pakistan and India.  \n\n<br />\n\n===US role===\n{{Main|Pakistan\u2013United States relations}}\n{{Unbalanced section|date=January 2014}}\nThe United States had been a major sponsor of President Yahya's military government. American journalist [[Gary J. Bass]] notes in ''[[The Blood Telegram: Nixon, Kissinger, and a Forgotten Genocide]]'', \"President Nixon liked very few people, but he did like General Yahya Khan.\"<ref>{{Harvnb|Bass|2013|p=7}}</ref> Personal initiatives of President Yahya had helped to establish the communication channel between the United States and [[People's Republic of China|China]], which would be used to set up the [[Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China|Nixon's trip]] in 1972.<ref>[http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB66/ Kissinger's Secret Trip to China]</ref>\n\nSince 1960, Pakistan was perceived in the United States as an integral bulwark against [[Global communist revolution|global]] [[Communism]] in the [[Cold War]]. The United States cautiously supported Pakistan during 1971 although [[United States Congress|Congress]] kept in place an arms embargo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asiaticsociety.org.bd/journals/Dec_2008/contents/ABMMoslehuddin.htm |title=Personal Prejudice Makes Foreign Policy |author=Mosleh Uddin |publisher=Asiaticsociety.org.bd |access-date=28 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706133004/http://www.asiaticsociety.org.bd/journals/Dec_2008/contents/ABMMoslehuddin.htm |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1970, India with a heavily [[Economy of India|socialist economy]] entered in [[Indo-Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Cooperation|a formal alliance]] with the Soviet Union in August 1971.\n\nNixon relayed several written and oral messages to President Yahya, strongly urging him to restrain the use of Pakistan forces.<ref>{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=751}}</ref> His objective was to prevent a war and safeguard Pakistan's interests, though he feared an Indian invasion of Pakistan that would lead to Indian domination of [[Indian subcontinent|the subcontinent]] and strengthen the position of the Soviet Union.<ref name=Time_19720117>{{cite magazine |title=The Kissinger Tilt |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,877618-2,00.html |url-access=subscription |magazine=Time |date=17 January 1972 |page=17 |access-date=30 September 2008}}</ref>  Similarly, President Yahya feared that an independent Bangladesh could lead to the disintegration of Pakistan. Indian [[Operation Jackpot|military support]] for Bengali guerrillas led to war between India and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=World: Pakistan: The Ravaging of Golden Bengal |url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,878408,00.html |magazine=Time |date=2 August 1971 |access-date=28 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Richard Nixon met Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]] and did not{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}} believe her assertion that she would not invade Pakistan;<ref>{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=752}}</ref> Nixon did not trust her and even once referred to her as an \"old bitch\".<ref>https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/indira-gandhi-is-a-bitch-the-indians-are-bastards/227789</ref> Witness accounts presented by Kissinger pointed out that Nixon made specific proposals to Prime Minister Gandhi on a solution for the crisis, some of which she heard for the first time, including a mutual withdrawal of troops from the [[Indo-Bangladeshi barrier|Indo-East Pakistan]] borders. Nixon also expressed a wish to fix a time limit with Yahya for political accommodation in East Pakistan. Nixon asserted that India could count on US endeavors to ease the crisis within a short time. But, both Kissinger and Gandhi's aide Jayakar maintained, Gandhi did not respond to these proposals. Kissinger noted that she \"listened to what was, in fact, one of Nixon's better presentations with aloof indifference\" but \"took up none of the points.\" Jayakar pointed out that Gandhi listened to Nixon \"without a single comment, creating an impregnable space so that no real contact was possible.\" She also refrained from assuring that India would follow Pakistan's suit if it withdrew from India's borders.  As a result, the main agenda was \"dropped altogether.\"<ref>Jayakar, Indira Gandhi, p. 232; Kissinger, White House Years, pp. 878 & 881\u201382.</ref>\n\nOn 3 December, Yahya preemptively attacked the Indian Air Force and Gandhi retaliated, pushing into East Pakistan.<ref name=\"cb753\">{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=753}}</ref> Nixon issued a statement blaming Pakistan for starting the conflict and blaming India for escalating it<ref name=\"cb753\"/> because he favored a cease-fire.<ref>{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=755}}</ref> The United States was secretly encouraging the shipment of military equipment from Iran, Turkey, and Jordan to Pakistan, reimbursing those countries<ref>{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=756}}</ref> despite Congressional objections.<ref name=NSA_Gandhi_20021216>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB79/ |title=The Tilt: The U.S. and the South Asian Crisis of 1971|work=National Security Archive Electronic Briefing Book No. 79 |date= 16 December 2002|first=Sajit|last=Gandhi|publisher=National Security Archive|accessdate=15 January 2009}}</ref>  The US used the threat of an aid cut-off to force Pakistan to back down, while its continued military aid to Islamabad prevented India from launching incursions deeper into the country.  Pakistan forces in East Pakistan surrendered on 16 December 1971, leading to the creation of the independent state of Bangladesh.<ref>{{Harvnb|Black|2007|p=757}}</ref>\n\n===Fall from power===\nWhen the news of [[Surrender of Pakistan|surrender]] of East Pakistan reached through the [[Pakistan Television Corporation|national television]], the spontaneous and overwhelming public anger over Pakistan's defeat by Bangladeshi rebels and the Indian Army, followed by the division of Pakistan into two parts boiled into street demonstrations throughout Pakistan. Rumors of an impending [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] by junior military officers against President Yahya swept the country. Yahya became the highest-ranking casualty of the war: to forestall further unrest, on 20 December 1971 he handed over the [[Pakistani presidency|presidency]] and [[Government of Pakistan|government]] to [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]]\u2014 the ambitious leader of Pakistan's powerful and popular (at that time) [[Pakistan Peoples Party|People's Party]].\n\nWithin hours of Yahya stepping down, President Bhutto reversed [[Judge Advocate General Branch (Pakistan)|JAG]]'s verdict against [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] and instead released him to see him off to London. President Bhutto also signed orders for Yahya's [[House arrest|house confinement]], the man who imprisoned Mujib in the first place. Both actions produced headlines around the world.\n\n==Death==\nYahya remained under house arrest orders until 1979 when he was released from the custody by [[Governor of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|martial law]] administrator General [[Fazle Haq]]. He remained out from public events and died on 10 August 1980 in [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Bass |first=Gary J. |year=2013 |title=The Blood Telegram: Nixon, Kissinger, and a Forgotten Genocide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9PnNZTp3BQYC&pg=PT28 |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |isbn=978-0-307-70020-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Black |first=Conrad |year=2008 |orig-year=First published 2007 |title=Richard M. Nixon: A Life in Full |publisher=PublicAffairs |location=New York |isbn=9781586486747 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|1}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Sharlach|first=Lisa|title=Rape as Genocide: Bangladesh, the Former Yugoslavia, and Rwanda|journal=New Political Science|year=2000|volume=1|issue=22|page=89|doi=10.1080/713687893|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sajjad|first=Tazreena|title=Plight and Fate of Women During and Following Genocide|year=2012|publisher=Transaction|isbn=978-1-4128-4759-9|pages=219\u2013248|edition=Reprint|editor=Samuel Totten|chapter=The Post-Genocidal Period and its Impact on Women|ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://pakistanarmy.gov.pk/AWPReview/TextContent.aspx?pId=148 Official profile at Pakistan Army website]\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878409,00.html?promoid=googlep Good Soldier Yahya Khan]----TIME\n* [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+pk0032) YAHYA KHAN AND BANGLADESH]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090402114442/http://therepublicofrumi.com/47.htm Chronicles Of Pakistan]\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB193/HAK%206-20-72.pdf Henry Kissinger and PM China discussed Yahya Khan and 1971 loss]\n* [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/96385676.html?dids=96385676:96385676&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=JAN+09%2C+1972&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=Yahya+Khan+Is+Arrested+In+Pakistan&pqatl=google Yahya Khan Is Arrested In Pakistan]----Washington Post\n* [http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,338612,00.html]----Spiegel Online\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sher Ali Khan Pataudi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of General Staff (Pakistan)|Chief of General Staff]